<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--O'KeeffeThieves     05-02 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--O'Keeffe Thieves,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Popular Art Show Prints Disappearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People have been stealing poster ads on
commuter-train platforms promoting an art exhibit of Georgia
O'Keeffe's work, authorities said.
   ``They keep bringing them in here, razor-bladed out,'' said
Larry Dilger, service director with Winston Network Inc., the
billboard company that installs the posters.
   ``People must find it very attractive if they will take the time
to cut the things out.''
   Posters of the painting ``Red Poppy'' have been displayed in
many parts of the city to advertise a showing of the late Ms.
O'Keeffe's work at the Art Institute of Chicago.
   At least 35 of 200 posters on rapid-transit platforms are
missing. When cut, only white borders and the words ``Georgia
O'Keeffe 1887-1986'' remain.
   Norman Baxter, a vice president of Southwestern Bell Corp.,
which is sponsoring the exhibit, said he considers the thefts a
form of flattery for the artist, who was known for her large and
precise designs of flowers and the skulls of animals.
</TEXT>
