<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MississippiWorkfare     05-02 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mississippi Workfare,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mississippi Welfare Officials Turn Workfare Jobs Into Paying
Employment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Welfare officials celebrating the first
anniversary of Mississippi's workfare program say they've shown
that even the nation's poorest state can take those who have never
had a steady job or who haven't worked in years off the dole.
   While Congress debated the most comprehensive welfare reform
bill in 50 years, Mississippi Department of Public Welfare
officials lauded their program for turning workfare jobs into
paying employment for 109 of the 765 food stamp recipients
participating so far.
   Welfare recipients, they said, may be pulling themselves up by
their own bootstraps largely because of the state's poverty.
   ``We're not distressed by the current economic situation. In
fact, I get a personal kick from trying to do more with less,''
Welfare Commissioner Thomas Brittain said.
   Mississippi has the lowest per capita income in the nation at
$10,204; 20 percent of its residents rely on food stamps.
   ``A lot of people, including some who work here in this
department, said workfare can't work in Mississippi,'' Brittain
recalled. ``The reasons they gave me for that is it's a rural-based
state, that we have high unemployment.''
   But Brittain said he knew workfare could work in Mississippi
because, although local governments and private non-profit groups
were short of revenue for needed services, there were ``tremendous
numbers of people on welfare who in my opinion were able to work.''
   Gloria Rutledge, a regional food program specialist in the U.S.
Department of Agriculture's Atlanta office, agreed that
Mississippi's poverty has contributed to its workfare success.
   ``I don't know that this would have worked so well in some other
place,'' Rutledge said of the program, which requires clients to
work for government the number of hours times the minimum wage that
equals the value of their food stamp allotment.
   She said because so many Mississippi agencies can't afford to
hire people to perform necessary tasks they'll give workfare
participants doing those jobs more responsibility and training than
they would otherwise.
   She also noted that Mississippi workfare participants can more
easily be recommended to private industry as solid, proven
employees because they work an average of six months before
Brittain personally presents their resumes at a meeting of local
business owners and managers in their community.
   Rutledge said that with 16 counties participating so far,
Mississippi probably has the largest-scale food stamp workfare
program in the Southeast. Brittain said he hopes to include all of
the state's 82 counties within a few years.
   Each county's board of supervisors must opt to join
Mississippi's version of the federally authorized program.
Participating counties pay $12.50 monthly to cover each workfare
client's travel and other miscellaneous expenses, with the federal
government matching that amount.
   Food stamp recipients in participating counties must sign up for
workfare, Job Find or educational programs. In the past year, 1,972
of 5,448 clients in the participating counties opted to discontinue
receiving food stamps rather than meet the requirements of one of
the three options.
   Forty-four states have a workfare program tied to the Aid to
Families with Dependent Children program, according to federal
officials in Washington.
   Among the workfare success stories provided by Brittain is the
case of Cecil Walker, a longtime unemployed off-shore oilfield
worker. Walker began his workfare assignment as a novice in the
Welfare Department's printing office. His workfare training later
allowed him to select from among several print shop job offers _ at
what he said is a livable salary.
   ``It's something when your children say, `I want this and I want
that, Daddy,''' Walker said. ``Now, I can't get everything they
want, but I get everything they need and some of the things they
want.''
</TEXT>
