<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TestBanTest     05-02 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Test Ban Test,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Scientists Leave U.S. Assured Test Ban Treaty Is
Cheat-Proof</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet scientists toasted their U.S.
colleagues and then headed home after recording simulated low-yield
nuclear bomb blasts that both sides said showed cheating on a test
ban treaty could be detected.
   The successful weekend experiments in the Nevada desert and
similar ones last September in the Soviet Union used delicate
seismographs to detect minuscule shock waves from the explosions of
10- and 15-ton charges of dynamite, a fraction of the strength of
most nuclear weapons tests, from as far as 400 miles away.
   The experiments are expected to show that ``any chances for
cheating are about excluded'' under a test ban, Evgeni Velikhov,
vice president of the Soviet Academy and an adviser to Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev, said Sunday.
   After seismometers detected the first detonation of 10 tons of
TNT on Friday, Charles Archambeau, a University of Colorado-Boulder
geophysics professor, said the experiments mean ``that we can more
accurately gauge the numbers and distribution of stations that will
be required to verify a low-threshold treaty.''
   Velikhov, wearing a sweatshirt that said, ``Arms are for Hugs,''
called a comprehensive test ban ``very important. It is extremely
important to stop the arms race.''
   The Soviets offered toast with vodka and beer on May Day, a
communist holiday.
   Scientists said they would turn to learning how to determine the
difference between nuclear weapons detonations and industrial
explosions by conducting more tests.
   Archambeau, head of the National Resources Defense Council's
seismic monitoring advisory committee, said he hoped both
governments would sponsor further experiments.
   The multimillion-dollar experiments in this country and in the
Soviet Union were conducted by the council, a private group, and by
the Soviet Academy of Sciences.
   Archambeau and other scientists in the project had been
concerned that after the success of last year's research near the
Soviet test site, efforts here might be thwarted by Nevada's
fault-riddled geology, which soaks up sound waves. He said he was
relieved by the success of Saturday's final test.
   ``This is quite a strong signal. It's highly valuable,'' he said
after a 15-ton explosion 100 miles east of Carson City on Saturday
sent seismic needles quivering at the joint U.S.-Soviet monitoring
station in Deep Springs, Calif., 210 miles away.
   On Friday, 10 tons of TNT were detonated beneath the desert 100
miles north of Reno and another 10-ton shot was set off 50 miles
south of the Nevada Test Site.
   They were monitored at the joint station in Deep Springs, midway
between Reno and Las Vegas, and at two permanent Defense Council
installations closer to the Test Site 110 miles north of Las Vegas,
where all U.S. underground nuclear detonations are conducted. One
hundred forty additional temporary monitoring stations were set up
across Nevada.
   Friday's first test barely moved the seismometers at Deep
Springs and the second was not detected, but both showed up on more
sensitive digital instruments, said Holly Eissler, research
geophysicist at the University of California, San Diego.
   She noted that a limited nuclear test ban treaty passed by the
House last week forbids detonations larger than one kiloton, 100
times stronger than the 10-ton TNT blast.
   Thomas Cochran, senior staff scientist for the Defense Council
and a co-director of the test ban verification project, said the
council had spent about $3.5 million on the effort since it began
two years ago. He estimated the U.S. group's share of the weekend's
testing at about $300,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
