<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Korea-Strike     05-02 0129</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Korea-Strike,0132</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea's No. 2 Car Plant Opens After 19-Day Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's second largest automaker
today resumed operations after a 19-day strike in which workers won
a nearly 20 percent increase in their salaries.
   The automaker, Daewoo Motor Co., is a 50-50 joint venture with
General Motors Corp. of the United States.
   Daewoo's 6,000 employees returned to work after accepting an
11-point settlement that gave them, among other things, a
19.6-percent pay increase and some additional fringe benefits,
company officials said.
   They said the settlement increased the workers' monthly average
salary to $565, including fringe benefits. Daewoo's assembly line
workers went on strike April 12 and to demand a 26.6-percent pay
increase.
   Daewoo reached agreement with labor leaders over the weekend.
</TEXT>
