<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     05-02 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELINSGROVE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stakes in world-champion
banana-split making got a bit higher _ er, longer _ thanks to the
determined residents of this central Pennsylvania town.
   Using 33,000 bananas, 2,500 gallons of ice cream and 150 gallons
of chocolate syrup, Selinsgrove made a 4.5-mile-long banana split
Saturday in a bid to regain a place in the Guinness Book of World
Records.
   ``It's something for the town to say, `When we work together,
anything is possible,''' said Kelly Stoops, a Selinsgrove teacher
who organized the event to raise money for a community development
organization.
   About 24,000 people standing and sitting in front of one-foot
sections of the 12.6 million-calorie dessert dug in at 4:30 p.m.
Each paid $2 for the privilege.
   ``It was getting pretty soupy after a while,'' said Robert Linn
of New Berlin, who was standing near the middle of the giant split,
made in three sections up Market Street through the center of this
town of 5,500 residents.
   Selinsgrove set the record for the world's longest banana spilt
in 1982 with a 1.5-mile concoction, winning a place in the 1983
Guinness Book.
   But in 1983, New York high school students created a banana
split a tenth of a mile longer.
   Selinsgrove on Saturday outdid Zeta Beta Tau Sorority at Bowling
Green University in Ohio, which created a 4-mile banana split in
1985, organizers said.
   A surveying company would verify the length of the banana split
and send the results to Guinness.
   Six hundred captains each produced 40-foot sections of the
dessert, made in a cardboard trough from empty carpet rolls.
   In addition to the ice cream, bananas and chocolate sauce,
organizers sprinkled on 600 pounds of chopped nuts, 150 gallons
each of strawberries and pineapples and 24,000 cherries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If all the quarters given away to
casino customers here last year were combined in one roll, the
package would stretch from Atlantic City to the outskirts of St.
Louis, more than 917 miles.
   Customers received more than $218.4 million, or 10.9 million
pounds, in complimentary quarters last year just for walking in the
doors of the city's 12 casinos, according to financial reports the
gaming halls filed with the state Casino Control Commission.
   That translates into more than 873.6 million quarters _ more
quarters than the U.S. Mint made in 1978, the year the first casino
opened here.
   ``No wonder we can't get change people,'' one casino official,
speaking on condition of anonymity, quipped, referring to the
industry's difficulty in finding enough workers to sell coins on
casino floors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLLINSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They tasted, tossed, and generally
touted horseradish at an outdoor bash in this Southern Illinois
community to honor the tangy root.
   ``We grow one-half to two-thirds of the world's crop in this
area. We think that's something,'' said Craig Keller, president of
the Tri-County Vegetable Growers Association, which sponsored the
first International Horseradish Festival on Saturday to promote
Madison County as the horseradish capital of the world.
   Both horseradish connoisseurs and novices strolled past the food
booths and displays in a Collinsville park.
   ``I love horseradish,'' said Melvin Lytle, 67, of Edwardsville.
``It clears the sinuses. And they say it's an aphrodisiac.''
   ``Honey and horseradish makes a good cough medicine,'' added his
wife, Helen, 66.
   In addition to tasting recipes made with horseradish, some
people participated in the Horseradish Olympics _ which included a
root toss, where contestants tried to lob foot-long horseradish
roots farther than anyone else, and a hot dog eating contest. The
dogs, of course, were slathered with horseradish.
</TEXT>
