<DOCNO> AP880502-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 0110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-LaRoucheCandidate     05-02 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche Candidate,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaRouche Victory In Pa. Congressional Primary Stuns Democrats</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-LaRouche Chairman, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAN GEHORSAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party officials in suburban
Philadelphia's 5th Congressional District are stuck with a
candidate they don't want: a backer of political extremist Lyndon
LaRouche.
   One official said party leaders were focusing on other campaigns
when LaRouche backer Donald Hadley defeated Robert W. Houchins, a
little-known candidate endorsed by the party, in Tuesday's
congressional primary.
   Hadley, a sales representative from Drexel Hill, will face Rep.
Richard Schulze, a well-financed Republican, in November's election.
   Houchins has blamed his loss on the Democratic organization in
Montgomery, Chester and Delaware counties, which make up the
district, and on voters, whom he accused of ignorance.
   ``Charles Manson could run for office and get elected,'' he said
Friday.
   ``The county committees did not take LaRouche seriously, the
area leaders did not take him seriously and the committee people
did not take him seriously. ... So ultimately the voter didn't take
the LaRouche threat seriously.''
   Party leaders agreed.
   ``Of course, it's our party's responsibility and obviously we
failed,'' said Delaware County Democratic Committee Chairwoman
Dianne Merlino. ``We should have exercised our maximum effort to
promote Houchins.''
   On Friday, Montgomery County Democratic Chairman Philip Berg
called for Hadley to step down to let a ``legitimate candidate
run.''
   Berg said he would rather see Schulze win. ``It would be better
than having a LaRouchian,'' he said.
   LaRouche, a perennial presidential candidate, has promoted a
quarantine of AIDS victims and the colonization of Mars, and has
charged that Queen Elizabeth II of England is a drug dealer.
   He is on trial in Boston with six aides and five of his
political groups on charges they conspired to obstruct a federal
grand jury investigation. The grand jury was probing allegations
that more than $1 million was raised for LaRouche's 1984
presidential campaign through credit card and loan fraud
   In an interview with the Delaware County Times, Hadley said he
openly identified himself with LaRouche and won the election
because of voters' dissatisfaction with mainstream Democratic
candidates.
   But Berg and other Democrats contend that Hadley concealed the
affiliation.
   ``I don't believe there was anything indicating he was a
LaRouchian published by him. I think he was more surprised than
other people that he even won,'' Berg said. ``No one could even get
a hold of him. I never saw him, I never met him, he was never at
any meetings held by the Montgomery County Democratic Committee. I
never received one phone call from him, not one piece of literature
from him.''
   Hadley said he was in the streets daily ``talking face-to-face
with people, talking about why they're trying to railroad LaRouche,
why they're trying to keep him out of politics.''
   ``I told them what we've got to do to get the economy in shape.
... That's what people are interested in.''
   Ms. Merlino said Hadley won because he was first on the ballot,
the candidates' names were similar and the victor made
misrepresentations.
   ``I didn't think the problem would be so big that we couldn't
overcome it in Delaware County,'' she said. ``I should have done
more. I should have been more aware.''
   Delaware County was the only one of the three that carried
Houchins. Overall, Hadley had 10,667 votes, or 53 percent, and
Houchins had 9,298 votes, or 47 percent, with 99 percent of the
vote counted.
   Democrats in the Republican stronghold were busy backing
candidates in other races, Ms. Merlino said.
   Berg and Ms. Merlino said their committees will not back him.
State party Chairman Larry Yatch said he and his aides are studying
what measures to take in the election.
   Dana Scanlon, a spokeswoman for the LaRouche for President
campaign, said Hadley is unlikely to receive much funding but will
get help from LaRouche supporters.
</TEXT>
