<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson Bjt   05-02 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson: Campaign a Success, With or Without Nomination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson gazed from a balcony over the
sunny, riverfront lawn party where a well-dressed crowd sipped wine.
   ``No one ever told us it was going to be easy,'' Jackson shouted
to the 300 partygoers.
   But the candidate wanted his predominately black audience to
remember something: ``When you consider what we came from, we don't
have the ability to get tired.
   ``This is not just Iowa to Atlanta. This is from the back of the
bus in Montgomery to being within one of three to being the next
president.''
   It is a theme that has become increasingly prominent for Jackson
in recent days after his heavy losses in the Pennsylvania and New
York primaries.
   He is sounding a twofold message as he trails Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis down the home stretch of the primary season:
   First, he vows to fight on to win the nomination and raise
issues. But second, Jackson highlights the historic aspect of his
candidacy, casting it in terms that spell victory whether he wins
or loses the nomination.
   In the face of a new poll showing Dukakis with a 40-point lead
in Ohio, whose primary is Tuesday, Jackson appeared to be dwelling
increasingly on this over the weekend.
   By pointing to his unquestioned successes and the wide
acceptance his candidacy has received, Jackson paints his effort as
an outgrowth of the civil rights struggles of the 1960s and another
step on the road to full equality for blacks.
   He contrasts his bid for the White House with the grim days more
than two decades ago when people died fighting for just the right
to vote.
   So as he campaigns across Ohio, he tells church crowds and
rallies that his candidacy is far more than a journey from the Iowa
caucuses in February to this summer's Democratic convention in
Atlanta.
   It's a journey that began when blacks began rebelling in
Montgomery, Ala., against being forced to ride in the back of the
bus, he said.
   And it's a mission that must be carried forward by people like
the well-heeled crowd at the estate of physician Alfred Jefferson
in this Columbus suburb, he told them.
   He said reporters are asking him after his string of losses,
``How can you go on?''
   Jackson's answer: ``Do you know how far we've come? ... We're
almost to the top of the hill. We've come too far. We must press
forward.''
   The crowd laughed with acknowledgement when he pointed to the
strides they have made financially, saying, ``Most of us standing
here today are one generation out of chitlins.''
   To dramatize his point, Jackson related as he often does the
story of his humble South Carolina beginnings _ born to a teenage
mother and the married man next door, living in a house with
wallpaper for warmth not decoration, waiting to eat Thanksgiving
dinner until his mother came home with leftovers from the table of
the white people whose meal she had prepared.
   Jackson sometimes seems amazed himself as he tells the story.
   ``When I win, there are no more impossible dreams,'' he often
says.
   But in keeping with his portrayal of his candidacy as part of a
historical continuum, he told his Dublin audience that he expects
them to carry on the movement. He said they must ``translate this
movement'' into demands for blacks in positions of authority at
banks and universities and corporations where there are still
barriers, as well as in government.
   ``When I shake apples from the tree, you must pick up these
apples and make them into jelly and take them to the market,'' he
said.
   ``To have continuity in our struggle we must establish a
heritage of success in the government for all coming generations.''
</TEXT>
