<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-HerbigResigns     05-02 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Herbig Resigns,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detroit Symphony Orchestra Conductor Quits, Cites Contract
Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunther Herbig said he planned to resign as
conductor of the Detroit Symphony Orchestra because of numerous
violations of his contract, a newspaper reported today.
   Herbig, the orchestra's conductor since 1984, told musicians
about his plans during intermission of Saturday night's concert. On
Sunday, he declined to discuss his resignation, effective when his
contract expires in 1990, The Detroit News said.
   Several musicians told newspaper that Herbig cited several
complaints, many of them related to the orchestra's financial
troubles.
   Among Herbig's complaints, they said, were cancellation of a
1989-90 tour of the Far East; refusal to guarantee frequent
domestic tours; reduction of the number of guaranteed musicians
from 103 to 97; and refusal to promise the orchestra will move in
1989-90 from Ford Auditorium to Orchestra Hall.
   ``Herbig told us that virtually the only thing they honored in
the contract was payment, and that even that was sometimes late,''
said Maxim Janowsky, a DSO bassist.
   Orchestra board Chairman Walter J. McCarthy Jr. said in a
statement Sunday that the orchestra's financial troubles caused the
board to fail to meet some terms of Herbig's contract.
   But it was the board's ``intention and hope to honor Maestro
Herbig's contract in every detail,'' the statement said.
   Herbig said he would complete a second three-year term under a
contract he signed in 1987, leaving 28 months to work with
management in finding a replacement.
   The orchestra in November, while musicians were in the midst of
a 12-week work stoppage, announced a deficit of $1.4 million for
the 1986-87 season, raising its cumulative deficit to $4.1 million
against an annual budget of $14 million.
   A deficit reduction campaign has been launched. But The News,
citing an unidentified source close to the orchestra, said
musicians were told last week an additional deficit of $400,000 was
anticipated for this season.
</TEXT>
