<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DunneAllegations     05-02 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dunne Allegations,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cook County Board President Denies Jobs-for-Sex Allegation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 75-year-old president of the Cook County
Board denied allegations he traded patronage jobs for sexual
favors, saying he was guilty of nothing more than poor judgment and
having sex that ``hurt no one.''
   George Dunne, who is also chairman of the powerful county
Democratic Party, read a short statement at a news conference
Sunday, then got into a shouting match with a reporter, went to his
office and locked the door.
   In his statement, Dunne called the allegations ``repulsive'' and
said they were an attempt to smear a reputation built in 35 years
in public office.
   He said the allegations raised by the Better Government
Association, a private watchdog group, and Chicago television
station WMAQ, ``wrongfully portray me as some sort of perverted old
man.''
   The association contends that Dunne engaged in three-way sex and
strip poker with various pairs of four lesbian women at his farm
near Hebron between 1980, the year his wife died, and 1986.
   While Dunne acknowledges having sex with two women he later
hired, he said his actions ``were not sordid, filthy or illegal.''
   In his latest denial of the accusations, Dunne said he was
guilty of nothing except ``extremely poor judgment'' and ``having
relationships with the opposite sex, which hurt no one.''
   Dunne, president of the county's governing board for 19 years,
rejected the association's call that he resign.
   ``There is nothing that I have done over those years that has
violated the public trust in me,'' he said.
   He refused to say whether it was appropriate to hire women after
having sex with them, and told a WMAQ reporter who repeatedly asked
that question, ``You're the scum of the earth and so is the BGA.''
   BGA Executive Director J. Terrence Brunner has admitted that
``as far as we know,'' Dunne did not make sex a condition for
hiring the women.
   ``Within two weeks in two instances, the people are on the
public payroll,'' Brunner said Sunday. ``To me, that's an obvious
link. There's no doubt about it.''
   Three of the women Dunne allegedly had sex with are on the Cook
County payroll and one used to be, the Chicago Tribune reported
Sunday.
   The BGA says one of the women who had sex with Dunne has been an
officer with the county Forest Preserve police since 1984, and
another was hired by the preserve as a laborer in 1980.
   Don Rose, a former political aide to Mayors Harold Washington
and Jane Byrne, said he doubts Dunne broke any laws.
   ``It's clear that he simply used his immense hiring powers ...
in effect to pass out favors to friends,'' Rose said. ``That's not
illegal ... but it is exemplary of really terrible abuse of the
patronage system.
   ``This is the kind of scandal that has brought down
governments,'' he said. ``However, Chicago being what it is, you
find more people on the street commenting on his virility at age 75
than whether or not this was a heinous act.''
</TEXT>
