<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 0226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OverseasVoters     05-02 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Overseas Voters,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters Overseas to Get Blank Ballots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ballots without the names of specific
candidates will be available for the first time to an estimated 3
million Americans in other countries who are eligible to vote on
Nov. 8 for the next president.
   The new, fill-in-the-blank ballots are for people who may not be
able to get a regular absentee ballot submitted in time _ from a
remote mission in Africa, for example, or a submarine at sea for
months. But mostly they are for the victims of slow mail deliveries.
   Henry Valentino, head of the Federal Voting Assistance Program
Office, said a million of these write-in ballots will be sent in
July to all U.S. embassies and consulates and to the voting
officers attached to each military unit overseas. The object is to
increase the number of Americans who vote, even if they are
working, traveling or living abroad.
   Canada and Mexico have the largest number of such civilians. The
biggest numbers of military are in West Germany, Japan and South
Korea.
   Valentino estimates that in the 1984 election, about 55 percent
of the overseas military and 35 percent of civilians cast ballots.
For civilians, that was much lower than the national average of
53.1 percent.
   He also estimates on the basis of polls that 8.5 percent _
roughly 250,000 _ tried to vote but failed to get in a regular
absentee ballot and have it counted by voting authorities at home.
There were many causes, including failure to write the proper
office in time, failure of local authorities to mail the ballot in
time, failure of the voter to mail it back, or failure of local
deliveries abroad.
   Absentee ballots that arrive too late are not counted.
   ``We just got a court order Monday to make election officials in
Pennsylvania count absentee ballots received up to 10 days after
the April 26 primary,'' Valentino said in an interview.
   ``Most Pennsylvania election officials began mailing their
absentee ballots only two weeks before the election.''
   One reason for slow mailing by local authorities is that they
have to wait until candidates are named before they can start
printing.
   The blank absentee ballots will be usable only for federal
positions in the general election on Nov. 8. The voter must first
write for a regular absentee ballot from his or her district at
home, getting the application in at least 30 days before Election
Day.
   If the absentee ballot does not reach the voter in time, he or
she can write in the name of a choice for president, for senator if
there is a senatorial election in the state and for a member of the
House of Representatives.
   The names of political parties can be written instead, and such
tickets may be split.
   ``You can write the name of one party as your choice for
president and another party for the senator, if you don't write
individual names,'' Valentino explained.
   State authorities will have to count the write-in ballot as they
do regular absentee ballots.
   The write-ins are not to be used or distributed within the
United States, including Puerto Rico, Guam, the Virgin Islands and
American Samoa. But they will be sent to units deploying to
overseas assignments and to ships and submarines expected to be at
sea on Election Day.
</TEXT>
