<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CongressionalMoney     05-02 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congressional Money,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PAC Contributions to House, Senate Races Up A Quarter in Two Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Special interest groups have supplied $53
million to congressional candidates in the last 15 months, with the
chairman of the tax-writing Senate Finance Committee making the
biggest haul.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, who faces a challenge this fall
from Republican Rep. Beau Boulter, led the list of recipients of
political action committee money with $1.4 million.
   Bentsen also ranked as the largest overall fund-raiser among
candidates so far, with just over $5 million by March 31, compared
with Boulter's $365,000.
   The figures were released Sunday by the Federal Election
Commission, which said congressional candidates raised $180 million
overall in the first 15 months of the two-year cycle that
culminates with November's elections.
   Of that, it said, $53 million _ or 29 percent _ came from the
special-interest groups known as PACs.
   At the comparable time in 1986, House and Senate contenders had
raised $167 million, of which $41 million was in PAC money, a 24
percent share.
   The growing clout of special interests in congressional
elections has prompted Senate critics to seek voluntary restraints
on the amount of such money that can be spent by Senate candidates.
The Democratic push has been stymied by Republican filibusters.
   Overall, the 143 candidates for Senate seats raised $79 million
during the 15-month period, about $1 million less than at the
comparable time two years ago. The decrease was due in part to a
smaller number of candidates than in 1986.
   The 1,201 candidates for House seats had pulled in $101 million
as of March 31, a $14 million increase. The jump came in part
because 17 more incumbents are seeking re-election than two years
ago.
   Aside from Texas, Senate races in two other populous states _
California and Ohio _ also ranked high on the money lists.
   Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., ranked second behind Bentsen in
overall fund raising, with more than $4 million collected toward
his contest with challenger Leo T. McCarthy, the Democratic
California lieutenant governor. McCarthy's receipts totaled $2.4
million.
   In Ohio, incumbent Sen. Howard Metzenbaum ranked third in fund
raising at $3.7 million, while his opponent, Republican Cleveland
Mayor George Voinovich, had raised $2.5 million.
   Among House races, the leader was Rep. Joseph DioGuardi, R-N.Y.,
who is trying to hold onto the traditionally Democratic seat he has
held for two terms. He raised $800,000 during the first 15 months
of the election season.
   Close behind were Reps. Mel Levine, D-Calif., with $750,000, and
Joseph Kennedy, D-Mass., with $706,000.
   Top recipients of PAC money among House members were Budget
Committee Chairman William Gray, D-Pa., with $267,000, and Mary
Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, with $257,000. Also ranking high on that list
was Energy and Commerce Committee Chairman John Dingell, D-Mich.,
with nearly $257,000 in special-interest money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
