<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Paraguay-Prisoner Bjt   05-02 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Paraguay-Prisoner, Bjt,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colombia And Paraguay Reach Stalemate Over Former Prisoner</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four months after he completed a
25-year prison term, Modesto Napoleon Ortigoza has yet to taste
freedom.
   The former army captain was convicted of killing a cadet in 1962
who allegedly learned of his involvement in a plot to overthrow
President Alfredo Stroessner, the Western Hemisphere's
longest-reigning leader.
   Ortigoza, 56, said in an interview in March that he was never
allowed to appear in court to plead his innocence and that his
confession was extracted by torture, including electric shocks on a
grill.
   ``When you are defenseless under the torturers, 10 in my case,
you give in and say what they want you to,'' Ortigoza told the AP.
   Ortigoza was released from prison on Dec. 20 but was put under
police custody in the town of San Estanislao, 85 miles northeast of
Asuncion.
   He was brought to Asuncion in February, where two
round-the-clock guards prevented him from leaving the home of his
invalid mother. The government said without elaboration that the
guards were protecting Ortigoza.
   He escaped March 25 with the help of an opposition leader. Both
fled one block to the residence of Colombian Ambassador Vicente
Martinez Emiliani.
   Colombia granted both political asylum but the Paraguayan
government has refused to act on Colombia's request for
safe-conduct passage out of the country for Ortigoza and the
dissident, Hermes Rafael Saguier. Emiliani recently said he has had
``no news'' on the pending requests for safe passage.
   Interior Minister Sabino Montanaro says his country is in no
rush to grant Ortigoza safe passage, calling him a ``common
criminal.''
   Government officials have branded Saguier, 40, a subversive and
compared Ortigoza's escape to the embassy ``a terrorist action.''
   Foreign Minister Carlos Augusto Saldivar declined to say when
the government would respond to Ortigoza's request for safe passage.
   ``It looks like it will be one of those things that will go on
and on and on indefinitely,'' said a European diplomatic who has
followed the situation closely. The diplomat spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Neither Ortigoza nor Saguier are allowed to speak to reporters
or to leave the ambassador's residence. Their lawyers, family and
close friends are the only ones permitted to visit.
   Paraguay's Human Rights Commission says Ortigoza's treatment is
meant to be a lesson to those who would conspire against
Stroessner, in power since 1954.
   Ortigoza's lawyer, Digno Britez, says the May 16-18 visit to
Paraguay by Pope John Paul II and Stroessner's trip to the United
Nations in June could help Ortigoza and Saguier gain safe passage
out of Paraguay.
   ``Stroessner would not want something like that to be brought up
while he visits the United Nations,'' Britez said, adding: ``Our
government is not a democracy so the consequences were pretty
predictable from the start.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 0319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-OPEC-Notebook     05-02 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OPEC-Notebook,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Talks: Fasting, Jet Lag And `Near Non-OPEC Members'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some wondered what it would be like if
OPEC leaders met during Ramadan, the traditional Moslem month of
fasting that began April 18. Now we have the answer: grueling.
   Because some of the 13 delegations are mainly or exclusively
Christian, part of the cartel's oil negotiations took place during
the day. That's the normal time for OPEC business.
   But because the Moslem members prefer to slow down during their
sunrise-to-sunset fast, the formal OPEC sessions started late at
night, after the Moslems had eaten their ``breakfast.''
   As a result, some of the oil debate was in progress almost
around the clock.
   The non-Moslem oil ministers found it hard to cope with the
schedule, which forced them to try to sleep part of the day.
   One said he was taking pills to stay awake during the nighttime
sessions.
   Some said they felt as though they had been hit with jet lag,
minus the travel.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Often it's hard to understand why OPEC leaders have so much
trouble settling their differences over oil policy.
   Once in a while it's easy. Consider a comment by Ali Khalifa
Sabah, the Kuwaiti oil minister, to reporters who asked whether he
was ready to give up his minority opposition to an OPEC plan:
   ``I usually am very reasonable and willing to discuss anything,
once our point of view has been accepted.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Another clue to why OPEC's meetings often last longer than would
seem necessary:
   ``We know that some (delegates) like to be out of our respective
countries,'' said an official from an African OPEC member. ``A
weekend in Europe _ not bad.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   It's getting harder to classify the players in the international
oil game.
   Time was, and not long ago, you had two types: those in OPEC and
those outside it.
   At the latest OPEC conference the distinctions were a little
less clear.
   You had the usual 13 OPEC members. But you also had something
called ``non-OPEC,'' an unofficial association of six independent
oil-producing nations, including Mexico and China, that wants to
establish formal ties to the cartel without becoming members.
   Then you had three other oil producers _ Norway, the Canadian
province of Alberta and the state of Texas _ who wanted to rub
elbows with the OPEC leaders but still keep enough distance to
stand outside the ``non-OPEC'' camp.
   Some called these three ``near non-OPEC.''
   And then there are the rest, producers such as the Soviet Union
and Britain that want to have nothing to do with the cartel.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Kent Hance, a member of the Texas Railroad Commission that
regulates the state's oil industry, met several staffers at OPEC
headquarters last week, including the deputy secretary general,
Fadhil Chalabi.
   He said he found them knowledgeable about oil but also very
cautious.
   ``I guess I would be, too, if I had 13 bosses,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Rilwanu Lukman, a Nigerian, is the top OPEC boss, at least in
title. He is president of the formal conferences and the highest
ranking spokesman for the cartel.
   At the end of the latest meeting Lukman lashed out at the news
media, accusing it of trying to stampede OPEC into making decisions.
   ``Why should we make a decision just because you say we
should?'' he said in a high-pitched tone to one reporter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
