<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--HeadlessMascot     05-02 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Headless Mascot,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Badger Mascot Loses Head At Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bucky Badger, the University of Wisconsin
mascot, lost his head, but officials say the costumed figure will
be back in action with a new one soon.
   The 4-foot-diameter, 19-pound head was stolen during an
off-campus party Friday, authorities said.
   Gavin Taylor, 21, one of four Buckys, said he had the costume at
his apartment in preparation for an appearance at the 14th annual
Midwest Rowing Championships at Lake Wingra on Saturday.
   Taylor said he left the party for a while and returned to find
someone had stolen the head.
   ``I couldn't just put the clothes on and pass as Bucky,'' he
said.
   The head is one of two used by the university and Bucky was
expected back in action soon, Taylor said.
   The heads are constructed out of fiberglass by fencing coach
John Gillham, who estimated the cost of each complete suit at $500.
</TEXT>
