<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-StrikeScene     05-02 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Strike Scene,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Strikers and Families Embrace at Plant Gate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the strike at the Lenin steelworks
entered its sixth day, 120 haggard workers appeared at the
facility's gate to receive flowers, food and words of support from
tearful family members.
   Most of the 50 wives, children and parents of the striking
workers remained outside the partially opened gate on Sunday, but a
some weeping wives stepped a few feet inside to embrace their
husbands.
   ``I know that my voice is breaking,'' strike leader Andrezej
Szewczuwaniec told the group. ``But I'm very moved. There is lot of
optimism in me because there is only one Polish heart, and it
cannot be split.''
   He told the families that the strike, which began Tuesday for
higher pay and union recognition, would continue today.
   ``We will not disappoint our wives, our sons, our mothers nor
you behind the gate,'' he said. When he stopped speaking, the crowd
began chanting, ``God bless you! God bless you!''
   The family members passed plastic bags of food and bunches of
flowers through the gate to the strikers, and the group sang
patriotic hymns from both sides of the fence.
   Earlier in the day, police had stopped some people from marching
to the plant. But police were nowhere around the main plant gates
at midafternoon, when the family members began arriving on foot or
by public transportation.
   The families offered words of support: ``We are with you. ... We
support you. ... Long live the mill.''
   ``We are all moved here,'' said another member of the strike
committee, Stanislaw Handzlik. ``Here we are seven years after
martial law and again we raise our hands, we raise our heads, we
raise our backs.
   ``We want to demand human and social rights that we deserve. We
want to assure you that we will go on with the strike.''
   After the speeches, the workers said ``Do widzenia'' _ ``Until
we see you again'' _ and marched back inside the plant.
</TEXT>
