<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     05-02 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Has No Taste For `Ribbon-Cuttings and Funerals' As VP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARBONDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon, who suspended his
Democratic presidential run last month, says he has no interest in
joining the national ticket as a vice presidential candidate.
   The Illinois Democrat said Sunday his lack of interest in the
No. 2 spot hasn't changed since his campaign was all but called off.
   ``In politics, you never say never,'' he told reporters. ``But
frankly, I doubt if I'd be interested even in the unlikely chance I
were asked.''
   Simon also said he thinks former Vice President Walter Mondale
wishes that he had stayed in the Senate instead of becoming
President Jimmy Carter's running mate in 1976.
   ``It's mainly a ceremonial thing, a lot of ribbon-cuttings and
funerals,'' Simon said. ``My interest in politics is policy making.
I'd sooner leave the ceremony to someone else.''
   Simon also said he has no intention of formally dropping out of
the race and releasing his 170 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention, including 137 from Illinois.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Sununu Will Be Bush's Spokesman On Convention Platform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. John Sununu, who ran George Bush's
successful New Hampshire campaign, will be the vice president's
spokesman during the drafting of the Republican platform at the
convention, a Bush campaign official said.
   Sununu was chairman of the Bush effort in New Hampshire that set
the vice president back on the road to the nomination after he had
lost to Sen. Bob Dole in the Iowa caucuses a week earlier.
   As ``official spokesman'' for Bush, Sununu will be his most
visible representative when the platform committee drafts the
party's statements on issues at the convention in New Orleans this
August.
   Bush's New England support, along with Sununu, included Gov.
John McKernan of Maine and Gov. Edward DiPrete of Rhode Island. The
latter two have not been offered jobs at the convention, Ron
Kaufman, Bush's Northeast political director, told the Boston
Sunday Globe.
</TEXT>
