<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CyanideDeaths     05-02 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyanide Deaths,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Closing Arguments In Cyanide Poisoning Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Closing arguments scheduled to begin at 12:30 p.m. EDT; lead
prospects doubtful.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal trial of a woman accused of killing
her husband and another woman with cyanide-laced Excedrin, the
nation's first murder-by-product-tampering case, is nearing its end.
   The jury in the trial of Stella Nickell, 44, was to hear closing
arguments today, then be charged by U.S. District Judge William
Dwyer before beginning its deliberations.
   If convicted, Mrs. Nickell could be sentenced to life in prison.
   She is accused of five instances of tampering with
over-the-counter medicine, including the two cases involving death.
She has denied any involvement in the deaths.
   According to prosecutors, Mrs. Nickell, unhappy in her marriage
and frustrated by more than $8,500 in debts, plotted the June 1986
death of Bruce Nickell, 52, to collect $176,000 in life insurance
benefits. They also said she placed other tainted pain-relievers on
the shelves of area drugstores to make the poisoning appear random.
   Sue Katherine Snow, 40, of Auburn, died two weeks after Nickell.
She swallowed poisoned Excedrin capsules, authorities said. The
Nickells apparently didn't know Ms. Snow.
   In sometimes tearful testimony Wednesday and Thursday, Mrs.
Nickell denied killing her husband of 12 years or knowing he had
more than $25,000 in life insurance.
   She said she did library research in 1983 and 1984 on poisonous
plants, including some containing cyanide, to protect children from
dangerous foliage on their rural property.
   Mrs. Nickell denied testimony by her 28-year-old daughter, Cindy
Hamilton, who said her mother had contemplated killing Nickell for
some time. Mrs. Nickell also denied testimony from another relative
who she had talked about reaping ``close to 200 grand'' in life
insurance benefits.
   Mrs. Nickell admitted that in the spring of 1986, she and her
sporadically-employed husband owed more than $8,500.
   But she insisted there was nothing macabre about the letters she
wrote to one bank shortly before Nickell's death indicating that
her ``marriage problems'' were almost over and that payments would
stay current.
   A prosecution rebuttal witness, Katherine Parker of Tacoma,
concluded testimony in the trial Thursday. She said that Ms.
Hamilton, her former roommate, had told her that Mrs. Nickell
talked of getting rid of her husband and asked how much cocaine it
would take to kill a person.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
