<DOCNO> AP880502-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 0338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DysonAide-Reax     05-02 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dyson Aide-Reax,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Pappas' Death Won't Affect Dyson Re-Election Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Dyson Aide, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The apparent suicide of Rep. Roy P. Dyson's top
aide sent shock waves through Maryland's political community, but
fellow Democrats predicted the congressman would be re-elected to a
fifth term.
   ``I don't think this reflects on Roy Dyson. At this point, I
would say it has no impact (on the election),'' said Rep. Benjamin
Cardin, a Democrat who represents Maryland's 3rd Congressional
District.
   The aide, Tom Pappas, 46, of Accokeek, was being investigated by
the Federal Election Commission over allegations that the
39-year-old Dyson's campaign disclosure reports concealed $6,650 in
payments to Pappas.
   Pappas' died Sunday, the day The Washington Post published a
story that described former aides' accounts of unorthodox job
demands Pappas made on young male congressional staffers and
allegations that Dyson had ceded control of his Washington office
to Pappas.
   ``I think the only thing I have to say is it's a real tragedy
that anybody gets to the place where they feel the alternative is
to take their life,'' said Rep. Steny Hoyer, of the 5th District.
   ``All the reports indicate apparently Mr. Pappas apparently did
some things that one would speculate from his actions that he felt
were very wrong,'' Hoyer said.
   ``None of the reports I've heard have indicated Mr. Dyson is
himself involved. If that is the case, I would see no reason that
he wouldn't be re-elected as he was in the past,'' said Hoyer, who
has known Dyson about 15 years.
   Eastern Shore Republicans, who are seeking to regain control of
the seat, also were shocked.
   ``I find it very difficult to be critical of Mr. Pappas at this
point,'' said Dyson's GOP opponent in the November election, Wayne
Gilchrest. ``Being critical at this point is not necessary.''
   He said the allegations in the Post story would have no effect
on the type of campaign he ran.
   ``Regardless of what happens in the Dyson camp, I have a certain
point of view I want to get across, and (it) doesn't change my
campaign.''
</TEXT>
