<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 0406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CableTV     05-02 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cable TV,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cable Industry Growing Into `Goliath'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of being considered the little
sibling of broadcast television, some say the cable TV industry is
beginning to look more like Goliath than David.
   Cable TV, now watched by more than 50 percent of all American
households, has become a $12 billion industry that is gaining
viewers steadily, mostly at the expense of the broadcast networks.
   But with prosperity comes increased scrutiny, and in cable's
case Congress has been raising questions about concentration of
ownership within the industry, complaints of poor service and
rising rates. Some in Congress say it may be time to reregulate
cable TV.
   ``We have to pay attention to this,'' James P. Mooney, president
of the National Cable Television Association, told an audience at
the opening session of the group's annual convention Sunday.
   ``We can't rebuff our friends,'' he said. ``An important part of
good business is good politics.''
   More than 13,000 people are expected to attend the convention,
which runs through Tuesday.
   Most governmental regulation has been lifted from the industry.
The most recent deregulation came in January 1987 when most cable
systems were freed of municipal rate control. They now have more
control than ever on what viewers see and how much they pay.
   Deregulation brought increases in rates. The industry says the
average subscriber's bill rose 6.7 percent in the first six months
after price control was lifted, but critics in Congress cite
instances of rates going up by as much as 400 percent in some
systems.
   Despite the increase, subscribers continued to sign on. Cable
systems added more than 4 million subscribers in 1987, putting the
percentage of households receiving cable to nearly 52 percent _
about 45 million households.
   Now that many cable companies have finished building their
systems _ wiring more than 80 percent of the nation's households _
cable companies are starting to pay off their debt and are putting
their cash into programming.
   ``Programming is going to drive penetration,'' said James S.
Cownie, president of Heritage Communications of Des Moines, Iowa,
and NCTA chairman.
   ``That's going to move us up to the 70 percent saturation level
from 52 percent where we are now.''
   The industry has been encouraged by the success of its early
efforts, like Showtime's ``It's Garry Shandling's Show,'' a comedy
series now on Fox Broadcasting Co.
   The show is one of only a few that have moved from cable to
broadcast. Most of the migration is still from broadcast to cable,
which has become home to many an old syndicated rerun.
   But cable executives say that will change as cable systems pour
more money into developing their own programs.
   ``We should be more concerned with what the content will be than
where it comes from,'' said Michael S. Fuchs, chairman of Home Box
Office.
   HBO received praise for its recent program ``Dear America:
Letters Home from Vietnam.''
   Cable TV, particularly the Entertainment and Sports Programming
Network, ESPN, also has been landing some big sports contracts.
Exclusive cable contracts for big sports events, though, have been
criticized for denying viewing of these games to those who don't
subscribe to cable. Before cable came along, these games could be
seen free on broadcast TV.
   But cable is likely to continue its foray into sports
programming.
   ``There are more first run movies and sports on cable, and
that's going to continue,'' said Fuchs. ``The only things that will
get some protection (from cable-exclusive contracts) are big sports
events like the Superbowl.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 0427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CoalingaQuake     05-02 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coalinga Quake,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feelings Mixed Whether Rebuilt Downtown Is Better</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALINGA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coalinga's downtown business district,
devastated five years ago by one of California's strongest
earthquakes this century, is still struggling to recover.
   In one terrifying moment, the town's turn-of-the-century stores
buckled under the force of the quake.
   The 6.7-magnitude temblor on May 2, 1983, dealt its heaviest
toll to two blocks that held most of the community's retail stores.
All had to be razed.
   Today on the same land, modern one-story block buildings house
the merchants who hung on during the hard times after the quake in
the town of 8,000 residents about 200 miles southeast of San
Francisco.
   But vacant lots also mark much of downtown, raising concern that
there are too few shops left to attract enough customers to be
profitable.
   ``If there were other businesses, things would be working
tremendously; there are too many empty lots,'' said Marjorie Kerr,
who moved all the clothes from her dress shop to her less-damaged
home after the earthquake until she could get back in business,
first in a gymnasium, then a house trailer and now in the
rejuvenated downtown.
   Downtown businesses now include two dress shops, two banks, two
drug stores, a furniture store, a combination bicycle-computer shop
and a Sears mail order store. Other downtown offices house a weekly
newspaper, a lawyer, accountant and real estate agent.
   ``There are no coffee shops, so people don't come downtown as
much,'' said Mrs. Kerr. ``We need more retail in these two blocks,
not offices.''
   The city government, which aggressively secured a variety of
financing to recover from the quake, owns the rebuilt stores and is
trying to find more financing and more businesses to fill the empty
lots.
   The city subsidizes rents, charging about 34 cents a square
foot, said Glen Adams, a councilman and Chamber of Commerce
director. That's a sharp increase from the 10-20 cents per square
foot merchants paid for space in the structures wiped out by the
quake.
   Those increases make survival difficult for store owners who
were just making it under the old rents. Mrs. Kerr said the owners
of a jewelry store decided to retire after the earthquake, a
television store closed and one business owner died of stress while
struggling to keep going in a house trailer.
   Not all merchants have been hurt, however. The operators of
Service Pharmacy owned their building and it was fully insured,
enabling them to rebuild large enough for their needs and allow
space to rent out offices.
   Sales taxes, which indicate how much retail business a community
is doing, haven't climbed back to the level before the earthquake,
which left 47 injured and caused an estimated $31 million in
damage, said Alan Jacobsen, the public works director.
   But 2,873 building permits were issued in the five years since
for $41 million worth of new construction or rehabilitation, he
said.
   ``That's about one permit per building in town,'' Jacobsen said.
   There has been a net gain of 384 dwellings in Coalinga since the
earthquake, allowing the population to increase from 7,000 to
8,000, Jacobsen said.
   The city also has a new natural gas system, new sewer lines, a
new fire station, bus terminal, day care center, senior citizens
center, fitness center and community swimming pool.
   Despite the personal and financial trauma, Jacobsen feels the
earthquake ``was a real positive thing in making us clean up some
problems we had in buildings _ safety and that type of thing.''
   The quake was one of California's 10 strongest quakes this
century.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. The San Francisco earthquake of 1906, which occurred
before the Richter scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3 on
the Richter scale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
