<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 0454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Contras     05-02 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Return After Talks Stall, Want Next Round Held Outside
Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders outraged over actions of the
Sandinistas said they want the next round of peace talks outside
Nicaragua, while President Daniel Ortega has insisted that any new
discussions take place in the country.
   Two of the five-member Nicaraguan Resistance, Adolfo Calero and
Joaquin Chamorro, returned here Sunday following the second round
of stalled talks.
   A key issue has been the workings of the cease-fire agreement
signed in Sapoa, Nicaragua, on March 23.
   ``They are hinging the entire cease-fire agreement on how goods
will be delivered instead of on the democratization of Nicaragua,''
Chamorro said. ``We had already agreed on how the goods will be
delivered, and now they bring it up again.''
   The leaders of the U.S.-backed rebels expressed outrage with the
actions of the leftist government during the talks, saying
Nicaraguan officials had reneged on promises and created an
oppressive atmosphere that jeopardizes future talks in the wartorn
country.
   ``They have been carrying on a succession of repressive actions
against the people of Nicaragua,'' Calero said.
   ``They have taken action against striking workers, the interior
minister has beaten one of Nicaragua's distinguished radio
reporters,'' he said, ``and we are forced to stay in our hotel like
it's a prison.''
   On Friday, Jose Castillo Osejo, director of the anti-Sandinista
Radio Corporation, claimed Interior Minister Tomas Borge summoned
him to his office, berated the radio's reporting of anti-government
demonstrations and punched him in the mouth.
   The next round of talks have been tentatively set for May 12-24.
Calero hopes they will be held outside of Nicaragua, maybe in
Guatemala, the Dominican Republic or Costa Rica.
   But Ortega harshly criticized the rebels in his May Day speech
Sunday in Managua, and insisted that the talks continue in
Nicaragua.
   ``It's tough to endure having them here in Managua. We have to
disinfect the entire city after these people leave,'' Ortega told
several thousand backers. ``But now that we're meeting in
Nicaragua, the meetings have to continue in Nicaragua.''
   Rebel leaders say the latest round of talks stalled over details
of how Contra forces may receive humanitarian supplies during a
pact that calls for rebels to enter truce zones. The government is
then to free 700 prisoners and allow Contras to join talks with
Nicaraguan political parties.
   The Contras on Friday rejected a Sandinista proposal that the
International Red Cross resupply the rebels.
   Chamorro said the Red Cross in Nicaragua is ``just another arm
of the Sandinista government.'' He preferred that a private carrier
agreeable to both sides bring in food, clothing and medicine.
   Sandinista police on Friday cordoned off the entrance to an
anti-government workers union where demonstrations had been taking
place. About 1,500 construction workers were protesting economic
measures enacted a week earlier.
   Thirty-eight of those workers are on a hunger strike in
Nicaragua, and Contra spokesman Jorge Rosales said Sunday that a
group of Nicaraguan exiles in Miami would lend support by starting
a similar hunger strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 0445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Election     05-02 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Election,0822</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Seek Majority In Iranian Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian radicals will try to win control
of Iran's Parliament in a runoff election on May 13 that could
determine the future course of the Islamic revolution.
   The staunchly anti-Western radicals made sizeable gains in the
first round of voting on April 8 for 188 of the 270 seats in the
Majlis, or parliament, but no faction won a majority. The runoff
will be for the 82 remaining seats.
   The results of the first round, announced by Iran's state-run
media, show a tilt toward the radicals, with some leading
conservatives losing their seats.
   The radicals could be helped in the runoff by the anti-American
passions that resulted after six Iranian vessels were destroyed or
disabled in the Persian Gulf in battles with the U.S. Navy on April
18.
   If the radicals win control of the legislature, they could use
that anti-American sentiment to adopt an even tougher stand against
U.S. intervention in the gulf over the next four-year parliamentary
term.
   Tehran Radio reported that just under 17 million Iranians voted
in the first round, about 80 percent of the electorate.
   Interior Ministry Ali-Akbar Mohtashemi, a hardliner whose power
is growing, declared that the turnout for the third parliamentary
election since Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's 1979 revolution was a
record.
   Among the winners were Hojatoleslam Mehdi Karroubi, firebrand
head of Iran's Pilgrimage Bureau who is believed to have
masterminded riots in the holy city of Mecca last July. Karroubi, a
middle-ranking cleric, heads a radical group called Militant
Clergymen.
   According to figures released by Iran's Interior Ministry and
broadcast by Tehran Radio, he polled 971,752 votes in his Tehran
constituency, second only to House Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, one
of the most powerful figures in Iran.
   Rafsanjani, a close confidant of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini,
took more than 1.3 million votes, the highest single vote so far
announced.
   ``The results so far indicate that the third Majlis will be
heavily weighted in favor of the radicals, opening the way for
reformist legislation,'' said London-based analyst Vahe Petrossian
in the Middle East Economic Digest.
   However, Gary Sick, a former Iran specialst with the U.S.
National Security Agency, said in a telephone interview: ``The real
picture won't emerge until the runoffs ... and when the Majlis
elects the cabinet.''
   Nonetheless, the election is expected to produce big gains for
the radicals who are advocating major economic and social reforms
long blocked by conservative clerics and the ``Bazaaris,'' the
wealthy merchant class who have survived the revolution and still
wield considerable influence.
   Although the final makeup of the Majlis remains incomplete, the
first-round voting appears to have bolstered both Rafsanjani, who
favors economic reforms, and Prime Minister Hussein Musavi.
   Among other radicals who won were Ateqe Sediqi Rajai, widow of
the late President Mohammed Ali Rajai, and one of 35 women among
the 1,700 candidates.
   Rajai was assassinated with Prime Minister Mohammed Javad
Bahonar, when leftist opponents of Khomeini bombed Bahonar's office
Aug. 31, 1981.
   Another winner was Hadi Ghafari, an Islamic ideologue who
trained with the PLO in Lebanon and was a key figure in forming
Khomeini's Revolutionary Guards.
   He was among the winners in 14 of the 30 Tehran districts where
final results were announced, along with Fakhreddin Hejazi, another
firebrand mullah who got more than 700,000 votes, and former
Agriculture Minister Mohammad Salamati, with more than 500,000.
   One of the winners in the holy city of Qom was Hojatoleslam
Sadeq Khalkali, a former Islamic judge who ordered the execution of
hundreds of people by firing squad or the hangman's rope in the
early days of the revolution. Tehran Radio said he polled nearly
200,000 votes in the first ballot.
   Several leading conservatives were either knocked out of the
running or failed to win absolute majorities and now face runoff
competition May 13, according to monitored radio reports.
   Among them were Rafsanjani's deputy, Mohammad Yazdi, a prominent
deputy in the Majlis; and former Commerce Minister Habib
Asgarouladi.
   Former Interior Minister Ayatollah Ali-Akbar Nateq-Nouri, a
member of the now-disbanded hard-line Islamic Republic Party,
failed to get a clear majority and will have to run in the May 13
second round, Tehran Radio said.
   Nateq-Nouri, who was also briefly armed forces commander after
President Abolhassan Bani-Sadr was ousted in 1982, now heads the
Hojati group, an extremist Islamic faction.
   Musavi's radicals held a slim majority in the last Majlis. But
he got a big boost from Khomeini before the election that could
improve that position.
   Khomeini, apparently seeking to break a legislative logjam he
feared was paralyzing the government and delaying badly needed
economic reforms, decreed sweeping powers for the government aimed
at increasing state control of the economy as advocated by Musavi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
