<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-USRabbi     05-02 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-US Rabbi,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frustrated American Rabbi Leaving Job In Communist East Berlin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After eight months on the job and several disputes
with Jewish leaders, the American rabbi who leads East Germany's
tiny Jewish community is heading home and may not return to
communist East Berlin.
   ``They attempted to silence me altogether,'' Rabbi Isaac Neuman
said of the leadership of East Berlin's Jewish community.
   Neuman, the communist country's first rabbi in 21 years, said:
``I don't want to come across as whining, or as an enemy of the
state or as being defeated.'' He added: ``I can at least say I have
tried. I cannot say I feel I have accomplished everything.''
   Neuman said he plans to return to Illinois on May 16.
   ``It's conceivable it (the return) is for good, but I may be
back in September. I have no intention of being here beyond 1988,
because the situation is too impossible to work.''
   In an interview with The Associated Press on Sunday, Neuman
compared his situation to a brief stint as a rabbi in Alabama in
the early 1960s when he ran into strong resistance for speaking out
in favor of civil rights for blacks.
   ``In a sense I feel the same kind of isolation,'' the feisty,
65-year-old reform rabbi said in his apartment in East Berlin.
   The Polish-born survivor of Auschwitz and nine other Nazi
concentration camps took over the post that had been empty since
1966. He is the rabbi for the less than 350 officially registered
Jews and about 100 people he says are ``on the fringes.''
   The largest Jewish community, with a little under 200 members,
is located in East Berlin. Others are in the cities of Halle,
Dresden and Leipzig.
   Neuman took over the post in September 1987, after retiring as
rabbi in Champaign, Illinois.
   Since then, he has run into several disputes with the head of
the Jewish community in East Berlin, whom he asked the AP not to
identify by name.
   ``Maybe he has orders from somewhere to keep me under control,''
Neuman says. ``He even controls my mail.''
   Neuman says there have been efforts within the Jewish community
to silence him, for example by making it difficult to teach adult
religious classes.
   ``I was told not to speak on Friday night because the service
was too long. But that's a lie,'' says Neuman. ``It was designed to
silence me.''
   He also has taken to task the editor of a government-run East
German newspaper for alleged inaccuracies in reporting about
Israel. He also is worried about anti-Semitism in the news media,
and points to the work of an East German cartoonist he says uses
such themes.
   Neuman also criticized the government's unwillingness to help
restore the dilapidated Jewish community building where he works.
   ``Yes, I have violated taboos,'' he says, but insists everything
he has done is permitted, even in East Germany.
   Neuman is paid by the East Berlin Jewish community, which in
turn receives funds from the communist government.
   The rabbi emphasized during the AP interview he had always
viewed his post as a ``temporary assignment.''
   Neuman said that he would return to his home in Champaign.
   Asked if he planned to write an autobiography, the rabbi replied
with a smile: ``I soon may have enough time.''
   While Neuman outlines his disagreements in East Berlin, there
has been some criticism of him as well.
   ``The Jewish community in East Berlin is startled by the
unconventionality and the independence of their rabbi,'' the
authoritative Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung newspaper said of him
in a profile on April 19.
   The West German newspaper also said the ``tempermental rabbi''
had threatened to leave in the past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0046 </DOCNO>
