<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 0512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-LePen     05-02 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Le Pen,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rightist Leader Refuses to Endorse Chirac</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jean-Marie Le Pen, France's extreme right leader,
refused to endorse conservative Premier Jacques Chirac but told
supporters not to vote for President Francois Mitterrand in the May
8 presidential runoff election.
   ``We are in a position of choosing between the bad and the
worst,'' Le Pen told 30,000 of his National Front followers in the
Tuileries Gardens in the heart of Paris on Sunday.
   Le Pen, who ran on an anti-immigration, ``French first''
platform, was eliminated along with six other candidates in
first-round voting April 24, but his surprisingly strong showing
means his National Front followers could influence the outcome of
the runoff.
   Le Pen called the runoff vote on May 8 ``a formality'' _ the
Socialist Mitterrand is widely considered a cinch to win.
   The right-wing candidate told his supporters to organize for the
future. ``Once the people of France are informed, we will be the
majority,'' he said.
   Hundreds of riot police sealed off the area, fearing clashes
with tens of thousands of unionists protesting Le Pen in
countermarches.
   Le Pen called his rally to honor May Day and Joan of Arc,
advancing her traditional feast day by a week because of the May 8
election. Le Pen has appropriated Joan of Arc as a National Front
symbol.
   Supporters first marched through the center of Paris, then moved
to the lushly green Tuileries where a Roman Catholic Mass was said
in Latin.
   Le Pen, 59, took 14.4 percent of the first-round vote, worrying
many who fear the National Front could awaken racist sentiments.
   Since April 24, Chirac has tried to attract Le Pen's following,
stressing the need to stop immigration and conserve France's
national identity _ top themes of Le Pen who claims that France,
inundated by immigrants from former North African colonies, is
being drained economically, socially and culturally.
   Le Pen called the Socialist president a traitor for his views on
immigrants and separatists in the strife-torn territory of New
Caledonia.
   ``No. No. No. Not a single vote for Francois Mitterrand,'' Le
Pen said from his rain-drenched stage in the elegant gardens
overlooking the Place de la Concorde and the Arch of Triumph.
   But Le Pen avoided a straight ``yes'' or ``no'' on Chirac, whom
he referred to as the ``residual candidate.''
   Le Pen spelled out three possibilities for his followers: stay
home, vote for Chirac ``to avoid the worst,'' or decide at the last
minute depending on Chirac's statements in the final week of the
campaign.
   ``If Jacques Chirac is defeated, he has only himself, his
friends and his allies to blame,'' Le Pen said. ``We have no
responsibility in the voting.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
