<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-02 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Stocks Close At Record High; Dollar Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose across the board today in the
Tokyo Stock Exchange while the dollar closed stronger.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, the market's main barometer,
closed at a record high of 27,669.72, or 160.18 points higher than
Saturday's close.
   Volume was estimated at a moderate 900 million shares.
   Traders said electronics shares, such as Sony and Toshiba, were
rising.
   ``Many institutional investors are on vacation so today's
bullishness is largely caused by private investors,'' said a broker
at a major Japanese securities firm. ``They (private investors) are
expecting share prices to soar after Golden Week. So, they want to
make sure they buy shares beforehand,'' said the dealer, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Golden Week is the seven-day stretch that began Friday in which
Japan celebrates four national holidays. The Tokyo foreign exchange
market was closed Friday and all banks, financial institutions,
markets and most businesses will be closed Tuesday through Thursday
for the holidays.
   ``The major shift will show up after the holiday,'' the broker
added.
   Meanwhile, the dollar also rose to close the day's dealings at
125.33 yen, up 0.51 yen from Thursday's close of 124.82 yen.
   ``The general trend is the strong dollar, but there are hardly
any major moves at all,'' said Hiroaki Shukuzawa of the Sumitomo
Bank. ``The market saw recent U.S. economic indicators as favorable
and the dollar regained the losses it suffered after the poor
showings of the last month's U.S. trade figures.''
</TEXT>
