<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-02 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Severe May Snow Storm Lashes Colorado, Wyoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wyoming and Colorado braced for near-blizzard conditions today
as a May snow storm bore down on mountainous areas, dumping up to a
foot of new snow, while a line of thunderstorms swept over the
Great Plains.
   In Wyoming, winter storm warnings remained in effect today for
the eastern portion of the state, along with the Bighorn Mountains
and the Wind River Range. Evanston and Rock Springs were blanketed
by up to 7 inches of snow Sunday night.
   Up to a foot of new snow was expected today in the higher
elevations of eastern Wyoming, and near-blizzard conditions were
expected to develop this afternoon in the southeast quarter of the
state.
   A winter storm warning was in effect for the northern and
central mountains of Colorado, where 6 to 12 inches of snow was
expected. The storm warning also covered western South Dakota,
where up to a foot of snow was forecast.
   A winter storm watch was posted for the northeastern foothills
and higher elevations around the Pikes Peak and Palmer Divide areas
in Colorado.
   Meanwhile, strong thunderstorms developed ahead of the cold
front crossing the Great Plains. A thunderstorm in southeastern
Colorado brought high winds that uprooted trees and damaged yard
fences Sunday night.
   The line of thunderstorms extended from southwest Kansas into
west-central Texas early this morning. A tornado watch was posted
for a large part of the Texas panhandle, portions of northwest
Texas and much of the Oklahoma panhandle.
   Today's forecast called for rain scattered over northern Maine
and the northern half of the Pacific coast; rain with snow in the
mountains from the northern half of the Plains into the Rockies;
rain and thunderstorms across Oklahoma and much of Kansas and
strong and gusty winds over Mississippi and the southern Plains.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 30s and 40s over the
Rockies; the 50s and 60s over New England, the lower Great Lakes,
Virginia, West Virginia, northern Minnesota, the Dakotas, the
western central Plains, the upper Missouri Valley, and the northern
half of the Pacific Coast; the 80s over Florida, the central Gulf
Coast states, the lower Mississippi Valley, southeastern Texas and
the desert Southwest; the 70s over the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 13
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 74 degrees at Key
West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 55 fair; Boston 45 showery; Buffalo 48 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 52 fair; Cincinnati 46 fair; Cleveland 43 fair;
Detroit 46 fair; Miami 69 cloudy; New York 50 cloudy; Philadelphia
51 cloudy; Pittsburgh 47 fair; Portland, Maine 44 rain; Washington
54 partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 51 showers; Chicago 47 fair; Dallas-Fort
Worth 63 fair; Denver 36 rain; Des Moines 61 cloudy; Indianapolis
53 fair; Kansas City 65 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 60
partly cloudy; Nashville 46 fair; New Orleans 54 fair; St. Louis 59
fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 44 partly cloudy; Anchorage 41 fair; Las
Vegas 54 fair; Los Angeles 61 fair; Phoenix 60 fair; Salt Lake City
38 partly cloudy; San Diego 59 fair; San Francisco 51 partly
cloudy; Seattle 44 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 41 fair; Toronto 45 cloudy.
</TEXT>
