<DOCNO> AP880502-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 0644EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NewCaledonia     05-02 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Caledonia,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Officials Offer To Take Place Of New Caledonia Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three rightist elected officials
today offered to change places with 21 hostages held by Melanesian
militants, but the main separatist group ridiculed the proposal.
   Dick Ukeiwe, who represents New Caledonia in the French Senate,
said he and two members of the National Assembly, Jacques Lafleur
and Maurice Nenou, wished to ``take the place of the hostages to
bring an end to their ordeal and to assume fully our
responsibilities.''
   A group of Melanesians who killed four gendarmes in an attack
April 22 are still holding 21 officers hostage in a cave on Ouvea,
a small island off the eastern coast of New Caledonia.
   Bernard Pons, minister for overseas territories in Premier
Jacques Chirac's conservative government, endorsed the proposed
exchange and Noumea Mayor Jean Leques ordered all offices, shops
and bars in the capital closed at 4 p.m. (1 a.m. EDT) in support of
the idea.
   The Kanak Socialist National Liberation Front, known by its
French initatials FLNKS, dismissed the offer and reiterated the
demand for a mediator with authority from Chirac and Socialist
President Francois Mitterrand to negotiate a referendum on
independence for the Pacific island territory.
   Hnalaine Uregei, a member of the FLNKS political bureau, told
reporters the exchange proposal was ``at the same time grotesque,
ridiculous and indecent.''
   On Sunday, the front rejected Monsignor Michel Calvet, Roman
Catholic archbishop of Noumea, as a mediator to negotiate the
release of the hostages.
   ``We want someone who would be representative of the colonial
power, who would have authority to commit the colonial power,''
Uregei said today.
   Uregei, Lafleur and Nenou are all members of Chirac's rightist
party, the Rally for the Republic, and among the most prominent
opponents of the separatist movement.
   Native Melanesians, known as Kanaks, make up 43 percent of New
Caledonia's 145,000 population. About 36 percent of the population
is European, and the others are mostly Asian or Tahitian.
   The FNLKS is opposed to Chirac's plan for giving partial
autonomy to the territory, as endorsed last year in a referendum
boycotted by the separatists.
   On April 22, the rebels raided a post of the gendarmerie _
police under military command _ seizing 27 officers and killing
four. Twelve hostages were released, but eight others taken,
including the head of an anti-terrorism squad and an assistant
prosecutor.
   The prosecutor and the anti-terrorism squad leader were freed
and ordered to negotiate on behalf of the terrorists, but told the
remaining hostages would be killed if the two men did not return to
the cave hideout. Because of that threat, authorities still
consider the two as hostages, for a total of 23.
</TEXT>
