<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 0653EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VeteranGlider     05-02 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Veteran Glider,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disabled War Veteran Begins Attempt to Cross Nation in Sailplane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHULA VISTA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnam veteran who lost both legs
in combat took off in a sailplane in a 2,500-mile attempt to become
the first person to glide across the United States.
   The sailplane Eagle, with pilot Terry Frazier, 41, at the
controls, was lifted into the air by a tow plane Sunday at Brown
Field near the Mexican border.
   Frazier is trying to raise nearly $50,000 in pledges to help
maintain the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington.
   Frazier, a nationally ranked sailplane competitor and English
professor, hopes to average about 200 miles a day, reaching Kitty
Hawk, N.C. _ the birthplace of aviation _ on May 19.
   Frazier plans to glide his 15-foot-long craft back to the
Charlotte (N.C.) Motor Speedway, landing inside the racetrack
grounds, to wave the starting flag for the May 22 Winston Cup
NASCAR stock car race.
   Others have tried similar flights, but have been forced to
complete part of the trip by hauling their sailplanes on a trailer,
he said.
   ``I'm not real concerned with whether I accomplish being the
first person to fly (a glider) the entire distance; I'm in it for
the challenge of making the flight,'' Frazier said before takeoff.
   Since taking up the sport six years ago, Frazier has conducted
one ``soar-a-thon'' a year to benefit charity. This is his first
transcontinental attempt, however, and he said the purpose makes it
even more special.
   ``I think the Vietnam Memorial is one of the most important
monuments we have. It's an opportunity for people to heal about the
war and come to grips with their feelings about Vietnam,'' Frazier
said.
   ``Every veteran I know who is still alive feels he's part of
that Vietnam Monument,'' said Frazier, who lost his legs in a 1967
morter attack that took the lives of six of his buddies and wounded
another 18.
   Proceeds from flight pledges will be given to Friends of the
Vietnam Veterans Memorial, a nonprofit group which helps maintain
the monument and assists in memorials for familes of deceased
veterans.
   Frazier has developed artificial legs that clamp onto his
glider's foot controls. He said he became hooked on gliding when he
saw his first one in flight 10 years ago.
   ``I don't even like planes that have engines or gas because when
I was in Vietnam I saw too many planes go down in flames,'' Frazier
said. ``I feel more secure in a plane with no fuel and no engine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
