<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-RedFlag     05-02 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Red Flag,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Editor Promises Lively Successor To Communist Party Journal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An editor of the Communist Party journal Red Flag
said it will be replaced by a livelier new magazine that readers
will enjoy.
   Red Flag, for decades the definitive account of China's
political theory, will cease publication June 16 and be replaced
July 1 by the magazine Seek Truth. The new title comes from a
favorite slogan of Chinese leaders: ``Seek truth from facts.''
   The new magazine ``will firmly implement the policy of `let a
hundred flowers bloom and a hundred schools of thought contend' and
have lively theoretical discussion,'' said Su Xing, Red Flag's
associate editor.
   The ``100 flowers'' slogan refers to Mao Tse-tung's 1957 call
for intellectuals to freely voice criticisms of the party. The
campaign was followed in 1958 by a severe crackdown.
   ``In short ... we will publish a lively magazine that readers
will enjoy reading,'' Su, 30, said in an interview in the official
People's Daily.
   Sources said last December that the Communist Party Secretariat
decided to stop publishing Red Flag because other publications have
taken over its role as the voice of the party.
   Thoughts of China's leaders are now found in the People's Daily,
the weekly Outlook and the national Guangming Daily, which is aimed
at China's intellectuals.
   Red Flag once was required reading for Chinese and foreigners
trying to follow theoretical and political trends within the
Communist Party.
   However, it was increasingly ignored as it gained a reputation
for supporting the old-guard conservative line being displaced by
China's more pragmatic, reform-minded leaders.
   Su said Seek Truth would reflect the thinking of China's
leadership by discussing the reforms in China and looking into the
current political situation, especially the problems created by
reform.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
