<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BandidoArrests     05-02 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bandido Arrests,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agents Arrest Motorcycle Gang Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen members of the Bandidos motorcycle gang
were arrested and eight others were being sought on federal
explosives and conspiracy charges stemming from two 1983 bombings,
an official said.
   Among those arrested Saturday in Corpus Christi, Longview and
Lubbock were top leaders of the national gang, said Richard Garner,
agent in charge of the Dallas office of the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms.
   The suspects are accused of staging the Dallas area bombings in
retaliation for an earlier 1983 clash with the rival Banche gang,
Garner said.
   The bikers were named in a 23-count sealed indictment returned
March 31 by a federal grand jury in Dallas, he said.
   Two other Bandidos members named in the indictment were already
in custody, Garner said.
   A bomb placed near the gas meter of a home in the Dallas suburb
of Lancaster exploded July 5, 1983. Later that day in Dallas, a man
and his 1-year-old daughter received minor injuries when a bomb
exploded inside the van they were in.
   Garner said the blasts were believed intended for members of the
Banches.
   ``Earlier in the year, in the spring of 1983, the Banches and
the Bandidos got into an altercation in Porter, Texas, that
resulted in one Bandido member being killed and several members of
each club being wounded,'' he said.
   Garner said a three-year investigation by the ATF and the
federal Drug Enforcement Administration turned up evidence that the
bombings were retaliatiory.
   Porter is about 25 miles north of Houston.
   Those arrested include Ronald Jerome Hodge, age unknown, of
Memphis, Tenn., identified by authorities as the Bandidos' national
president; Franklin D. Schmick, 44, of Lubbock, national vice
president; and William Jerry Pruett, 48, of Mansfield, Texas,
national secretary-treasurer.
   Garner said all face federal explosives and related conspiracy
charges and some may face further charges.
   The maximum federal penalty for receiving or possessing
destructive devices is 10 years imprisonment and a $250,000 fine on
each count. The maximum penalty for the conspirarcy charge is five
years and a $250,000 fine.
</TEXT>
