<HEAD>Gang Fights Erupt at Anti-Drug Dance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police confiscated weapons ranging from
garden tools to a tire iron when rival gangs battled at a ``Say No
to Crack'' dance.
   At least four people were arrested for investigation of assault
and drunkenness during Sunday night's violence at the United Irish
Cultural Center across from the San Francisco Zoo, police said.
   Within hours, two drive-by shootings occurred in other parts of
the city that may have been related to the battle at the hall, said
officer Dennis Norris.
   Although the fighting was at the Irish center, Norris said most
of those involved in the violence were black or Samoan.
   Officers confiscated an aluminum baseball bat, a tire iron, a
hoe, a shovel, 50 wooden clubs and other weapons, said police Sgt.
Ann Cazahous.
   Norris said a 16-year-old male was shot in the stomach from a
passing vehicle and in another incident a 20-year-old man was hit
in the arm with a blast from a shotgun.
   Both victims were in stable condition at San Francisco General
Hospital.
