<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Teachers-Smoking     05-02 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Teachers-Smoking,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Forbidding Teachers From Smoking Goes To Kansas Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas schoolteachers could not smoke at
school under a bill sent to Gov. Mike Hayden.
   The bill, approved by the House late Saturday, would forbid the
use of all tobacco products inside public school buildings where
students are taught. School district workers could smoke in
administration or maintenance buildings where students don't attend
classes. Teachers could smoke outside schools.
   Several public school districts already ban all tobacco within
their buildings, said John Koepke, executive director of the Kansas
Association of School Boards. Many others allow teachers to smoke
in employee lounges, and some allow students to smoke in outside
areas.
   The bill, supported by Hayden, also would prohibit smoking in
juvenile detention centers and group homes for juveniles operated
by the state.
</TEXT>
