<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SubmarineFire     05-02 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Submarine Fire,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Honors Three Sailors Killed In Submarine Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The loss of three sailors who died
aboard the submarine USS Bonefish was a loss for everyone in the
Navy family, a chaplain said during a weekend memorial service.
   ``All of us gathered here are in a very real sense one large
family,'' Navy chaplain Lt. Cmdr. Raymond Michener told a
congregation of about 500 at St. Michael's Lutheran Church on
Saturday.
   ``We are brought together by nothing else than the sea,'' he
said, adding ``we remember in sadness at our loss _ a son, a
brother, family members, crew members.
   ``We are also here to remember in joy ... and give thanksgiving
for the lives of our brothers,'' he added.
   The April 24 explosion and fire aboard the USS Bonefish off the
Florida coast killed three sailors and injured 22 others among the
92-member crew of the diesel electric submarine.
   Funerals for Lt. Ray Everts, 30, of Naoma, W. Va.; Petty Officer
1st Class Robert W. Bordelon Jr., 39, of Willis, Texas; and Petty
Officer 3rd Class Marshall T. Lindgren, 21, of Pisgah Forest, N.C.,
were held over the weekend.
   During the memorial service under the white Gothic arches of the
church on the edge of the city's historic district, the crew of the
Bonefish dressed in their somber winter blue uniforms as a sign of
mourning. Other Navy personnel in the congregation wore their
summer whites.
   ``We loved these three valiant men,'' said Capt. James
Rutherford of Submarine Group Six _ the group to which the Bonefish
was assigned. ``Thank God for men like them who know the price of
liberty.''
   Vice Adm. Daniel Cooper, the commander of the Atlantic Fleet
submarine forces said ``it is all the men of the Bonefish we honor
today.''
   ``The miracle is that 89 men were rescued and the ship returned
to port through the heroic, professional and unselfish acts of
others,'' he added.
   The Bonefish was on exercises off the Florida coast at the time
of the accident. She was towed back to shore, arriving at the
Charleston Naval Base on Friday.
   A Navy investigation into the cause of the accident is under
way, said Lt. Cmdr. John Tull, a spokesman for the Charleston Naval
Base.
</TEXT>
