<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Leader Tortured, Slain; Palestinian Fighting Kills 12</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with shelling continuing today, more
detail on Khreish's killing, comments. No pickup. Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shell blasts and staccato bursts of
gunfire shook the capital today as police reported 12 people died
and 35 were wounded in factional fighting in Palestinian refugee
camps and neighboring Shiite Moslem slums.
   Meanwhile, the synod of Maronite Catholic bishops met in an
emergency session at the residence of the community's patriarch to
investigate the kidnapping, torture and killing of Monsignor Albert
Khreish, 53, head of the Maronite Spiritual Affairs Court.
   The meeting was chaired by the Nasrallah Sfeir, patriarch of the
850,000 Maronites who make up Lebanon's largest Christian community.
   Police said Khreish's bullet-riddled body was found Sunday by a
bird hunter in a pine tree forest near the Christian resort town of
Ghazir.
   Gunmen kidnapped the priest from his home in Jounieh, a
Christian port north of Beirut, on April 26. He was in his pajamas
when his body was found.
   Khreish was the nephew of Cardinal Mar Antonios Butros Khreish,
the Maronites' former patriarch.
   Police said there were scars indicating physical torture on
Khreish's face and that he had been shot at least 30 times.
   They had no immediate indication as to the reason for his
abduction and slaying in an area controlled by the Lebanese Forces,
the Christians' main militia.
   Christian sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
victim's sister is the wife of the elder brother of Nayef Hawatmeh,
a Palestinian leader who heads the Moscow-oriented Democratic Front
for the Liberation of Palestine.
   ``But no one can ascertain whether this has anything to do with
the murder,'' one source said.
   The Lebanese Forces militia is a bitter enemy of the
Palestinians, who have fought alongside other Moslems in Lebanon's
13-year-old civil war.
   Police said gunfire and shell blasts in Chatilla and Bourj
el-Barajneh refugee camps began Sunday and continued today between
PLO chairman Yasser Arafat's Fatah guerrillas and Syrian-backed
dissidents.
   It was the first major clash between the two sides since
Arafat's reconciliation meeting with Syrian President Hafez Assad
in Damascus last week.
   Police said they had no word on what touched off the clash. They
said both sides fired mortars, rocket-propelled grenades and
machine guns.
   At least two people were killed and 15 wounded in the two camps
in southern Beirut, the police report said.
   Ten people were killed and 20 wounded in fighting Sunday and
early today between two Shiite Moslem groups in the slums of Raml
el-Aali and Roweisse, police said. Police said fighters of the Atat
and Awad clans were battling for local dominance in the two
neighborhoods that adjoin Beirut's airport highway.
   Justice Minister Nabih Berri's Amal militia, the Shiites' main
paramilitary force, moved in after after midnight Sunday in a bid
to end the fighting.
   An Amal communique ordered both clans to lay down their arms and
withdraw from the streets and said violators would be shot.
   South Beirut's slums are outside the jurisdiction of a
7,500-strong Syrian army contingent posted in the Moslem sector of
the Lebanese capital.
   The force has restored some measure of order in west Beirut,
which had been plagued by kidnappings, assassinations and bank
robberies since the civil war began in 1975.
</TEXT>
