<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpearmanSuicide     05-02 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spearman Suicide,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Murderer Commits Suicide In Cell After Escape Plans
Foiled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POLK CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A millionaire boatyard owner convicted in
the contract killing of his wife hated prison and killed himself
when an escape plan was foiled, his attorney and friends said.
   Robert Spearman was imprisoned for hiring two men who answered
an advertisement in Soldier of Fortune magazine to kill his wife,
Anita.
   He hanged himself Saturday in his single confinement cell at
Polk County Correctional Center, three days after authorities
thwarted a helicopter escape plan, said state corrections spokesman
Bob Macmaster.
   ``He was always talking about getting out, that he couldn't
stand it,'' said longtime friend Gene Fenno.
   The attempted breakout also did not come as a complete surprise
to another friend nor to his attorney, David Roth.
   ``Mr. Spearman is approaching 60 and serving a sentence which
would not permit him to be released until he's in his 80s,'' said
Roth, who represented Spearman. ``Someone in his position would not
have a great deal to lose.''
   Dyle Lee, a friend, said the escape attempt was ``not out of
character.''
   ``He's the type of person who does what he wants to, when he
wants to,'' Lee said.
   Spearman, 60, had been sentenced to life plus 20 years.
   ``He had tied one end of the bedsheet around his neck and the
other to the top bars in his confinement cell,'' Macmaster said.
``He was in the cell because he was an escape risk _ nobody thought
he would kill himself.''
   The suicide came after authorities uncovered his escape plans,
an elaborate scheme that included escape by stolen helicopter from
the Zephyrhills Correctional Institution in Tampa, where he had
been serving his sentence until Monday.
   Two undercover agents from the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement posing as pilots received $4,700 as a down payment on a
$54,700 contract to steal a helicopter and fly Spearman out of the
prison, said Ed Williams, agent in charge of the FDLE's Tampa
office.
   Spearman asked the undercover agents to have two machine guns
and four hand grenades aboard the helicopter, authorities said. He
intended to use the grenades to kill his prosecutor, Palm Beach
County Assistant State Attorney Moria Lasch, said John Joyce, an
FDLE spokesman in Tallahassee.
   Spearman was charged with attempted escape and weapons offenses.
Stepson Fred Douglas Laurent Jr. of Fort Lauderdale, a suspected
accomplice, was charged with the same offenses but remained at
large, authorities said.
   In his murder trial, prosecutors said Spearman wanted to get rid
of his cancer-stricken wife, a former West Palm Beach assistant
city manager, because he had fallen in love with his secretary and
didn't want a costly divorce. His wife was bludgeoned to death in
November 1985.
   Spearman was accused of paying $20,000 to Knoxville, Tenn., bar
manager Richard Savage, who placed the Soldier of Fortune
advertisement.
   Authorities contended Savage then sent Sean Doutre, 22, a
bouncer at his bar, to kill Mrs. Spearman. Savage, 39, was
convicted and sentenced to 40 years in prison for his role.
</TEXT>
