<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Sharansky     05-02 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Sharansky,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharansky Leads Immigrants' Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Soviet emigres applauded Natan
Sharansky when they elected him chairman of a group of fellow
former Soviet refuseniks that plans to challenge Israel's
immigration policies.
   ``The recent arrival of a few thousand immigrants showed how bad
the immigrant absorption system is,'' Sharansky said at the meeting
Sunday. ``How can we talk about attracting tens of thousands of
immigrants to Israel when we can't even deal with the few thousand
who came last year?''
   The 40-year-old human rights activist, who spent nine years in
Soviet labor camps, conducted a three-week campaign to unite about
20 groups representing Soviet Jews into an umbrella lobbying forum.
   About 400 activists at the meeting spoke in Russian and proudly
displayed round blue badges designating them as delegates. There
are about 200,000 former Soviet Jews in Israel.
   Sharansky said he wants to set up a private fund to provide
low-interest housing loans for immigrants and create a company that
immigrants can go to for help in building low-cost housing.
   He also proposed an employment agency to help find work for
immigrants and clubs to help immigrants adjust to life in Israel.
   Sharansky said American Jewish organizations are ready to donate
funds directly to the immigrants on condition that they speak with
a single voice.
   His attempt to unite the emigres is not the first in the 19
years of Soviet Jewish emigration. Others have ended in failure,
among them an all-Soviet Jewish party that did not gather the
necessary votes to win a Parliament seat.
   Sharansky has the support of many activists and has succeeded in
bypassing political differences by declaring his forum a
non-political, non-affiliated group.
   ``We shall try to speak in one voice about the issues we agree
upon without involving political arguments,'' he said. But he
dismissed the notion that his movement may become a political party.
   Sharansky played a similar role among Soviet Jews refused
permission to leave the Soviet Union in the 1970s. The best known
Soviet dissident after Andrei Sakharov, he was arrested in 1977,
convicted of being a U.S. spy and sentenced to 13 years in Soviet
prisons. He and the United States denied he was a spy.
   Sharansky was released in February 1986 and came to Israel to
meet his wife Avital, who left the Soviet Union a day after they
were married in 1974.
   Sharansky was seen as a prize for political parties, but he has
called Israeli politics ``nightmarish.''
   ``For a long time I was very cautious about getting involved,''
he said. ``But now it's time to unite.''
   Others at the meeting expressed concern about the high number of
Soviet Jewish ``dropouts,'' Jews who decided to settle in the
United States or West European countries instead of Israel.
   Of more than 8,000 Jews permitted to leave the Soviet Union in
1987, only 20 percent settled in Israel. In April, 1,088 Jews left
the Soviet Union and only 180 came to Israel, Israeli reports said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
