<1ST_LINE>u w PM-FactoryOrders     05-02 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Factory Orders,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gain Biggest Since December</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured
goods climbed 1.6 percent in March, the biggest increase in three
months, the Commerce Department said today.
   The department said that orders for durable and non-durable
goods rose to a seasonally adjusted $216.08 billion in March, the
best showing since a 2 percent rise in December.
   The March advance represented surprising strength, especially
since the government had reported 10 days ago in a preliminary
report that orders for durable goods had remained frozen in March.
   That was changed today to show a healthy 1 percent increase,
reflecting new-found demand in orders for primary metals and
machinery and in the transportation sector.
   The 1.6 percent overall increase followed no change in February
and a slight 0.6 percent drop in January.
   During the first two months of the year, many businesses cut
back on orders in an effort to reduce a large buildup of unsold
goods.
   Originally there was concern that the big rise in unsold goods
that had occurred in the last three months of 1987 would topple the
country into a recession, especially if jittery consumers stopped
buying big-ticket items following the Oct. 19 stock market collapse.
   These fears proved unwarranted, however, as a rebound in
consumer spending helped propel the overall economy to healthy
growth at an annual rate of 2.3 percent in the first three months
of the year.
   The 1.6 percent March increase in factory orders was aided in
part by a 17.4 percent surge in demand for military equipment,
which rose to $10.04 billion. Without this big defense buildup, the
overall orders increase would have been a smaller 1 percent.
   The key category of non-defense capital goods fell 3.8 percent
to $32.5 billion. Despite the setback, analysts are still looking
for this sector to show strength this year as U.S. businesses boost
spending on expansion projects to meet rising demand.
   Orders for transportation equipment climbed 3.4 percent while
orders for primary metals such as steel were up 6.1 percent and
orders for non-electrical machinery advanced 2.1 percent.
   Orders for non-durable goods, items not expected to last three
years, rose 2.3 percent to $100.6 billion.
   Shipments of manufactured goods increased 2.6 percent to a
record high of $214.4 billion following a 0.8 percent February
increase.
   In a separate report, the Commerce Department said that
construction spending rose 1.5 percent in March, the biggest
increase since April 1987.
   The advance was led by a 5.4 percent surge in spending on
government building projects, which climbed to an annual rate of
$82.3 billion, 8.1 percent higher than a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
