<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Contempt     05-02 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Contempt,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules in Case of Rhode Island Newspaper that Published FBI
Information</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ruled that federal
lawyers procedurally botched a contempt-of-court case against a
Rhode Island newspaper that published FBI information about a Mafia
boss.
   By a 6-2 vote, the justices said the procedural flaw must result
in dismissing the government's appeal from a ruling that the
Providence Journal was justified in defying a judge's order barring
publication of the material.
   The newspaper thus had its federal appeals court victory
sustained without the Supreme Court ever reaching the merits of the
contempt-of-court case.
   ``Having concluded that the court-appointed prosecutor who
(appealed) and briefed and argued the case without the
authorization of the solicitor general may not represent the United
States before this court, we dismiss (the appeal),'' Justice Harry
A. Blackmun wrote.
   The flaw was called to the court's attention by the Journal's
lawyers, who requested that the case be tossed out.
   The controversy stems from publication of information the FBI
obtained about Raymond L.S. Patriarca, reputed longtime crime boss
for New England, by tapping his Providence telephone without court
approval from 1962 to 1965.
   The Journal was allowed access to FBI logs and memoranda from
the recordings in 1985, after Patriarca died.
   But Raymond J. Patriarca, son of the reputed crime figure,
challenged in court the information's release. He sought to bar
publication.
   U.S. District Judge Francis J. Boyle held hearings on
Patriarca's complaint on Nov. 13, 1985, and ordered the newspaper
not to publish anything from the FBI materials until a Nov. 15
hearing.
   The Journal on Nov. 14 published an article that included
information from the FBI logs and memoranda.
   Boyle then ruled that the newspaper and its executive editor,
Charles M. Hauser, were in contempt. He fined the Journal $100,000
and ordered Hauser to perform 200 hours of public service.
   But the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned Boyle's
ruling. The appeals court said the order barring publication had
been ``transparently invalid'' and the newspaper therefore could
violate it with impunity.
   When Patriarca challenged release of the information, Boyle had
appointed Providence lawyer William A. Curran as a ``special
prosecutor'' to represent the federal government because the FBI
and Justice Department were defendants in Patriarca's lawsuit.
   Curran also represented the government in the appeals court, and
filed the Supreme Court appeal that was granted review last October.
   But Curran never received Justice Department permission to file
that appeal, and the Journal's lawyers said the lack of permission
was illegal.
   Federal law requires the solicitor general, the Justice
Department's top-ranking courtroom lawyer, to file virtually all
Supreme Court appeals for the government unless he authorizes
someone else to do so.
   Just why Curran was not authorized by Solicitor General Charles
Fried to file the appeal was not explained in briefs submitted to
the justices.
   The National Law Journal reported that sources close to the case
``blame the solicitor general's office, which, they say, showed
little interest in the case despite efforts by the special
prosecutor to maintain contact.''
   Writing for the court today, Blackmun said, ``Absent a proper
representative of the government as a petitioner in this criminal
prosecution, jurisdiction is lacking and the (appeal) heretofore
granted is now dismissed.''
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice John Paul Stevens
dissented. Justice Anthony M. Kennedy did not participate in the
case, U.S. vs. Providence Journal Co., 87-65.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0081 </DOCNO>
