<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0556,0800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lenin Shipyard In Gdansk On Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 5-7, bgng, `Also today ...,' with 5 grafs to UPDATE
with agreement in Wroclaw. PICKS up 8th graf, `Sunday, thousands
...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers went on strike today at the Lenin
shipyard in Gdansk, birthplace of the Solidarity independent trade
movement, government and opposition spokesmen said.
   Government spokesman Zbigniew Augustynowicz said he did not know
how many shipyard workers were taking part in the strike. It
followed an appeal by Solidarity leader Lech Walesa on Sunday for a
``day of action'' to support striking steelworkers in southern
Poland.
   A banner at the shipyard gate said ``Sit-In Strike,'' said
Andrzej Gwiazda, a local Solidarity leader in Gdansk, speaking by
telephone. He said the strike began between 1:30 p.m. and 2:30 p.m.
   The strike was proclaimed in all departments of the shipyard and
at least 3,000 people were participating, according to Walesa, the
1983 Nobel Peace Prize laureate who is employed as an electrician
at the plant. Walesa's remarks were reported by Jacek Kuron, a
senior Solidarity adviser in Warsaw.
   Also today workers at an electronics factory in southwest Poland
ended a one-day work stoppage after they obtained a promise for a
$15 a month pay increase and possible further increases later in
the year, opposition spokesmen said.
   The work stoppage at the Dolmel electronics plant in Wroclaw
involved about about half of the plant's 3,500 workers, said
opposition and government spokesmen.
   At a rally held at 2 p.m., workers were told that management
promised the raise after two hours' negotiations, said Jozef
Pinior, a Wroclaw Solidarity leader at the plant. The workers then
decided to return to work Tuesday, he said.
   In Krakow, authorities locked the gates to the medieval
Jagiellonian University after students scheduled a rally there in
support of the striking steelworkers.
   Despite heavy police presence, dozens of students gathered
briefly at two locations in the Old City of Krakow with banners and
leaflets, said Wladyslaw Surdy, a spokesman for the strike. Police
detained 10 people, he said.
   Sunday, thousands of people heeded Solidarity's call for a
national day of protest and scores of demonstrators were arrested
in clashes with police in at least 19 cities.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said 90 people were detained
during the May Day protests. Solidarity spokesman Zbigniew
Romaszewski said authorities detained at least 200 people.
   There were scattered reports of injuries but figures were not
available.
   Meanwhile, steelworkers striking for a seventh day near Krakow
in southern Poland awaited an answer to a request for negotiations
with the deputy prime minister in charge of the economy.
   A secretary to Deputy Prime Minister Zdzislaw Sadowski said
Poland's economic and planning chief had not received a letter sent
Sunday by striking steelworkers. The letter invited Sadowski to
negotiate with them at the Lenin steelworks in Nowa Huta.
   A strike committee at the plant says it represents 16,000 of the
plant's 32,000 employees and is demanding recognition of their
union rights and a 50 percent raise on the average salary of $105 a
month.
   Management said that fewer than 1,000 strikers were at the Nowa
Huta plant Sunday. In Polish strikes, workers come to the plant
during their scheduled shifts but do no work.
   Urban said at least 12,000 people took part in illegal
demonstrations Sunday. Reports from witnesses and opposition
spokesmen put the number at more than 30,000.
   The demonstrations followed a week of strikes and the worst
labor unrest in Poland since the communist government suspended
Solidarity in December 1981. It later outlawed the trade federation.
   Solidarity had called for the demonstrations to protest a lack
of union freedom and the government's austerity policy which has
caused prices to rise by 42 percent recently.
   Romaszewski, the Solidarity spokesman who kept track of arrests,
complained of ``exceptional brutality'' by police in Wroclaw. He
said 84 demonstrators were detained there and claimed that that
even passive protesters were repeatedly beaten.
   In Gdansk on Sunday, Walesa told 6,000 supporters they must
support strikers at the Lenin steel mill.
   ``I demand from you solidarity with Nowa Huta tomorrow, in your
shipyards, in your ports and in your factories. I want it to be
effective. Show me tomorrow what you can do,'' he declared.
   After the rally, police with clubs attacked 500 militants who
tried to march through Gdansk. During the 40-minute melee,
protesters hurled rocks and police beat demonstrators. At least
four people were seen bleeding. Dozens were herded into police vans.
   The state-run news agency PAP said more than 9 million people
attended official May Day ceremonies nationwide.
</TEXT>
