<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Kungys     05-02 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Kungys,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Further Hearings on New Jersey Man Accused of Helping
Nazis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ordered further lower
court hearings to determine whether a New Jersey man accused of
helping Nazis kill more than 2,000 Jews in Lithuania should be
stripped of his U.S. citizenship.
   By a 6-2 ruling, the court set aside a lower court ruling that
revoked the citizenship of 71-year-old Juozas Kungys, a retired
dental technician from Clifton, N.J.
   The decision means at least a temporary postponement in the
government's likely effort to deport Kungys.
   The justices also provided some guidelines for determining when
the government may strip the citizenship of those accused of lying
to gain entry to the United States and to win citizenship.
   Revoking citizenship _ a process called denaturalization _ is a
preliminary step leading to deportation.
   Justice Antonin Scalia, in his opinion for the court, said
citizens generally may be denaturalized if their alleged
misstatements or concealments of facts ``had a natural tendency''
to influence decisions by immigration officials.
   Moreover, Scalia said another provision of immigration law
permits denaturalization if the misstatements demonstrate lack of
good moral character.
   The court ordered the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to
reconsider Kungys' case in light of the standards the justices
outlined today.
   The 3rd Circuit court stripped Kungys of his citizenship in
1986, clearing the way for his likely deportation.
   Kungys has lived in the United States since 1948 and became a
citizen in 1954.
   The government said he lived in Kedainiai, Lithuania, in 1941
when Germany's Nazi forces invaded that area, and that he aided in
atrocities against Lithuanian Jews.
   Government lawyers said Kungys, as a member of a miltiary
organization known as Sauliai, helped force more than 2,000 Jewish
men, women and children to undress and walk into ditches, where
they were shot.
   The 3rd Circuit court had ruled that Kungys made ``material
misrepresentations'' when applying for entry into this country and
when applying for citizenship.
   Kungys' lawyers said the alleged lies _ mispresentations about
his age and place of birth _ were not significant enough to cost
him his citizenship.
   Government officials said Kungys also lied about where he lived
during World War II in an effort to conceal his true identity.
   Justices Byron R. White and Sandra Day O'Connor said in a
dissenting opinion that they would uphold the 3rd Circuit court
ruling stripping Kungys of his citizenship.
   The case is Kungys vs. U.S., 86-228.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
