<2ND_LINE>PM-Helicopter Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0479,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helicopter Crashes in East River, Killing Businessman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after the 3rd to update with NTSB
investigation, and Subs the 11th thru 13th grafs, beginning ``The
passenger,'' to CORRECT Bellvue to Bellevue.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MEG THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sightseeing helicopter that crashed into the
East River, killing a Japanese businessman and injuring the four
other people aboard, fell out of the sky ``like a stone,'' a
survivor says.
   The Bell 206-B Jet Ranger plunged 1,400 feet into the river
Sunday minutes before it was to land. It quickly sank to a depth of
35 feet in the 40-degree water.
   The 22-year-old pilot had been trying to make an emergency
landing and had radioed that the helicopter was experiencing
``performance difficulties,'' said Island Helicopter Corp. Chairman
George Dempster, whose company owns the aircraft.
   Frank Ghiorsi, head of the National Transportation Safety
Board's New York office, said the aircraft was taken to Island
Helicopter's Long Island base for a mechanical investigation.
   Passenger Christian Pelikan said he heard a ``loud, whistling
noise,'' then the helicopter fell ``like a stone into the water.''
   The pilot had activated emergency flotation pontoons, but they
apparently separated from the craft on impact, Dempster said.
   The cabin darkened and filled with water, Pelikan said.
   ``I couldn't open the seat belt,'' the 55-year-old West German
businessman said. ``After about 45 seconds, I slipped out of the
safety belt and found a hole in the door, perhaps it was a window.
I do not know. I could not see.''
   Pelikan, the pilot and two other passengers who made their way
to surface were pulled out of the water by police. They were not
seriously hurt.
   A police scuba diver found the fourth passenger strapped into a
rear seat in the helicopter 1{ hours later, and cut him loose.
   The passenger, identified by the Japanese Consulate as Takashi
Oyama, was taken to Bellevue Hospital, where he died, said Peter
Schectman, a hospital administrator.
   Oyama worked for Honda Inc. in Japan, the consulate said.
   Three of the survivors were also taken to Bellevue, where they
were listed in stable condition today. Pelikan was at the Ear and
Eye Infirmary in satisfactory condition.
   The Federal Aviation Administration and the National
Transportation Safety Board are investigating the accident, said
Kathleen Bergen, an FAA spokeswoman.
   The pilot, Robert Marshall of Sea Cliff, was experienced and had
1,700 hours of flight time, Dempster said.
</TEXT>
