<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-FangLizhi     05-02 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Fang Lizhi,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Scientist Published Five Books Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astrophysicist Fang Lizhi, an outspoken critic of
Marxism in China, published or edited five scientific works last
year, an authoritative weekly said today in a lengthy article
chronicling Fang's academic achievements.
   ``Writing and editing five books in one year is my record,'' the
Beijing Review quoted Fang as saying. ``It may be the result of my
concentrated effort.''
   One of the books, ``Creation of Cosmology,'' was co-published
with his wife Li Shuxian, a physics teacher at Beijing University,
where the couple live.
   Fang, 52, was expelled from the Communist Party and fired from
his job as vice president of the University of Science and
Technology in Anhui province in January 1987 after being accused of
inciting students to stage pro-democracy demonstrations.
   The official media, however, has stressed in several pieces on
Fang that he enjoys academic freedom at the Beijing Observatory,
where he has been working since last year.
   Since losing his university job ``for outspokenly advocating
bourgeois liberalist views,'' the Beijing Review said, ``Fang has
achieved a great deal in his research work.''
   The article said Fang was allowed to visit Italy for the 12th
time last summer for academic activities, during which he reached
an agreement with the Italian Foreign Ministry to jointly build an
international exchange center for astrophysics in Beijing.
   While in Italy, friends urged him to stay abroad, but Fang
refused, saying that as a scientist he had a social responsibility,
the weekly said.
   It did not mention an interview Fang gave to the West German
magazine Der Spiegel while in Rome in which he said that ``Marxism
is a thing of the past'' and that ``democracy that comes from above
is no democracy, it is nothing but a relaxation of control.''
   The Beijing Review quoted Fang as saying that last year's
student demonstrations and Chinese authorities' ensuing campaign
against bourgeois liberalization, or Western ideas, at least made
people think.
   ``I haven't done an all-round, deep study of China's politics
and economy. I just speak my own mind,'' he said.
   He said the Chinese people have high hopes in the Communist
Party following a major party congress last fall in which leaders
committed the party to long-range political and economic reforms.
</TEXT>
