<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FairgroundsAccident     05-02 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fairgrounds Accident,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Race Car Accident Kills One Spectator, Injures Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness said a stuck throttle may
have caused a race car to spin out of control, killing one person
and injuring five at the state fairgrounds.
   ``There was general chaos, a lot of dust, screaming and
running,'' Kent Gray, who was taking pictures at the event, said
Sunday. ``The driver walked away from the accident in tears.''
   State Police Trooper Nelson Capitano said the car, equipped with
large wheels, hit spectators who were watching the ``mud bog''
event of the General Tire 4-Wheel and Off-Road Jamboree Spring
Nationals.
   ``The vehicle going through the mud bog lost control and went
through a fence that was 350 feet from the end of the bog, and hit
spectators who were 95 feet back of the fence,'' Capitano said.
   ``He just couldn't stop. We don't know if something mechanical
broke or what. We're investigating,'' he said.
   Gray said that when the car got out of the mud bog it made a
loud noise as though the throttle was stuck.
   The car crashed sideways through a wire and wood fence that was
erected for crowd control, then ``rocketed'' toward a group of 30
to 50 spectators at a high rate of speed, Gray said.
   The mud bog is a heavily watered route, 200 feet long, that
includes steep hills.
   Kevin W. Huntley, 23, of Moline, died of massive multiple
injuries, said Sangamon County Coroner Norm Richter.
   Huntley was apparently run over by the car, Richter said.
   Brian T. Luber, 9, of Jacksonville was in critical condition
today at St. John's Hospital, said spokeswoman Mary Jo Gardiner.
   Josephine Gron, 32, of Hobart, Ind., was in serious condition,
and Steve Gand, 23, of Springfield was in fair condition, Ms.
Gardiner said.
   Lewis C. Angeli, 15, of Springfield, was treated and released.
   The driver, Michael Keeney, 31, of Coon Rapids, Minn., was caged
in the car and escaped without serious injury. He was treated at
Memorial Medical Center and released.
   The vehicle was impounded and Keeney was interviewed, but no
charges were expected, Capitano said.
</TEXT>
