<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Productivity     05-02 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Productivity,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Efficiency Gain Nearly Reverses Previous Quarter's Decline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The efficiency of the nation's businesses in
churning out goods and services improved at an annual rate of 0.9
percent in the first quarter of 1988, nearly reversing a
deterioration of 1 percent in the last three months of 1987, the
government said today.
   Despite an increase of nearly a million new jobs from January
through March, non-farm businesses raised the total number of hours
worked by only 1.7 percent while achieving a 2.7 percent increase
in output.
   And for the first time since late 1986, workers overall are
keeping up with inflation, the Labor Department said.
   Wages and benefits increased at an annual rate of 3.4 percent in
the first quarter, raising the labor costs associated with each
service or product by 2.4 percent. Those labor costs had
skyrocketed at an annual rate of 4.5 percent in the final quarter
of 1987 on a massive employment surge.
   However, after taking inflation into account _ as measured by
relative changes in total output and prices _ the wage gains
yielded not a penny more of purchasing power.
   The 0.9 percent improvement in productivity for non-farm
businesses, which are responsible for about three-fourths of the
nation's economic activity, is only slightly ahead of the 0.8
percent increase for all of 1987.
   Earlier figures had shown a 0.3 percent increase in the fourth
quarter of last year, but those were revised in today's report to a
1 percent deterioration.
   Manufacturing, which still accounts for about one-fourth of the
country's gross national product, continued to lead the effort in
restoring U.S. competitiveness.
   Manufacturers' productivity increased at an annual rate of 2.9
percent in the first quarter with a 4.3 percent increase in output
on only a 1.3 percent increase in the number of hours worked in the
nation's factories.
   For the first time since early 1986, factory workers actually
kept ahead of inflation.
   Nominal wage gains averaging 3.9 percent annually in the first
quarter _ the biggest jump in about three years _ increased the
purchasing power of manufacturing employees by one-half of 1
percent after dropping 2.2 percent in 1987.
   It also raised the labor costs associated with each item coming
off the assembly lines by 1 percent, compared with a nearly 2
percent drop in labor costs in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SpaceFactory     05-02 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Factory,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Influential Senators Say `No' to Lease-back Space Lab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four senators who hold sway over NASA spending
say they will not authorize a $700 million scheme to lease an
unmanned robot space factory from the private developers who would
build and own it.
   In a letter to the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, the senators said that neither the Reagan
administration nor NASA has done the studies to justify such an
expenditure. They directed the space agency to contract with the
National Academy of Sciences to ``undertake a thorough and
independent review'' to be completed by next March.
   President Reagan proposed that the government agree in advance
to lease 70 percent of the so-called Commercially Developed Space
Facility at $140 million a year for five years.
   The private facility would be carried into orbit by the space
shuttle and revisited periodically by astronauts who would service
the factory and bring back its products.
   ``The committee feels that a $700 million budget commitment,
especially in these times of severe budget constraints, should be
based on a detailed assessment of the nation's microgravity
research requirements and capabilities,'' the senators told NASA
administrator James C. Fletcher.
   The letter, dated last Thursday, was signed by the chairman of
the Senate Commerce Committee, Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C.; the
panel's ranking Republican, Sen. John Danforth of Missouri, and by
senators Donald W. Riegle, D-Mich., and Larry Pressler, R-S.C., the
chairman and ranking Republican member of the space subcommittee.
   The administration has sought the facility, which could be ready
for launch in the next decade, as an interim facility to be used
until the proposed manned space station is in orbit in the mid- to
late-1990s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
