<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HaydenProtest     05-02 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hayden Protest,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hayden Clashes With Protesters at Santa Monica Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Assemblyman Tom Hayden
confronted some South Vietnamese protesters outside his home with a
baseball bat, police said. However, a spokesman for Hayden said the
politician was carrying a bat because he was on his way to coach a
Little League baseball game.
   No injuries were reported and no arrests were made Saturday
outside the home Hayden shares with his wife, actress Jane Fonda,
said Santa Monica Police Sgt. Walter Hard. Miss Fonda, a two-time
Oscar winner, is in Mexico filming the movie ``Old Gringo,'' with
Gregory Peck and Jimmy Smits.
   About 25 people, most of them South Vietnamese, participated in
the protest, carrying signs and calling Hayden a traitor and liar,
Hard said.
   ``Some of them activated the intercom at his front gate and
began chanting into it,'' Hard said. ``It created a confrontation
between the demonstrators and Hayden, who was carrying a baseball
bat.''
   ``He came out swearing at the Vietnamese,'' said Bob Zirgulis of
the International Human Rights Watch, which organized the protest.
   ``We were completely stunned and taken aback that this
politician would go berserk. He actually went berserk,'' Zirgulis
said.
   Hayden, a baseball enthusiast, was on his way to coach a Little
League game when he met the demonstrators on the sidewalk outside
his home, his spokesman, Bill Schulz, said Sunday.
   ``He said he `chewed them out like (Los Angeles Dodgers Coach)
Tommy Lasorda would have had they been banging on his gate,'''
Schulz quoted Hayden as saying.
   Hayden's opponent in the June 7 primary, Alex Cota, was also at
the demonstration, which Hayden accused Cota of staging. Both are
Democrats. On Sunday, Schulz also termed the protest political
shenanigans.
   ``That is totally false,'' Cota responded Sunday. ``I did not
organize the demonstration at all. I came only as an observer after
I heard about the demonstration.''
   The protest was staged to coincide with the 13th anniversary of
the fall of South Vietnam to the communists, Zirgulis said. But the
group also wanted Hayden to apologize for past remarks they feel
were insulting to the Vietnamese, he added.
   Those remarks were made by Hayden in June 1987 about a
U.S.-based Vietnamese gang whom he described as a ``bully element''
involved in shootings, extortion and efforts to raise money to
overthrow the Hanoi government.
   The Santa Monica Democrat, who is seeking his fifth term in the
state Assembly, has often been a target of protests over his
anti-war activities, as has Miss Fonda.
   Hayden was one of the so-called ``Chicago 7'' who were convicted
for their role in protests during the 1968 Democratic National
Convention in Chicago. The convictions later were overturned.
   He was elected to the state legislature in 1982.
</TEXT>
