<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Snooker-Hooky,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hooky-playing Snooker Fan Fired After Being Spotted On TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Haldron played hooky so he could watch the
snooker world championships. But when he told his boss he had been
absent due to stomach pains, his boss said, ``You looked all right
on TV'' and fired him.
   The television cameras screening the event live to about 10
million viewers picked him out in the audience at the Crucible
Theater in Sheffield in northern England, the Daily Mail reported
Monday.
   Among the 10 million was Michael Mohr, managing director of
Thomas Dudley Engineering in Sedgley, 60 miles to the southwest,
who dismissed Haldron when he reported to work the next day.
   ``It never occured to me that I would be picked up by the
cameras and have my face beamed to the whole country,'' Haldron, a
27-year-old truck driver, was quoted as saying. ``I have since seen
a video of the day's snooker and saw myself as clearly as if I had
been playing.''
