<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Rebels,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eritrean Rebels Claim 222 Government Troops Killed in Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eritrean rebels said they shelled
Ethiopia's second biggest port, Massawa, and killed 222 government
troops in a battle near Asmara, the region's capital.
   In a clandestine radio broadcast monitored Sunday in Nairobi,
the Eritrean People's Liberation Front said it did not have full
details of the Massawa attack but that ``our combatants inflicted
heavy losses.''
   The radio said front guerrillas fought government troops Friday
at Bahri. The site is near Asmara, Ethiopia's second largest town,
673 miles north of the capital, Addis Ababa.
   ``During this fierce battle our combatants put out of action
about 600 Dergue (government) soldiers. These include 222 soldiers
killed and 375 wounded,'' the rebels said.
   The government rarely comments on rebel claims and there was no
other means of confirming the report.
   On April 19, rebels shelled Assab, Ethiopia's main Red Sea port
in Eritrea. Government-owned Ethiopian News Agency reported the
attack.
   Rebels seeking a separate nation in the northern province of
Eritrea have been fighting the central government in Addis Ababa
for 27 years, the longest civil war in Africa.
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam announced in March that his
government is preparing a huge offensive against the rebels, who
have captured several towns in major victories this year.
