<HEAD>65,000 Taiwanese Visited Mainland China Over Past Six Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 65,000 Taiwanese have visited
the Chinese mainland since the Nationalist government eased a
38-year-old travel ban to the mainland last October, the Interior
Ministry said Monday.
   A ministry statement said that by the end of April, another
75,000 people had received approval for making trips to mainland
through a third country.
   The Nationalists, who fled to Taiwan in 1949 after losing a
civil war to the Communists, allow people to travel to the mainland
only for family reunions. The government still bans other contacts
with China.
   Interior Minister Wu Poh-hsiung told reporters that authorities
would review the current policy over the next two months to decide
whether to further ease the restrictions on travel to China.
   Some Taiwanese have called for athletic, cultural and other
exchanges with China.
