<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-Rice     05-02 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Rice,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Asks For Aid As It Heads Into Another Year of Bad Harvests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam is asking for urgent assistance
from the West because its staple crop, rice, is being ravaged by
bad weather, disease and insects.
   Top Vietnamese government officials told representatives of
foreign embassies and relief agencies on April 14 that these same
problems had caused a shortfall of more than 1.6 million tons of
foodgrain last year.
   According to a Western diplomat who attended the meeting in
Hanoi, the Vietnamese said there was a risk of famine in some
provinces and that some villages in the northern part of the
country hadn't had rice for weeks.
   Two days before the meeting, Vietnam's official domestic radio
said the first crop of 1988 was developing poorly because of lack
of sunlight in the first three months. Twenty percent of the
cultivated area can be rated poor, Radio Hanoi said in a broadcast
monitored in Bangkok.
   The broadcast said nearly 74,130 acres were affected by insects
and diseases and 247,000 acres by root suffocation disease.
   Another 321,100 acres lacked sufficient water, and the water
level of ponds, lakes and reservoirs has dropped 6.5 to 19.5 feet
compared with previous years, it said.
   Storms and typhoons also are expected to take their annual heavy
toll on crops after the rainy season arrives in a few months.
   Communist-ruled Vietnam, one of the world's poorest nations,
annually suffers from a combination of stagnant food production and
high population growth.
   The new pragmatic leadership has stressed reforms based on
material incentives to try to boost agricultural production.
   Western relief officials interviewed last year said there were
no signs of starvation on any significant scale among the country's
63 million people, but that there was widespread and serious
malnutrition, especially among children.
   In the April 14 meeting, the Vietnamese asked for insecticide
and fertilizer which the Western diplomat estimated would cost $100
million.
   He said he doubted the international community would provide the
full amount.
   On April 26, Khmer Rouge guerrillas fighting Vietnamese troops
occupying Cambodia said the West should exploit Vietnam's food
plight by increasing pressure for a Vietnamese pullout.
   ``If aid is given ... it would be like a transfusion of fresh
blood into the body of a blood-starved Vietnam writhing in its
death throes, thus reviving it and enabling it to carry on its war
of aggression in Cambodia,'' a guerrilla radio broadcast said.
   The Khmer Rouge, the strongest of three anti-Vietnamese
guerrilla groups, massacred millions of people when it ruled
Cambodia from 1975 until 1978, when the Vietnamese invaded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
