<DOCNO> AP880502-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IndianEducation     05-02 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indian Education,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BIA Seeking Advice from Indian Parents on Upgrading Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bureau of Indian Affairs, concerned about
the weak education its schools are delivering, is asking Indians
how it should strengthen the instruction of their children.
   A new report from the bureau documenting test scores worse than
those of 79 percent of the nation's students calls on tribal school
boards, councils and others to consider an improvement strategy
emphasizing strong principals held accountable for results.
   Of the bureau districts, what it calls ``agencies,'' only one
showed children scoring above the national median for their grade.
   Tribal leaders and school boards have had access to their own
scores before. But the new report commissioned by Ross Swimmer,
assistant interior secretary for Indian affairs, provides the first
opportunity for one tribe or area to compare its standing with
another, said an Interior Department official who discussed the
document on condition of anonymity.
   The authors conceded that it will be difficult to install new
leaders and revitalizing a system that appears too often to be
going through the motions.
   Calling the system ``in dire need of improvment,'' the report
said: ``It is no secret that BIA education is today an organization
lacking in a sense of direction.''
   ``Its most productive members often feel that any successes they
achieve occur despite the system, rather than with its support.
   ``Collegiality, the act of putting aside vested interests and
working for the good of the whole, is found in America's best
educational institutions but is often missing in the BIA system,
where administrators are sometimes more interested in shoring up
and expanding their administrative domain.''
   Drawing on research findings being promoted by the Department of
Education, the report said:
   ``It is the principal above all who needs to insist on high
standards of achievement for students and teachers and to
communicate the firm expectation that these standards will be met.
Some BIA teachers seem to begin with the expectation that their
students will do poorly.''
   The bureau educates 37,917 Indian students, about 10 percent of
the nation's young Indians and about as many pupils as the public
schools of Oklahoma City, Okla. or Corpus Christi, Texas. About 30
percent attend boarding schools and about 30 percent are in schools
run by tribes under contract with the bureau.
   Few of the students even approached national averages on
standard tests administered in the 1985-1986 school year.
   The highest scores appeared in New Mexico's Northern Pueblo
agency, where 27 second-graders averaged in the 52nd percentile.
This means they did better than 52 percent of all students taking
the test.
   The Laguna agency, also in New Mexico, showed an average in the
46th percentile for its 63 second-graders, and schools not
affiliated with an agency in the eastern states showed 73
sixth-graders in the 49th percentile.
   The worst scores were recorded in the Chinle district of
Arizona, where 202 fourth-graders and 154 fifth-graders, mostly
from rural Navajo families, wound up in the 7th percentile.
   The report highlights some success stories but says the system
needs a systematic way of spreading knowledge of successes to other
areas.
   For instance, the Dilcon and Chuska boarding schools for Navajo
in the Fort Defiance, Ariz., district use a special curriculum
requiring students to write something every day. Their
eighth-graders do well, with Dilcon's two months ahead of the
national average and Chuska's a year above the bureau average,
though a year behind the nation.
   Because of the isolation of the schools, administrative demands,
pay falling behind the public schools and other reasons, the bureau
system has an annual turnover rate of 33 percent per year among
principals and 20 percent among all professionals.
   Among other recommendations, the report calls for consideration
of education loans for prospective teachers, with a larger fraction
forgiven the longer the teacher stays in the system; for recruiting
retired people with valuable knowledge who might like a second
career; and for easing the requirement that Indians be given
preference as principals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
