<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArmsSales 1stLd-Writethru a0490 05-02 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Arms Sales Could Rise $3.3 Billion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with the State calls report
misleading; picks up 3rd graf, `The request...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. arms sales abroad could jump by $3.3
billion, to more than $15 billion this year, with much of the
increase going to the Middle East, The New York Times reported
today.
   But State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the Times
report was misleading because a confidential report on which the
story was based does not reflect anticipated sales. He said it
considers only sales which are ``eligible'' for approval during the
calendar year.
   Since U.S. law requires inclusion of all sales that might be
approved, many of which will not take place, ``it would be wrong to
characterize the report in any way as a sales plan or to attribute
any significance to changes in dollar amounts from one year to
another,'' Redman said.
   The report cited by the Times, sent by the State Department to
Congress, lists potential sales to 33 countries. Israel would get
$3.6 billion worth of arms and Egypt $2.7 billion, the Times said.
   The request gives more attention to the Persian Gulf region than
requests of previous years, with the Reagan administration asking
for advanced arms and equipment for Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain
and the United Arab Emirates to counter threats from Iran, the
newspaper said.
   Elsewhere, one of the biggest possible purchasers is South
Korea, with a potential $3.3 billion in arms, the report said.
   The president is required to submit an arms sale proposal to
Congress each year, but the master list has rarely become public.
   In the last fiscal year, the United States delivered $11.7
billion in military equipment and services to foreign governments
and $2 billion more was sold directly by manufacturers, according
to the Defense Department. Arms sales abroad peaked in 1982 at
$17.7 billion.
   Egypt was the biggest gainer this year, having bought $378
million last year, the Times said. Most of that was in tanks, it
said.
   Israel would receive nearly $2.8 million worth of helicopters
and F-16 jet fighters under the proposal, the newspaper said.
   Pakistan is listed as a potential buyer of $797 million in
equipment this year, compared with $138 million last year.
   Military sales to the Philippines would decline to $45 million
from $108 million, according to the Times.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
