<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--CommemorativeCoins     05-02 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Commemorative Coins,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary Strikes 1988 Olympic Commemorative Coins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III on Monday
struck the first 1988 U.S. Olympic coins during a ceremony at the
Denver Mint. The coins commemorate U.S. athletes' participation in
the 1988 Olympic Games.
   Sales of the $5 gold and $1 silver coins are expected to raise
$49 million, which will be sent to the U.S. Olympic Committee to
train present and future Olympians. The gold coins will sell for
$35, and the silver coins for $7.
   Congress has authorized the minting of a million gold coins and
10 million silver coins as keepsakes of the 1988 Olympics.
   Other dignitaries besides Baker present at the ceremony included
Katherine D. Orteza, the U.S. treasurer; Donna Pope, director of
the Mint, and several past and present U.S. Olympians.
   The coins will be available in mid-August at retail stores, coin
and precious metals dealers and participating banks and financial
institutions.
</TEXT>
