<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FamousDakotans Bjt   05-02 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Famous Dakotans, Bjt,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hall Of Fame To Feature Famous North Dakotans</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE WETZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It has Angie Dickinson scripts, a Bobby
Vee sweater and a replica of the bubble machine that became a
trademark of bandleader Lawrence Welk. But the North Dakota Hall of
Fame, despite years of effort, is still short of the money it needs
to display its exhibits to the public.
   The hall, conceived as a way of recognizing prominent North
Dakotans in fields of endeavor ranging from dairy production to
sportswriting, resembles nothing so much as the cluttered attic of
an eccentric relative.
   It takes up most of a columned office building north of the
state Capitol, but it's not officially open and a visitor is
greeted by an expanse of empty floor space.
   Piles of logs, stacks of bricks and bags of dried leaves rest in
one corner. A potbellied iron stove stands near an old-fashioned
white porcelain sink.
   A 1950s-style malt shop booth and five Welk bandstands, painted
with the Strasburg native's ``LW'' script, sit incongruously in the
center of the main display floor.
   Most of the Hall of Fame's possessions are locked in eight small
rooms, from plaques to books to a mannequin dressed in the uniform
of former Minnesota Vikings standout Dave Osborn. A life-size
cutout of Welk, holding his conductor's baton, stands next to the
football player.
   The white-suited Welk likeness was once stationed on the main
floor, said Jim Kennedy, the hall's executive director. But it was
moved into a room ``because when I'd come in here, (if) it was a
bit dark, he'd kind of startle me,'' Kennedy said. ``It is pretty
realistic looking.''
   Also stashed away are a number of wax dummies, some dressed in
Indian garb, that once were the property of the defunct Great
Plains Museum near Mandan.
   Kennedy and Gary Pearson, a broadcast executive who first
thought of the hall of fame idea five years ago, concede its
development has been slower than expected.
   But Pearson, who has been meeting recently with a number of
non-profit groups in an attempt to obtain contributions, said he
remained optimistic.
   ``We're continuing to move ... except it's taking us a little
bit longer than we thought,'' Pearson said. ``At this point, we
need to work harder at it. We have been.''
   The hall has been adept at publicity, organizing high-profile
North Dakota appearances by Miss Dickinson _ a native of Kulm,
south of Jamestown _ and former CBS News commentator Eric Sevareid,
who was born in Velva, several miles southeast of Minot.
   But promoters have been unable to translate the exposure into
enough money to put the hall into shape. Pearson estimates it will
take $200,000 to $250,000 to organize and staff it for a year.
   So far, the hall has raised $10,000 through a car raffle and a
small sum from selling memberships, said Kennedy.
   ``We don't have very much (money) at all,'' Kennedy said last
week. ``We're just squeaking.''
   Once the hall is set up, Pearson believes it could draw as many
as 90,000 people annually, paying a $2 entrance fee, he said. That
is roughly half the number of vistors that the nearby state
Heritage Center draws each year, he said.
   ``We're not looking at any gigantic amount of money,'' Pearson
said.
   Celebrities such as Miss Dickinson, Welk, Sevareid and pop
singer Vee, who grew up in Fargo, are the highlights of the hall,
Kennedy said. However, its primary goal is to spotlight North
Dakota groups such as the Boy Scouts, civic club dignitaries and
sporting organizations.
   The celebrities ``hopefully are what will make people come in
off the interstate,'' Kennedy said. ``Once they're here, they can
enjoy the rest of it ....
   ``Not too many are going to pull in just to see who the North
Dakota water user of the year is.''
</TEXT>
