<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IMF-Trade     05-02 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IMF-Trade,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boom in US Exports, Japanese Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. exports and Japanese imports both boomed
last year, while the United States slowed the pace of its buying
abroad and Japanese sales actually declined, the International
Monetary Fund reported Monday.
   But the United States still bought $173.7 billion worth of goods
more than it sold, up from $169.8 billion the year before.
   Japan's surplus dropped to $80.4 billion from $83.2 billion in
1986.
   Dollar figures reflect the drop in the value of the U.S.
currency in terms of the yen as well as the actual amount of the
goods traded. This drop reduces the value of foreign sales and
increases the cost of imports. In Japan and West Germany, the
effect is the opposite: imports are cheaper and sales bring in less
money, in terms of dollars.
   The drop of the dollar was so large that it outweighed the
increase of U.S. exports in the final balance. At the end of March,
the dollar was worth 8.65 percent less than it was 12 months
earlier, the fund calculates.
   In terms of actual goods sold, U.S. exports rose 13.2 percent
for the year, against only 1 percent in 1986. Imports still grew by
2.2 percent but that was much less than the 10.9 percent of the
year before.
   Japanese imports rose by 6.1 percent in the first nine months of
1987, a considerable increase though less than the 12.8 percent of
1986. Exports dropped by 2.4 percent, more than double the 1
percent of 1986.
   The fund calls these ``real adjustments in trade patterns.'' But
it notes that trade remains way out of balance.
   West Germany raised its imports by 5.2. percent _ somewhat less
than the 5.9 percent increase the previous year. But it also
increased its foreign sales by 2.8 percent, considerably more than
the 0.9 percent rise in 1986.
   The Germans increased their trade surplus to $65.8 billion in
1987 from $52.2 billion a year earlier.
   Taken as a whole, the 21 countries that the fund calls
``industrial'' bought more than they sold to poorer areas: $85.4
billion worth, up from $66.1 billion in 1986. Neither the Soviet
Union nor any other country with a communust government is included
in this category.
   For poorer countries, the fund's monthly ``IMF Memorandum''
emphasized the rise in prices paid by consumers.
   ``Inflation rose sharply in the developing countries in 1987,
led by a sharp acceleration of inflation in the Western
Hemisphere,'' it reported.
   In the Americas, the rise was 118.8 percent, up from 82.2 in
1986, but still below the 161.4 rise in 1985.
   The Third World's three biggest debtors also had the biggest
price rises: 229.7 percent in Brazil, 131.8 percent in Mexico and
131.3 percent in Argentina.
   For the fund's 130 poor countries, inflation was put at 40.1
percent, compared with 29.3 percent in 1986. The rise was moderated
by the record in Asia, where the rate was held to 6.9 percent, up
from only 5.4 percent in a year.
</TEXT>
