5th graf, `Agents posing ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive suspected in a two-year crime spree
that included bank robberies and a shootout with police has been
tracked down through his fascination with high-performance cars.
   Forty FBI agents staked out an auto show at Hershey, Pa., and
arrested Ray Allen Minnick, a convicted bank robber accused in a
series of crimes in the Baltimore area. He was armed but was
arrested without incident Saturday.
   In Harrisburg, Pa., U.S. Magistrate J. Andrew Smyzer today
scheduled a preliminary hearing and bail hearing Thursday morning
for Minnick.
   FBI agent Joseph V. Corless said Minnick's arrest was based in
part on a profile that reflected Minnick's interest in race cars
and his habit of frequenting automotive flea markets. Agents also
received a tip that Minnick would be at the show, but would not say
where it came from.
   Agents posing as gate attendants at the auto show spotted
Minnick when he entered and identified him from an ``X'' tattoo on
his left hand, Corless said.
   He was carrying two concealed handguns and $15,000, Corless
said. A search of his car turned up more weapons, including a fully
loaded machine gun with five loaded magazines, a shotgun, a couple
of switchblade knives and a machete.
   FBI agents had been trying to apprehend Minnick, 40, since
February 1986, when he escaped from Howard County after his alleged
involvement in an armed holdup of a supermarket and a shootout with
Howard County police, the FBI said.
   He is suspected in at least eight robberies of banks and savings
and loans in the Baltimore area and is wanted in connection with
other robberies in Maryland and Pennsylvania, the FBI said.
   The FBI first investigated Minnick in 1972 for the armed robbery
of the First National Bank of Columbia. He was convicted and was
sentenced to 20 years in prison, and was paroled in 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
