<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-02 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NENZEL, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crossbreeding between prairie chickens and
grouse is common, but one prairie chicken has taken things a step
further by courting a brown pickup truck as the object of his
affections.
   He arrived at the J.B. and Pat Fischer ranch 23 miles south of
here in late March and has stayed, probably hoping he can convince
the pickup to agree to a mixed marriage of sorts.
   ``He likes my pickup,'' Fischer said. ``He runs toward it
whenever I drive across the meadow, stamps his feet and performs
his ritual for me. I have seen a few grouse near where he stays,
but he tends to ignore them.''
   Prairie chickens ``boom'' and grouse ``dance'' as they gather
for their spring courtship rituals, which are common to both
species and are similar. Prairie chickens inflate large orange air
sacs on their neck, erect tufts of neck feathers and produce a deep
resonant ``boom'' that can be heard for nearly a mile in calm
weather.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WOODLAND PARK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the halls of Woodland Park
Junior High became a little too gnarly for Principal Charles
Lutgen, he thought it was time students gave him a lesson in the
slang of the day.
   ``I'd hear things,'' he said, ``and I'd think, gosh, is that
good or bad or indifferent?''
   The principal found his answer in ``Slang Struck: A Handbook for
Parents To Better Understand What We're Talking About,'' a
137-word, student-compiled guide.
   The idea for the handbook came from English teacher Lynn
Heintzman. Encouraged by the principal, she tacked a piece of
poster board on the classroom wall and invited students to write in
and ``keep it clean.''
   Included in the handbook are such terms as babe (nice-looking);
stud muffin (nice-looking male); majorly (very, very important);
sweetness (special); and gnarly (cool).
   But the new handbook is in danger of obsolescence already. Some
of the words in ``Slang Struck'' already have different meanings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Alaska Airlines Eskimo is getting a
``cooler'' look for what company officials hope will be a hot
marketing campaign.
   Sunglasses are being added to the popular logo on the tails of
jets serving California routes, company officials announced Sunday.
Flight crews and ground workers also are to wear shades until the
promotion ends in late June.
   ``We are emphasizing our interest and commitment to California
and having a little fun while we do it,'' said Bill McKnight, vice
president of marketing.
   Since 1979, when Alaska added three flights to San Francisco,
the company has grown to one of the major carriers along the West
Coast with 105 flights a day from 10 California airports.
   The Eskimo logo seemed an endangered species earlier this year
after a new, stylized emblem was designed as a potential
replacement, but howls of protest from Fairbanks to San Diego put
that idea on ice.
</TEXT>
