<DOCNO> AP880502-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NewCaledonia     05-02 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Caledonia,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Militants Reject Offer To Trade Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Melanesian separatists rejected an
offer Monday by three rightist elected officials to trade places
with nearly two dozen police hostages being held in a cave.
   Dick Ukeiwe, who represents this French Pacific island territory
in the French Senate, announced at a meeting of New Caledonia's new
regional assembly that he and two National Assembly members,
Jacques Lafleur and Maurice Nenou, wished to ``take the place of
the hostages to bring an end to their ordeal.''
   Bernard Pons, minister for overseas territories in Premier
Jacques Chirac's conservative government, praised the offer and
said it could bring movement in the stalemated hostage drama.
   Noumea Mayor Jean Leques ordered all offices, shops, schools and
bars closed at 4 p.m. in support of the idea. Even taxi drivers
stopped work in the capital, a stronghold of pro-French,
anti-independence sentiment.
   But the Kanak Socialist National Liberation Front rejected the
offer and repeated its demand for a mediator to negotiate terms for
a referendum on independence for the Pacific island territory.
   ``We want someone who would be representative of the colonial
power, who would have authority to commit the colonial power,''
Hnalaine Uregei, a member of the front's political bureau, told a
news conference.
   He said the proposal from the three officials was ``at the same
time grotesque, ridiculous and indecent'' and said they knew it
would not be taken seriously.
   New Caledonia has become an issue in next Sunday's presidential
election between Socialist President Francois Mitterrand, who urges
dialogue with the separatists, and Chirac, who calls them a small
band of terrorists.
   A recent opinion poll in France found 41 percent in favor of
independence for the territory, 34 percent opposed and 25 percent
giving no opinion. But among those who voted for Chirac in the
first round April 24, only 24 percent back independence and 58
percent want to keep New Caledonia part of France.
   Ukeiwe, Lafleur and Nenou are members of Chirac's rightist
party, the Rally for the Republic, and are prominent opponents of
the separatist movement.
   About 43 percent of New Caledonia's 145,000 people are native
Melanesians, known as Kanaks, and many of them favor independence.
About 36 percent are Europeans, who generally want to remain part
of France. The rest are mostly Asian or Polynesian.
   On April 22, the rebels raided a rural police post on the island
of Ouvea, seized 27 military policemen and killed four others. They
released 12 hostages but took eight more, including the head of an
anti-terrorism squad and an assistant prosecutor.
   The remaining hostages are being held in a cave in a remote part
of Ouvea, which lies off the east coast of New Caledonia's main
island, La Grande Terre.
   The prosecutor and the anti-terrorism squad leader were allowed
to leave the cave hideout and ordered to negotiate on behalf of the
terrorists, but were old the remaining hostages would be killed if
the two did not return. Because of that threat, authorities still
consider them hostages for a total of 23.
   The front, which calls the 23 ``prisoners of war,'' said in a
statement Monday that they were ``in good health and well
cared-for.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
