<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietJews     05-02 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Jews,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Jewish Conference Schedules Pre-Summit Vigil in Helsinki</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Jewish leaders said Monday they will
hold a religious service and a vigil in Helsinki, Finland, before
the Moscow summit as a way of drawing attention to the plight of
Soviet Jews.
   The events, organized by the National Conference on Soviet
Jewry, will take place May 27-28 while President Reagan is in
Finland.
   Reagan, who is scheduled to fly to Moscow on May 29 for the
three-day summit with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, has been
invited to the Friday night service at the Helsinki synagogue.
Organizers said they did not know if he would attend.
   Morris B. Abram, chairman of the national conference, told
reporters the activities in Helsinki are designed to impress upon
Soviet leaders the conference's commitment to seeing Soviet Jews
accorded more freedom.
   He said his group will continue the campaign ``to free Soviet
Jewry so they can emigrate ... and to permit those who wish to
remain to live as Jews without any limitations and without any
discrimination against them.''
   The conference estimates that as many as 400,000 Jews are
seeking to leave the Soviet Union, but have been denied exit
permits. There are more than 2 million Jews in the Soviet Union,
which has about one-fifth of the world's Jewish population.
   Jews have been persecuted for practicing their faith in the
state-controlled society and are often discriminated against.
   Soviet Jews are planning an event in Moscow during the summit,
but conference officials refused to provide details, fearing
organizers might be subjected to harassment by Soviet officials.
   When Gorbachev visited Washington for a summit last December,
supporters of Soviet Jews staged a massive demonstration near the
White House. Vice President George Bush attended that rally.
   Abram and Richard Maass, head of the conference's Moscow task
force, also said they want the Soviet Union to abide by the 1975
Helsinki Final Act that proclaimed that people have a right to
leave a country freely.
   Gorbachev and other Soviet officials have voiced irritation at
the attention the United States focuses on human rights. In recent
speeches Reagan has urged the Soviets to allow more freedom of
speech and religion, and his aides say he will revisit that subject
in a talk Wednesday in Chicago.
   The conference will hold a day-long ``Summit Action Day for
Soviet Jews'' Tuesday in Washington, where Secretary of State
George P. Shultz is to speak.
   Also attending will be Joseph Begun, a mathematician who was
allowed to emigrate in January after spending many years in Soviet
labor camps.
   The American Jews say that under Gorbachev, the treatment of
Soviet Jews has been mixed. On the one hand, there has been some
improvement in cultural life, such as the creation of a Hebrew
study group in one region.
   But the number of Jews allowed to emigrate is still a trickle
compared with the 1970s, and some emigration laws have been
tightened.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0129 </DOCNO>
