<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People 1stLd-Writethru a0638 05-02 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0638,0725</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lead of 2nd item, with New York datelione, about
Frank Perdue.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some sour notes came from the Detroit Symphony
Orchestra's conductor over the weekend.
   Gunther Herbig, the orchestra's conductor since 1984, told
musicians during intermission of Saturday night's concert that he
plans to quit, the Detroit News reported Monday. Several musicians
told the newspaper that Herbig cited several complaints, many of
them related to the orchestra's financial troubles. On Sunday, he
declined to discuss his resignation, effective when his contract
expires in 1990.
   ``Herbig told us that virtually the only thing they honored in
the contract was payment, and that even that was sometimes late,''
said Maxim Janowsky, a bassist with the orchestra.
   Orchestra board Chairman Walter J. McCarthy Jr. said the
orchestra's financial troubles caused the board to fail to meet
some terms, but it was the board's ``intention and hope to honor
Maestro Herbig's contract in every detail.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicken magnate Frank Perdue's three-year
marriage has come to an end.
   Frank Perdue and Kathleen Markey Perdue were divorced last week
in Salisbury, Md., a spokesman for Mrs. Perdue's lawyer said Monday.
   The terms of the divorce were not divulged, but Mrs. Perdue's
lawyer, Marvin Mitchelson, characterized thesplit as ``very
amicable,'' said the spokesman, Sy Presten.
   The marriage on May 4, 1985, had been the first for Mrs. Perdue,
38, a former vice president of Salomon Brothers, the Wall Street
firm.
   Perdue, 67, whose chicken business is headquartered in
Salisbury, had been married once before.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Muhammad Ali's manager says it was a ``big
misunderstanding'' that caused police to issue a bulletin that the
former heavyweight boxing champion was missing.
   Ali left his hotel room Sunday morning for a walk and a hotel
clerk, fearing he might not be able to take care of himself, phoned
police.
   Soon after, Ali was seen walking peacefully along the street.
   ``I wasn't worried about him,'' said his manager, Avudi Mahdi.
``I didn't even get out of bed when the hotel staff called me. I
told them Ali can take care of himself.''
   In 1984, Ali checked into a New York hospital complaining of
symptoms similar to Parkinson's disease.
   He was in the city for a fund-raising dinner for Rep. Joe
Kennedy of Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Papandreou, the American-born
wife of Greece's socialist premier, is calling for the
establishment of a Women's Peace Institute to promote disarmament.
   She made the call Monday came after chairing a three-day
conference aboard a Greek cruise ship for members of Women for a
Meaningful Summit.
   ``The world's true enemies are hunger, disease, racism, poverty,
inequality violence and not other nations and other peoples,'' Mrs.
Papandreou told a news conference. ``This institute would carry out
research on issues of world peace.''
   Mrs. Papandreou said the institute should be financed by a
percentage of both NATO and Warsaw Pact military budgets.
   More than 40 women from 14 countries cruised around the Saronic
Gulf islands. The Soviet Union, Bulgaria and Czechoslovakia were
among the nations sending delegations. Coretta Scott King, wife of
the late civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr., led the
16-member U.S. delegation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The practice of pediatrics today should
include pressing for better day care and schools, Dr. Benjamin
Spock said Monday as he celebrated his 85th birthday at Creighton
University's Center for Healthy Aging.
   ``The first job for pediatricians today should be to go around
stirring things up ... to make a better life for all our
children,'' Spock said.
   Medicine has eradicated many of the childhood diseases, but has
done ``almost nothing on issues really crucial to the child,'' he
said.
   Spock called the weakening of the extended family ``a great
mistake.''
   ``Many people consider it a curse if they have an older person
living with them,'' he said. ``It's a great help to live in an
extended family'' with a built-in babysitter or consultant on baby
matters.
   ``Young people do owe it to their parents ... to provide for
them,'' he said. ``We're very neglectful of the old.''
</TEXT>
