<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-SEC     05-02 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-SEC,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Spur SEC To Move on Tougher Corporate Accounting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a congressional committee scolded
the chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission on Monday
for failing to require that companies establish tougher auditing
procedures.
   Such a recommendation was among several made last October by a
private task force headed by former SEC Commissioner James Treadway.
   The Treadway Commission proposed that the SEC require publicly
traded companies to have independent audit committees, composed of
people from outside the corporation, to double-check financial
statements. The New York Stock Exchange already requires companies
it lists to have such committees.
   The SEC, however, has decided to only urge the nation's
financial markets and other industry groups that oversee securities
trading to ``consider upgrading and expanding the scope of their
standards with respect to audit committees,'' SEC Chairman David S.
Ruder told the House Energy and Commerce oversight and
investigations subcommittee.
   Subcommittee Chairman John D. Dingell, D-Mich., noted that the
Treadway Commission had concluded that fraudulent financial
reporting was a major problem and should be addressed by the
government.
   ``Somebody's got to do something to see to it that we have
confidence in our system ...,'' Dingell told Ruder. ``One of the
reasons the (Securities and Exchange) Commission is drawing pay is
to do that.''
   Another subcommittee member, Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said he was
``amazed'' that the SEC ``plans to pass the buck to others.''
   Ruder said SEC officials were wary of imposing the requirement
because of a fear that it would be too costly for small businesses.
   However, he added there had been ``strong disagreement'' among
the SEC's commissioners over implementing the proposal. He said he
himself favored the idea and believed that a mechanism could be
worked out to reduce the burden on small companies.
</TEXT>
