<2ND_LINE>PM-Guantanamo Wreck, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driver Charged After Crash On U.S. Navy Base Kills Six, Injures
Four</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to update with names of victims. Picks up
7th graf pvs ``A base security ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GUANTANAMO, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manslaughter charges have been filed
against the driver of a car that smashed into a U.S. Navy van at
the Navy base here, killing five sailors and their driver and
injuringfour people, officials say.
   The car was speeding on the base's main road when the fiery
wreck occurred Saturday night, base spokesman Lt. Bob Hines said
Sunday. All those killed were in the van, which was more heavily
damaged by fire than by the car, Hines said.
   Lt. Russ Greer, a spokesman at Atlantic Fleet headquarters in
Norfolk, Va., identified the five sailors killed as Seaman Recruit
Michael W. Bauman of Clovis, N.M.; Storekeeper-Seaman Brent D.
Jervey of Gainesville, Fla.; Boatswain's Mate 1st Class John F.
Piper of Monongahela, Pa.; Seaman Jeffrey M. Rais, of Cincinnati;
and Petty Officer 1st Class Frederick W. Vilmar of Saginaw, Mich.
   Greer said three injured sailors were evacuated in serious
condition to the Brooke Army Burn Center in San Antonio, Texas.
   He identified them as Aircraft Storekeeper Recruit Demetric L.
Cofield of Harrisburg, Pa.; Ship's Serviceman Prentice D. Johnson
of Indianapolis; and Fireman Darren Stevenson of Chester, Pa.
   Greer said the ages of the victims were not immediately
available, nor were the names of the driver of the car or of the
civilian Navy employee who was driving the van.
   The private car's driver, who is not a U.S. citizen, was charged
with six counts of manslaughter and was under guard at the base
hospital in Guantanamo, where he was listed in stable condition,
according to Lt. Cmdr. Aaron Long, another Atlantic Fleet spokesman
in Norfolk.
   A base security vehicle observed the car speeding about 1{ miles
before it crashed into the taxi van, which was operated by the
base's retail exchange, Long said. The security vehicle followed
the car but could go no faster than 40 mph, he said.
   ``The vehicle outran the naval station vehicle,'' but the
accident was not a result of ``hot pursuit,'' he said. ``The
security vehicle did not see the accident occur.''
   Long said the speed limit on the base is 25 mph.
   About 7,000 people, including military personnel and civilian
workers, live on the base at the southeastern tip of communist
Cuba. The facility, which is enclosed and surrounded by a
minefield, serves as the main training site for the Atlantic Fleet.
</TEXT>
