<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1540EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ThirdWorld-Women     05-02 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Third World-Women,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Not Enough AID Money Going to Third World Women, Studies Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agency for International Development
doesn't pay enough attention to women in the Third World, despite
their roles in farming and other areas of commerce, two studies say.
   Reacting to the independent studies, members of Congress have
introduced a bill they say would redress the situation by requiring
the AID office that oversees women in developing nations to spend
$10 million annually. Last year the office spent about $2 million.
   The bill _ introduced by Democratic Reps. Mickey Leland of Texas
and Pat Schroeder of Colorado in one chamber and Sen. Barbara
Mikulski of Maryland in the other _ also would order AID to place
women in 50 percent of positions in training programs abroad.
   ``Much has been said and written about incorporating women in
development efforts, but far too little has been done,'' Schroeder
and Leland said in a joint letter to colleagues.
   The bill, which has 89 co-sponsors in the House, is being
promoted by Bread for the World, a Christian group that lobbies
against hunger and poverty.
   That group plans a letter-writing campaign to encourage AID to
increase benefits given to women in developing countries, said
president Art Simon, the brother of Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill.
   AID opposes the bill, even though Alan Woods, the agency's new
director, is ``committed to AID's efforts to integrate women into
developing economies,'' spokesman Jerry Lipson said.
   Although the agency believes more needs to be done for women in
developing countries, the legislation would create an additional
layer of bureaucracy and cut down on AID's flexibility, he said.
   Agency officials think the legislation is like ``using an
elephant to deal with a fly,'' he said.
   Moreover, he said that while Americans recognize the importance
of women in the Third World, AID officials sometimes run into
roadblocks in developing countries where women frequently have
inferior status.
   What prompted congressional interest were two independent
studies _ commissioned by AID and completed in 1987 _ that said AID
programs often are inattentive to women.
   ``AID's women in development policy is not being implemented
fully or vigorously, and there is little enthusiasm and few
incentives for doing so,'' Development Associates Inc., a
consulting group, wrote in a December report.
   Unless there is agency-wide acceptance of the policy of
incorporating women, it will be ``marginally useful at best,'' the
study said.
   While lip-service is given to the importance of women's roles in
development, the policy is not a ``serious concern'' for many AID
managers, the study said.
   Numerous studies have demonstrated the vital role women play in
a developing nation's economy.
   In Africa, for instace, it is estimated that women are
responsible for growing more than 80 percent of the food consumed
in the home.
   Case studies in Botswana, Kenya and the Caribbean, for example,
show that when there is widespread male migration, women's earnings
are the mainstay for subsistence expenditures.
   Women also play a large role in informal commerce, serving as
traders and merchants in countries like Nigeria and Ghana. In a
community in Bolivia, women's earning from handicrafts tided
families over during a drought.
   The failure to take women into account can undermine some
development projects, according to a report written by Alice
Carloni for AID in April 1987.
   The Botswana Agricultural College Expansion project was rated
highly successful in developing an agricultural training
institution.
   But the project may not ultimately improve the lives of farm
families if the extension service continues to bypass female
farmers who play a major role in agriculture, the study said.
   In another project in Nepal, architects focused too narrowly on
the domestic role women play, the study said. The women were taught
to use a different type of stove designed to reduce deforestation,
but were not educated on broader conservation topics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
