<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     05-02 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Appoints Moderates To Head Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo replaced the
head of the governing party with a moderate Monday and was expected
to reshuffle his Cabinet after the opposition took control of the
National Assembly.
   In a speech Monday, Roh adopted a conciliatory attitude to the
opposition, which won parliamentary elections April 26.
   Government officials said Roh would reshuffle his Cabinet and
replace rightists with moderates.
   ``Hardliners and those with military background are not
considered for nomination,'' said one source, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   Police, meanwhile, stopped opposition activists from circulating
a petition calling for an investigation of former President Chun
Doo-hwan.
   Roh nominated moderate Yun Gil-jung, 71, to head the Democratic
Justice Party and replce Chae Moon-shik. Other senior party
officials appointed later in the day were all moderates.
   Opposition candidates made a surprisingly strong showing in the
National Assembly elections, depriving the Roh's party of its
majority for the first time in South Korea's 40-year history.
   ``We lost the elections but we have not lost our fair and just
attitude. We have no regrets about holding fair elections,'' Roh
told a meeting of party officials.
   Roh said the opposition-dominated National Assembly would pose a
serious problem but his party should tackle it under the principle
of ``dialogue and compromise.''
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung, whose Party for Peace and
Democracy emerged as the largest opposition party, on Monday called
for a parliamentary investigation into past wrongdoings under
ex-President Chun.
   Kim, 62, demanded that the National Assembly probe alleged
corruption involving Chun and and his family and a 1980
anti-government uprising in the southern city of Kwangju, during
which nearly 200 people were killed.
   But Kim said the investigation could be delayed if it would
affect a successful staging of the Olympic Games in Seoul in
September.
   Chun, whose term ended Feb. 24, has come under fire for alleged
involvement in large-scale financial scandals. His younger brother,
Chun Kyung-hwan, was arrested in March on charges of embezzling
official funds.
   Opposition politicians are pushing a petition drive to collect 1
million signatures to demand the former president be subpoenaed for
investigation. About 300,000 signatures have been collected, they
said.
   But police Monday banned collection of signatures in the streets
for the petition. No official reason was given for the action.
   Kim said he would support a probe of Chun's alleged financial
wrongdoings but opposed putting him on trial because he was a
president.
   Aides said Kim would once again be appointed to lead his party
at a convention scheduled for Saturday. He resigned the party
presidency two months ago to help unite the divided opposition.
   Kim Dae-jung emerged from the elections in a far stronger
postion than rival opposition leader Kim Young-sam. Both Kims ran
for president against Roh and split the opposition ticket, allowing
Roh to win.
</TEXT>
