<2ND_LINE>AM-Minnesota Delegates,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Edges Jackson in Minnesota District Conventions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE LAHAMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis edged rival Jesse Jackson in Minnesota's seven
congressional district conventions with the Massachusetts governor
collecting a larger share of national delegates.
   Dukakis captured 19 delegates at the weekend conventions,
Jackson picked up 14 and eight were uncommitted. Illinois Sen. Paul
Simon, who has suspended his presidential campaign, won two
delegates to the Democratic National Convention, scheduled July
18-21 in Atlanta.
   Eight delegates at stake in the eighth congressional district
will be chosen next weekend, and the remaining 27 delegates will be
picked at the state convention on June 12.
   Minnesota also has nine ``super delegates,'' including former
Vice President Walter Mondale.
   Both Dukakis and Jackson fared better than their vote totals in
the presidential preference poll taken Feb. 23 at the precinct
caucuses, where Dukakis got 33.5 percent and Jackson had 19.9
percent. The two candidates also improved on their strategists'
expectations.
   ``The major thing we're seeing in congressional district after
congressional district, is undecideds largely coming to Dukakis,''
said a jubilant Gary Cerkvenik, state coordinator for Dukakis.
Cerkvenik had predicted that Dukakis would win 13 to 15 delegates.
   ``We're broadening our base; it's a long election process,''
said Scott Adams, a spokesman for the Jackson campaign which
expected its candidate to capture 12 or 13 delegates.
   All told in Minnesota, Dukakis has 32 delegates, Jackson 24 and
Simon two. Twenty delegates remain uncommitted, according to The
Associated Press count.
   On the Republican side, Vice President George Bush, who has a
mathematical lock on the nomination, added one delegate to his
total of four and former television evangelist Pat Robertson picked
up two delegates. Five of the 12 delegates picked at this stage of
the GOP process remain uncommitted.
   Minnesota Republicans choose another 12 delegates this weekend
at four congressional district conventions. The final seven members
of the state's 31 delegates will be selected at the state
convention June 16-18.
</TEXT>
