<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bennett     05-02 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bennett,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Education Secretary Strikes Back At Critics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary William Bennett struck
back Monday at critics who charge he is too negative about the
nation's educational system, saying it has not made sufficient
progress in the last five years.
   Bennett said he gave ``a fair amount of praise'' to improvements
in a report issued last week on the fifth anniversary of ``A Nation
at Risk,'' the devastating analysis issued by his predecessor,
Terrel Bell.
   ``We can show some progress since 1983,'' Bennett said in a
speech to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``Despite that progress, I
cannot come candidly before the American people and say that
everything's great.''
   Bennett said the five-year update, ``American Education: Making
it Work,'' had provoked a firestorm of criticism although ``no one
has challenged any facts in it.''
   In the report, released last week, Bennett said progress has
been too slow and ``we are still at risk.''
   He told the Chamber of Commerce that the ``educational
establishment'' gave him grades of C's and D's on the report, but
``I don't give a tinker's damn what they give me as long as they
get to work improving American education.''
   Bennett said fewer than 2 percent of American students can write
a clear, detailed, coherent narrative and only 3 percent of high
school seniors scored above 600 on their verbal SATs last year.
   He said middle-class kids usually can survive the decline of an
education system but lower-class children end up losing their only
chance for a better life.
   ``So if I seem a bit edgy at times about improving our education
system, there's a good reason,'' he said.
   Bennett told the audience they should go to see the film ``Stand
and Deliver'' for an example of how American education can be made
to succeed without huge infusions of cash.
   The movie, based on the true story of Jaime Escalante, is about
an East Los Angeles calculus teacher who tames a class of inner
city Hispanic teen-agers through force of personality. The kids end
up learning calculus and going to college.
   Bennett, often at odds with teachers' groups, said Escalante had
never been nominated by anyone for a teacher-of-the-year award.
``Why?'' he asked. ``Because he's an embarrassment. He proves you
can do it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
