<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Trade     05-02 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Trade,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Plant-Closings Provision of Trade Bill a Sure Loser</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan vowed anew Monday to veto a
major revision of trade laws and said a controversial provision
requiring advance notification of plant closings was ``like playing
Russian roulette with a machine gun.''
   Reagan's veto promise, in a speech to the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce's annual meeting, drew loud applause from the audience of
about 2,000 people. They also cheered his statement that capital
gains taxes should be cut sometime in the future.
   The trade bill, expected to reach the White House this week, won
final congressional approval in the Senate last Thursday on a 63-36
vote, three votes short of the margin needed to overturn a veto.
   One provision would require all but the smallest businesses to
provide a 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs.
The bill specifies exceptions for companies in serious financial
trouble.
   ``The plant-closing restriction is the bill's worst provision,
not the only bad one,'' Reagan said. He did not cite any other
features he considered objectionable, although the administration
has complained about the bill's curbs on Alaska oil exports.
   He said some supporters of the notification provision say it
will not hurt, noting that many European countries have similar
restrictions.
   ``Yep, and that's among the reasons for Europe's poor job
performance over the last six years,'' Reagan said.
   ``If we had done as poorly, our unemployment rate would be up
like theirs, not down from 10.8 percent to 5.5 percent,'' Reagan
said. ``What would organized labor say then?''
   ``Anyone who would copy Europe in this way is no friend to
American workers,'' he added. ``For America, plant-closing
restrictions are like playing Russian roulette with a machine gun _
a sure loser.''
</TEXT>
