<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Cocaine     05-02 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Cocaine,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cocaine Refining Complex Destroyed, 30 Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Monday they destroyed a huge
cocaine refining complex, confiscated 5,830 pounds of cocaine and
arrested 30 people during a search for an alleged drug trafficker
wanted in the United States.
   Authorities said they also found one thousand containers of
chemicals used in cocaine processing, an electric power plant
powerful enough to supply 3,000 homes and an airfield under
construction.
   The drugs and chemicals were destroyed on the spot.
   The finds were made during a search for Pablo Escovar Gaviria,
the alleged head of the Medellin Cartel, the biggest ring of
Colombian drug traffickers. U.S. officials have said the ring is
responsible for moving about 80 percent of the cocaine used
annually in the United States.
   Police estimated the value of the drugs and other equipment
seized at the laboratories at about $14 million.
   The laboratories were in Doradal, about 120 miles north of
Bogota.
   Those arrested said they had been unemployed and had to work at
the drug factory to support their families. Another 30 reportedly
fled during the raid.
   Police said the clandestine drug factory was uncovered at the
Jamaica ranch, which used stockraising as a cover for its
operations.
   Police said they were unable to establish ownership immediately,
but the factory appeared to be part of extensive landholdings of
Medellin Cartel members in the area.
   Police and army troops have been combing the area for three days
in search of Escobar Gaviria. He and three other men are wanted for
extradition to the United States on drug-smuggling charges.
</TEXT>
