<DOCNO> AP880502-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1801EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SeaTurtleNursery     05-02 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sea Turtle Nursery,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Artificial Nesting Beach Being Built for Kemp's Ridleys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nursery with an artificial nesting
beach is being built at the Clearwater Marine Science Center with
the goal of boosting the population of the imperiled Kemp's Ridley
sea turtle.
   The $10,000 project will experiment with a first-of-its-kind
beach that includes a gently sloping sand ramp and sea oats, said
Dennis Kellenberger, the center's executive director.
   The purpose: to encourage female Kemp's Ridley sea turtles to
crawl ashore and lay their eggs. Only about 400 to 600 reproducing
females of the species remain.
   Eight Kemp's Ridley turtles, including both sexes, live at the
marine center. These 6-year-old turtles are ready to reproduce, and
center officials hope they will breed and nest in captivity.
   Kellenberger said an attempt at using an artificial beach is a
new approach. ``We're hoping that if they're confined to an area
where they really have no choice but to nest here, then they
will,'' he said.
   The tank will be partially filled with water and the turtles
will be placed there together. At one end of the tank will be a
beach area created by putting sand on a fiberglass liner atop a
wood platform. A gently sloping sand-covered ramp will enable the
turtles to crawl ashore and nest there when they are ready.
   The Kemp's Ridley species was decimated by poachers who waited
for the arrival each summer of the egg-laden females at their only
natural nesting area on a Gulf of Mexico beach at Rancho Nuevo,
Mexico. Poachers sought turtle meat, widely considered a delicacy,
and eggs.
   The nesting beach has been protected since 1966, but the turtles
have not yet recovered to their former numbers partly because they
are frequent victims of shrimpers who unwittingly drown them in
their nets.
   The cream-colored Kemp's Ridleys are the smallest of the sea
turtles, weighing about 100 pounds. They are found throughout the
coastal waters of the United States and Central America, and often
forage in the Tampa Bay area.
   Scientists don't know exactly why the Kemp's Ridleys females lay
their eggs on only one beach or whether enough of them can be
persuaded to nest elsewhere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0151 </DOCNO>
