<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial     05-02 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lehder Defense Rests Without Calling Witnesses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for reputed Colombian drug
lord Carlos Lehder Rivas rested their case Monday without calling
any witnesses to counter 22 weeks of testimony that their client
ran a vast cocaine-smuggling empire.
   Defense attorney Edward R. Shohat rested on the defense's first
day after filing documents on deals the government made to get
testimony from some of the 115 prosecution witnesses, many of them
admitted smugglers.
   ``The government has literally given away the courthouse to get
our client,'' Shohat said. He declined to discuss the move with
reporters outside the courtroom.
   Stephen J. Weinbaum, an attorney for co-defendant Jack Reed,
also rested his case without calling any witnesses.
   Defense attorneys often use that tactic ``to keep the
sufficiency of the government's case at issue,'' said Weinbaum.
   Defense attorneys have questioned the credibility of witnesses
throughout the case, contending that the government reduced
sentences, gave grants of immunity and even decided not to seek
charges against witnesses.
   Last week, Shohat had said the defense would take two weeks, and
prosecutors acknowledged they were caught off-guard by the sudden
change.
   ``You could honestly say I looked surprised and stunned,''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Ernst Mueller said after the announcement
was made. The jury did not show any reaction.
   U.S. District Judge Howell Melton set closing arguments for next
week.
   Lehder, 38, allegedly one of the leaders of the violent Medellin
cartel, is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise. He is accused of smuggling 3.3 tons
of cocaine into the United States from his private island of
Norman's Cay in the Bahamas from 1978 to 1980.
   If convicted of all 11 counts against him, Lehder faces a
maximum sentence of life, plus 165 years.
   Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., is charged with conspiracy and
faces a maximum sentence of 15 years.
   Melton denied a defense motion Monday to sequester the jury
during closing arguments, which defense attorneys complained will
come during ``Just Say No To Drugs Week.''
   The judge also denied a motion from Shohat for a 60-day
continuance to give attorneys time to go over thousands of
documents and visit foreign countries to prepare their defense.
   ``The defense in this case depended in large amount on evidence
from outside the Unites States _ that includes principally the
Bahamas, Germany, Haiti, Colombia,'' said Shohat.
   Lehder also is also charged in separate indictments in Los
Angeles and Miami.
   The Miami indictment accuses him of being one of the leaders of
the so-called Medellin cartel, believed to be responsible for 80
percent of the cocaine smuggled into United States _ a bonanza
worth $8 billion each year.
   According to law enforcement officials who have requested
anonymity, U.S. Attorney Robert W. Merkle has been presenting
evidence from the Lehder trial to a federal grand jury in Tampa
investigating possible drug links to Bahamian Prime Minister Lynden
O. Pindling.
</TEXT>
