<HEAD>Divorced Couple In Contest for Watauga Register of Deeds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-State Primary Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOONE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The GOP primary Tuesday for Watauga County's
register of deeds pits two people who have squared off against each
other at least once before _ in the divorce courts.
   Orville Foster is challenging incumbent Phyllis Foster, his
ex-wife.
   A little less than three years ago, three days after their
divorce, Foster was arrested on charges of assault with a deadly
weapon, his car, for ``swerving in an attempt to strike'' a female
companion walking with Mrs. Foster in a shopping mall parking lot.
   Of the election contest, Mrs. Foster says: ``It's excruciatingly
painful. But situations like this build character.'' The Fosters
were married for 35 years.
   Foster, the county Republican chairman, says: ``I would be
running for register of deeds if (Gov.) Jim Martin were running for
register of deeds in Watauga County. The fact that Phyllis and I
used to be married has nothing to do with it.''
   Foster has attacked Mrs. Foster's budget practices as register
of deeds.
   ``The register of deeds office does pay its way, but it should
be making money _ a great deal of money _ rather than just breaking
even,'' he said.
   ``I'm running on my record,'' Mrs. Foster said.
   The Fosters had been married for six years when Foster was
appointed county tax collector and named his wife his part-time
assistant in 1956.
   In 1962, Foster won his first elected office, clerk of Superior
Court, a post he held for 12 years. He appointed his wife a deputy.
   On Oct. 2, 1985, their divorce was finalized. All records of the
divorce are inaccessible. A handwritten note on one file says
``Closed to the public,'' while another file is ordered closed on
request of Foster, the plaintiff.
   A deferred prosecution deal ordering Foster to keep a clean
record allowed the 1985 assault charges to be dropped a year later.
   More than a week after his arrest, Foster wrote to the state
treasurer, telling him retirement credits Mrs. Foster was claiming
as assistant tax collector should not be allowed because she did
not work full time.
   A two-year probe led to a state ruling against Mrs. Foster.
