went to the polls in 1984 when Jackson took all but three of the
Democratic delegates, and a similar turnout is expected Tuesday.
   In the district, less than 22,000 people are registered
Republicans. In the GOP primary, voters are expected to give George
Bush 14 delegates in a winner-take-all primary.
   District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry Jr. and the district's
delegate to Congress, Walter Fauntroy, have been active Jackson
supporters and participants in his national campaign.
   Barry has predicted that Jackson will take 70 percent of the
Democratic primary vote in the district, which is 67 percent black.
   The district and Louisiana were Jackson's only primary victories
in 1984.
