<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseSpending     05-02 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Refuses To Ban US Manuevers Along Honduras-Nicaragua Border</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted easily Monday to again ban any
U.S. combat troops from Nicaragua, but refused to prohibit American
servicmen from conducting maneuvers along the border of the
leftist-ruled Central American nation.
   The decisions came as the chamber began a second week of work on
a bill authorizing the Pentagon budget for the next fiscal year.
   First, the Democratic-controlled House voted 276-92 to block the
sending of any combat troops into, or over, Nicaragua.
   A similar ban had been approved by the House in each of the past
two years. But it had been changed by a House-Senate conference
committee to simply make it a ``sense of the Congress'' resolution
and say the ban didn't affect a president's constitutional power as
commander-in-chief.
   Rep. Thomas Foley, D-Wash., the House majority leader, sponsored
the proposal.
   He noted that President Reagan has repeatedly stated the United
States has no intention of invading Nicaragua, where U.S.-backed
Contra guerrillas are now conducting peace talks with the leftist
leaders of Nicaragua's Sandinista government.
   ``It may seem to some wise to reaffirm this intention on the
part of the administration and Congress not to maintain any threat
of intervention,'' said Foley.
   But Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said, ``this perennial amendment is
still unconstitutional, in my judgement. I don't think we can
repeal the power of the president to be commander-in-chief.''
   Before passing the Foley proposal, the House voted 336-21
approval of an amendment by Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., which
said U.S. forces could be sent into Nicaragua to respond to a
hijacking, a kidnapping, or other acts of terrorism against U.S.
citizens or citizens of a U.S. ally.
   Then, the House rejected, 238-147, an amendment by Rep. Edward
Markey, D-Mass., that would block U.S. personnel who are assisting
the Contras from being within 20 miles of the Nicaraguan border.
The prohibition would specifically apply to U.S. military exercises.
   The Pentagon has conducted a series of exercises in Honduras,
which shares a border with Nicaragua. But U.S. personnel have
generally stayed away from the border.
   The House also rejected, 267-111, an attempt to delete the $3
million in the bill which would go for Army construction plans in
Honduras.
   The Senate is expected next week to begin considering its
version of a Pentagon budget bill, and the provisions that
separately pass the two chambers will eventually have to be
reconciled by a House-Senate conference committee.
   Both the House and Senate measures authorize $299.5 billion in
defense spending for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1. But the House
has already added three nuclear arms control restrictions strongly
opposed by Reagan, in addition to the Foley proposal.
   More restrictions are likely as the House continues to work
through the bill, including a deep reduction from Reagan's request
for spending on his Star Wars anti-missile research plan.
   Reagan sought $4.8 billion for the plan, but the House bill
would permit $4.0 billion, while the Senate measure allows $4.6
billion. The current budget is $3.9 billion for the Strategic
Defense Initiative, as Star Wars is formally known.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
