<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissingBody     05-02 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Body,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Says Police Bungled After Son's Body Lay In Morgue For
Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of Allan Ruffin lay unidentified in the
Cook County morgue for a month while his family searched
frantically for him, badgering police, calling hospitals, even
asking the morgue if his body was there.
   Ruffin's family accused the Chicago police on Monday of bungling
the investigation of his disappearance, launched nearly two months
ago when the family first filed a missing person's report.
   ``How is it that they did not discover my brother at the morgue
when they told us they assigned an officer to us and he was
investigating?'' said Ruffin's older sister, Thelma, 38. ``They
just didn't do their jobs.
   ``We're still in a state of shock. I can't believe that this has
happened,'' Ms. Ruffin said Monday in a telephone interview.
   The Ruffin's complaint is under investigation and ``there's no
comment on it until the investigation is cleared,'' said Officer
Ernestine Dowell, a Chicago Police Department spokeswoman.
   Ms. Ruffin said the family last saw Allan, 35, a disabled
Vietnam War veteran, on March 3, but didn't worry until three days
later when he still hadn't shown up for his medication, which he
kept at his mother's apartment.
   He had suffered a head wound in Vietnam and took medication to
prevent seizures, Ms. Ruffin said.
   On March 7, another sister, Laverne Walker, went to Ruffin's
room at the Mark Twain Hotel on the city's West Side to look for
him. She found his room in bloody disarray, Ms. Ruffin said.
   ``We thought that he might have had a seizure and hit his head
and that would have caused the blood,'' she said. ``So we started
calling the hospitals and calling around the neighborhood.''
   The family filed a missing persons report on March 9, but Ms.
Ruffin contends the initial officer assigned to the case never came
to pick up a photograph of her brother.
   Police pulled Ruffin's body from the Chicago River on March 28.
   It remained at the county medical examiner's office until last
Wednesday when a second police investigator assigned to the case
discovered the clothes found on the body matched the description
provided by the family in its original missing persons report, Ms.
Ruffin said.
   ``Everything we said that he was wearing when we last saw him
was at the morgue,'' she said. ``Why did he lay in the morgue since
the 28th (of March)? He had loved ones.''
   While her brother was missing, Ms. Ruffin said she and other
family members regularly called local hospitals and distributed
fliers with Ruffin's photograph.
   ``We were hoping he had a seizure and bumped his head and maybe
was wandering around still alive, but just didn't remember who he
was,'' Ms. Ruffin said.
   She said they also called the morgue regularly and even went
there on April 11 _ while her brother's body was there _ and
inspected another unidentified body found under a viaduct to see if
it was Allan.
   Ms. Ruffin said the medical examiner's office told the family
her brother had drowned, but Roy Dames of the medical examiner's
office said the cause of death listed on his death certificate was
left blank _ ``pending police investigation.''
   Ruffin's will be buried Tuesday.
</TEXT>
