<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseNomination     05-02 0116</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Nomination,110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Diplomat Named to Pentagon Special Operations Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles S. Whitehouse, an American diplomat in
Southeast Asia during the Vietnam War, will be nominated by
President Reagan as assistant secretary of defense for special
operations and low-intensity conflict, it was announced Monday.
   Whitehouse was regional director of the U.S. Agency for
International Development in South Vietnam from 1969 until 1970,
when he became acting deputy assistant secretary of state for East
Asian-Pacific affairs.
   He returned to Saigon as a deputy chief of mission in 1972.
Later he was ambassador in Laos, and then ambassador in Thailand.
Whitehouse retired in 1978.
   If confirmed, Whitehouse, 66, will succeed Chapman B. Cox.
