<HEAD>N.C. Convention Scuffle Could Mean Trouble, GOP Chairman Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISBURG, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fistfights that erupted at the 4th
District Republican convention over the weekend could point to a
future showdown between supporters of presidential candidate Pat
Robertson and other delegates, North Carolina's GOP chairman says.
   ``Who was right, I can't say, but certainly there needs to be
more maturity and evenhandedness in handling the whole situation,''
Jack Hawke told The News and Observer of Raleigh.
   The confrontation involved the selection of three delegates to
the Republican National Convention in August. Competing for the
delegate slots were Robertson supporters and GOP party leaders
backing Vice President George Bush.
   After the confrontation, Robertson supporters walked out to hold
their own convention, while Bush supporters elected their three
delegates inside.
   A group of Robertson supporters then returned to the podium, and
screaming and fist-throwing followed as Bush and Robertson forces
battled for control.
   No one was seriously injured, officials said.
   Hawke said he fears possible reprisals from conservative GOP
members if differences aren't resolved at the state convention.
   ``When you are a minority party and you are used to being
behind, you need all the help and support you can possibly
receive,'' he said. ``But it's a very unfortunate threat for
anybody to oppose somebody just to get even.''
