<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Media Allow Dukakis ``to Have Teflon''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB grafs 2-4 with 4 grafs to add more detail on the minimum
wage proposal bgng ``Jackson, spelling...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Monday that he and
Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis are not being held to the
same standards, with the news media allowing Dukakis ``to have
Teflon'' while Jackson is required to back up his proposals and
statements.
   Jackson, spelling out proposals of his own, also called for a
substantial increase in the minimum wage and for a corporate code
of conduct to press companies benefiting from federal help to
invest in America and not take jobs outside the country.
   In a luncheon speech to The City Club, a Cleveland civic
organization, Jackson said he would raise the minimum wage of $3.35
an hour to half the average hourly wage of production workers,
which is $9.19.
   Jackson's staff said he gradually would increase the wage
standard to $5.50 an hour by 1993.
   He said a conduct code should establish ``a set of
responsibilities to accompany the right to do business, the receipt
of government incentives, tax credits and grants. It encourages
participation of workers in their companies and a greater
productivity.''
   Earlier, after a speech to high school students in nearby Parma,
Jackson said Dukakis has not been forced to give specifics to back
up his campaign generalities.
   ``So far the media is allowing him to have Teflon,'' Jackson
said, a reference to a situation in which opponents' criticism
slides right off.
   ``In time, that will change,'' Jackson said. ``The media
challenged me to show how I would pay for my dreams. I have done
just that.''
   For now, however, Jackson said Dukakis has not come under the
same kind of scrutiny concerning the priorities he would set and
how he would pay.
   ``So far Dukakis has operated with caution when we must operate
with courage, clarity and candor,'' Jackson said.
   In a wide-ranging economic speech on the eve of Ohio's
presidential primary, Jackson sought to give specifics of his own
economic proposals in what aides said was an effort to draw
comparisons with Dukakis.
   Jackson said his corporate code of conduct would be ``based on
democratic values and a common definition of the national
interest.'' He said it would make corporations accountable ``not
only to shareholders but to all stakeholders, including the
community and workers.''
   He said he wants to change corporate behavior as part of his
plans for reversing President Reagan's economic policies.
   Jackson also renewed his call for investment of a portion of
public pension funds into domestic development projects. He said
the program would use federal guarantees to issue bonds backed by
development projects and would sell the bonds to the pension funds.
   He said the program should include cooperation between federal
and local governments as well as business interests.
   Jackson spent Sunday night at the modest Berea home of
steelworker union organizer Valentino Fulimeni to symbolize concern
for laborers who he said had been hurt by Reagan administration
economic policies.
   ``There simply are two dimensions to this campaign,'' Jackson
said. Besides the race for the presidency, there is also ``a
historical dimension. It is part of the thrust to open up the
American political system ... the thrust to empower locked-out
people.''
</TEXT>
