<HEAD>First Lady Tells Entertainment Moguls Her Post White House Dream</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf ``Among those'' to add further identification
and CORRECT to Murdock sted Murdoch.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Nancy Reagan will forge
ahead with her anti-drug crusade in her post-White House years, but
she told Hollywood's money barons Monday that she needs help to
realize her dreams.
   On the lavish grounds of the four-acre Merv Griffin estate, Mrs.
Reagan told the 42 guests gathered at a ``power breakfast'' that
her proposed Nancy Reagan Center for drug abuse is the next stage
in her drug fight.
   Several locations in Los Angeles County are being considered for
the $10 million facility and no decision has been made on a site,
said Dan Langdon the the New York-based Phoenix House.
   ``She was received very well,'' said Griffin publicist Warren
Cowan. ``She is going to be very active and work at this when she
leaves. She talked about setting up this facility and she recounted
her history with the drug program.''
   The Phoenix House, the nation's largest private, non-profit drug
abuse service agency, will operate the center described by Mrs.
Reagan as ``a central institution in the battle against youthful
drug abuse.''
   Breakfast guests began arriving just before 8 a.m. with a
procession of Rolls-Royce luxury cars led by actress Eva Gabor's
gray Rolls. She emerged in a canary yellow suit and was greeted by
boyfriend Griffin on the steps of the massive stone mansion.
   Among those dining with the first lady at the estate's tennis
pavilion were wealthy businessmen Marvin Davis, Fred Hartley, Fred
Hayman, Rupert Murdoch and David Murdock and entertainment
executives Grant Tinker and Jerry Weintraub.
   ``This was a power breakfast for power people,'' said Cowan.
Griffin described the group earlier as ``every mover and shaker in
this part of the world.''
   Mrs. Reagan spent two hours with the group, dining with them on
smoked salmon and sturgeon, fried apples and scrambled eggs, before
her motorcade sped off for Los Angeles International Airport and a
flight back to Washington.
   Guests then heard from Griffin in a 30-minute discussion about
the proposed Nancy Reagan Center and he announced formation of a
fund-raising effort. Cowan said, however, that guests weren't
directly asked for money.
   The center will be a residential high school for youngsters with
drug abuse problems, said Langdon, adding that a research unit and
training institute were also part of the master plan.
