<DOCNO> AP880502-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1909EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ReligiousDeaths     05-02 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religious Deaths,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christian Science Couple Face Manslaughter Charges in Death of Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christian Science couple pleaded innocent Monday
to charges that they caused their son's death by failing to seek
medical treatment because of their religious beliefs.
   David and Ginger Twitchell, formerly of Boston's Hyde Park
section, appeared in Suffolk Superior Court on manslaughter charges
stemming from the April 8, 1986, death of their 2{-year-old son,
Robyn.
   Twitchell, dressed in a dark blue leisure suit, and his wife,
who wore a lavender pantsuit with lavender-colored plastic flowers
in her hair, stood close to each other and held hands as they both
entered not guilty pleas before Trial Magistrate Gary Wilson.
   A pretrial conference was set for June 1. The Twitchells, who
have two other sons, Jeremy, 6, and Brian, 7 months, were released
on their own recognizance.
   In response to a motion filed by the prosecution, Superior Court
Judge Sandra Hamlin imposed a gag order on all parties in the case
pending a hearing Thursday on the matter.
   Assistant District Attorney Thomas J. Mundy requested the order
for attorneys in the case, complaining about the published remarks
made last week by one of the two defense attorneys, Rikki Klieman.
Mundy said Klieman's statements violated the canon of ethics and
``could poison the pool of prospective jurors.''
   Klieman's remarks, published in The Boston Globe, included the
statement that the death of the Twitchell child ``was not a crime.''
   Klieman argued in court Monday that she was not suggesting that
the Twitchells were either innocent or guilty but was merely
referring to the fact that the child's death did not constitute a
crime under state law.
   ``It's our reading of the law that there has been no crime
here,'' she said.
   The Twitchells are the second set of Christian Science parents
to be prosecuted in the state and the first since 1971, when the
state amended the child abuse and neglect law to recognize
spiritual healing as an alternative to modern medicine.
   Followers of Christian Science refuse medicine or other health
care on the belief that true understanding of God acts as a cure.
   According to police reports, Robyn Twitchell became feverish and
lethargic in early April 1986. The Twitchells contacted a church
practitioner, who came to their home to pray for the boy's recovery.
   On the evening of his death, the boy developed convulsions and
lost consciousness and vital signs. The boy's father first called a
funeral director, who told him to contact the police. The boy was
pronounced dead at Carney Hospital in Boston.
   Klieman said the official cause of death was complications from
a bowel obstruction. She said it stemmed from a congenital birth
defect.
   Officials will not reveal the Twitchells' current town of
residence. Klieman said David Twitchell works in a retirement home
and Mrs. Twitchell is a ``homemaker.''
   In 1967, Dorothy Sheriden of Harwich was convicted of
manslaughter for the death of her 5-year-old daughter from a lung
infection.
   The Church of Christ, Scientist is located in Boston and the
denomination has about 3,200 branches worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
