<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Namibia-Nujuma     05-02 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Namibia-Nujuma,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Group Leader Would Establish Democracy in Namibia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a guerrilla group seeking to end
South Africa's rule in Namibia said Monday he intends to create a
democratic state with a non-aligned foreign policy.
   Sam Nujoma of the South-West Africa People's Organization, or
SWAPO, also said that if he attains power in Namibia he would
``destroy colonial institutions'' and replace them with programs to
provide health services and education to the African majority.
   ``The national policy would be geared to developing Namibia's
economy,'' Nujoma said at a Capitol Hill conference sponsored by
the World Council of Churches.
   Nujoma's vision of the kind of government SWAPO would run came
in response to questions about his supposed links to communist
groups.
   Nujoma, who has been fighting the war for Namibia's independence
for 22 years, acknowledged that his organization accepts assistance
from any group if ``the assistance is genuine.'' SWAPO has observer
status at the United Nations.
   Nujoma has his headquarters in Luanda, the capital of Angola,
which is backed by the Soviet and Cuban governments. An estimated
70,000 Namibian refugees live in Angola and neighboring Zambia.
   Nujoma described SWAPO as a ``national liberation movement,''
with many Christian members as well as a sprinkling of whites.
   If he is ever elected, he said he would ``create a democratic
state,'' recognizing the freedoms of speech and assembly. Turning
to those Namibians who have collaborated with the white South
African regime, Nujoma said, ``We will find a way of accommodating
them.''
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since after World War 1. In 1978,
the United Nations Security Council adopted a resolution which
calls for the immediate withdrawal of South African troops from
Namibia and the holding of U.N.-sponsored elections. The South
Africans have refused to leave.
   Reagan administration officials have tried to broker a deal
whereby the Cuban troops leave Angola in exchange for South
Africa's withdrawal from Namibia, but that effort has not been
successful.
</TEXT>
