<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-SovietResolution     05-02 0121</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Soviet Resolution,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Resolution Condeming Soviet Religious Persecution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed a Senate resolution
Monday deploring persecution by the Soviet government of religious
believers in the Ukraine.
   The resolution, approved by a voice vote, urges the United
States to refrain from participating in ceremonies in June marking
the millennium of Christianity in the Soviet Union if religious
persecution persists.
   The ceremonies mark the founding of Christianity in Kievan Rus',
an area now within the Ukraine, 1,000 years ago.
   The document also expresses congressional concern for Ukrainian
religious believers who are persecuted for attempting to worship.
   Last Friday, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev condemned past
anti-religious repression and called for a more tolerate attitude
toward religion.
</TEXT>
