<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Netherlands-IRA     05-02 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Netherlands-IRA,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Unable To Trace IRA Attackers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROERMOND, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dutch police were reported stymied
on Monday in efforts to track down IRA attackers who killed three
British airmen, and a British anti-terrorist unit arrived to help
in the search.
   The Irish Republican Army raiders struck in closely coordinated
attacks on Sunday in the midst of a festive Dutch holiday.
   ``We have no indication as to the description (of the
attackers), nor indications of their escape route or their means of
escape,'' police spokesman Harry Clabbers told reporters at a
briefing in this southeastern Dutch city.
   Scotland Yard announced Monday night that an anti-terrorist
squad officer and an officer from the Special Branch, which deals
with national security matters, had come to the Netherlands at the
request of Dutch authorities.
   Earlier Monday, another Dutch police spokesman noted it was easy
to escape through porous Dutch borders, with little time needed to
get away to West Germany or Belgium.
   Three British air force men stationed in West Germany were
killed and three others injured in an early Sunday ambush at
Roermond and a car bomb attack in Nieuwbergen, 30 miles to the
north.
   The British Defense Ministry said the victims were unarmed and
off duty and were in the Netherlands over the weekend for
celebrations of the official 50th birthday of Dutch Queen Beatrix.
   On Sunday, the IRA claimed responsibility for both attacks in a
coded message to Belfast news media.
   In The Hague, police presence around the British Embassy was
reinforced but Dutch law enforcement officials refused to discuss
increased security measures.
   The feeling expressed in official British circles in the
Netherlands was that the IRA mounted the attacks in reprisal for
the March 6 killing by British soldiers of three IRA activists in
Gibraltar.
   Clabbers told reporters dozens of residents and bystanders were
questioned in Nieuwbergen and Roermond, ``but the information
yielded by those interviews is very meager.''
   He said forensic experts closely studied the attack sites on
Monday.
   Road signs and military radio stations meanwhile discouraged
British forces in West Germany from travel in or through the
Netherlands.
   About 70,000 British military are stationed in West Germany,
along with 80,000 dependents.
</TEXT>
