<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-WesternSahara     05-02 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Western Sahara,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Chief's Peace Mission Runs Aground</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. secretary-general's mission to
North Africa failed at the outset Monday and he will end the trip
after visiting only one of three parties to a dispute over the
Western Sahara, a U.N. source reported.
   Javier Perez de Cuellar said he would return to New York from
Morocco without visiting Mauritania or Algeria.
   Algeria supports the Polisario independence movement, which has
fought Morocco for control of the the Western Sahara since Spain
withdrew from the phosphate-rich territory in November 1975.
   The secretary-general said he had to cut short the trip because
of ``quite a lot of problems in New York,'' but the U.N. source
said the mission foundered because of difficulties with the
Polisario. He would not provide details, and spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Perez de Cuellar had been scheduled to visit a major Polisario
base at Tindouf, Algeria, and meet with Chadli Bendjedid, Algeria's
president. He was also was scheduled to meet with officials in
Mauritania.
   He arrived in Rabat, Morocco on Monday for a meeting with King
Hassan II.
   There, he said he had changed his schedule and planned to see
the leaders of Algeria and Mauritania and the secretary-general of
the Polisario later this month during the Organization of African
Unity summit in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.
   His remarks in Rabat were made available to reporters at the
United Nations late Monday.
   Neither Morocco nor Algeria had indicated willingness to make
concessions in the 13-year dispute over the Western Sahara.
   After Spain left the territory, it was divided between Morocco
and Mauritania, which ceded its interest to Morocco in 1979.
   Official media in Morocco and Algeria had reiterated the
irreconcilable positions of their governments on the eve of Perez
de Cuellar's mission.
   Algiers radio repeated demands for Moroccan withdrawal from the
territory and direct negotiations between Morocco and the Polisario
as a preliminary to any referendum.
   Moroccan media restated Morocco's refusal either to withdraw or
negotiate with the Polisario, which it calls ``Algerian
mercenaries.''
   Since November 1975, Morocco has spent an estimated $1.5 million
a day defending the territory against Polisario attacks from
sanctuaries on the Algerian side of the unmarked border.
   Thousands of combatants have died on both sides of the
undeclared war. The 80,000 nomads who lived in the territory in
1975 have fled to Algeria or safe parts of the desert region.
   King Hassan has offered to conduct a U.N.-supervised referendum
among the inhabitants, on condition that his 120,000-man army is
not required to withdraw before the vote.
</TEXT>
