<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaLondeCase     05-02 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaLonde Case,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins in Highly Publicized Tug-of-War Over 9-Year-Old Girl</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A long battle for custody of a 9-year-old girl
whose mother went to jail rather than disclose her whereabouts went
before a probate judge Monday in a private proceeding that court
officials said could take weeks.
   The highly publicized fight over Nicole LaLonde began three
years ago when 41-year-old Virginia LaLonde accused her ex-husband,
Stephen LaLonde, 37, of sexually abusing the child while he had
custody of her.
   A probate judge determined the charges were unfounded. Then, in
June 1986, Mrs. LaLonde went into hiding with Nicole rather than
obey a court order allowing unsupervised visits with the father.
   Mother and daughter eventually settled in Florida. But in March
1987, Mrs. LaLonde decided to return to Massachusetts to settle the
matter. When she did, she was thrown in jail and thrust into the
public spotlight.
   Mrs. LaLonde returned alone and refused to disclose her
daughter's whereabouts. Her silence drew a contempt-of-court
citation and an open-ended term in jail, where she remained until
October.
   Mrs. LaLonde was released after Nicole was discovered in Durham,
N.C. A babysitter there tipped police that the child was being
sheltered by an underground railroad of women who claim the courts
ignore claims that their husbands abused their children.
   The LaLonde fight persisted and made headlines until it headed
for the showdown in court.
   Suffolk County Probate Judge Mary C. Fitzpatrick has barred the
public from the proceedings, which are expected to last six weeks.
In addition, participants in the case and their lawyers are
forbidden to speak to reporters.
   An array of lawyers and medical experts are expected to testify,
but central to the case will be a medical and psychological
evaluation performed on Nicole last fall.
   As soon as the girl was brought back from North Carolina, the
state Department of Social Services took her into custody and
admitted her to Cambridge Hospital, where she stayed more than a
month as investigators tried to find out whether her mother's
charges were true.
   Although the resulting report was sealed by the court, excerpts
were leaked to the media alleging that doctors had found signs the
girl had been sexually abused. It also was disclosed that the
evaluators had recommended that Stephen LaLonde seek counseling.
   LaLonde had remained mute for six months while proclaiming his
innocence through his lawyer. When he briefly broke his silence, he
said said he was receiving psychotherapy. He has remarried.
   Meantime, Nicole has lived with a foster family since leaving
the hospital.
</TEXT>
