<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     05-02 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tamil Rebels Blamed For Bombing that Injures 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A time bomb exploded Monday in the
eastern town of Batticaloa, wounding at least 10 people and
destroying a building, police reported.
   Police blamed the bombing on the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, the most powerful Tamil group fighting the
Sinhalese-dominated government and military.
   The blast, 140 miles east of Colombo, wrecked a two-story
building that housed a Moslem-owned textile shop, said police chief
Gamini Seneviratne.
   Seven of the injured were hospitalized, he said.
   Sri Lankan military officials also blamed the Tigers for an
attack Sunday near Trincomalee. Twenty-six people, including two
little boys, were killed when buried explosives were detonated
under a bus in the port town 150 miles northeast of Colombo.
   Thirty others were injured, and 15 of them were reported in
critical condition.
   Most of the victims were Sinhalese, the majority ethnic group on
the island, said the officials.
   In a separate incident on Sunday, a member of Parliament, G.V.S.
De Silva, was shot to death when Sinhalese extremists ambushed his
car as he left a Buddhist sanctuary in the town of Galle, 70 miles
south of Colombo, police said.
   A police inspector, a driver and another civilian in de Silva's
car suffered gunshot wounds.
   The government blamed that attack on the People's Liberation
Front, an ultra-nationalist Sinhalese group accused of killing more
than 200 government officials and supporters.
   De Silva, who was wounded last August in a grenade attack on
Parliament, belonged to the governing United National Party.
   The People's Liberation Front has vowed to kill anyone who
supports a peace pact signed by the government and India last July.
The agreement grants some autonomy to minority Tamils.
   Sinhalese extremists say the treaty makes too many concessions
to the group.
   Tamil extremists have been fighting for a separate homeland for
four years in northern and eastern Sri Lanka and have refused to
surrender their arms under the terms of the peace accord.
   More than 50,000 Indians have been deployed to disarm the
rebels, who say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
while 75 percent of the population is Sinhalese.

</TEXT>
