<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0642 05-02 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Responds To Jackson Criticism While Courting Black Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS new grafs 2-4 to UPDATE; DELETES outdated penultimate
graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis,
responding to Jesse Jackson's assertion that he is a manager but
not a leader, said Monday he was ``not just a talker'' and had a
proven leadership record.
   He also fired anew at the apparent Republican nominee, George
Bush, saying he would continue to press the vice president to fully
explain his role in the Iran-Contra affair and the Reagan
administration's dealings with Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   ``This administration ... has broken the law,'' Dukakis said in
an interview with The Associated Press. ``I think the vice
president has to address the issue.''
   As Dukakis took the offensive against Bush, he was fending off
barbs by Jackson.
   On Sunday, Jackson repeated his contention that Dukakis would
``manage Reaganomics'' and said of his Democratic rival: ``Don't be
bragging about how clean the kitchen is, and cool. If the kitchen
is clean and cool, ain't nothing cooking.''
   Asked to respond Monday, Dukakis referred to his state's 2.9
percent unemployment rate, its anti-drug programs and the recent
passage of legislation guaranteeing all workers health care.
   ``That's a lot of fire and a lot of productivity,'' said
Dukakis, the likely Democratic nominee. ``I'm not just a talker.
I'm a doer. There's no question about my record.''
   The Massachusetts governor, winding down his campaign for
Tuesday's presidential primary in Ohio, also courted black voters
and chided the Reagan admimistration for what he said was a failure
to provide adequate support for day care programs.
   Surrounded by a dozen black children at a nursery in a
Cincinnati high school, Dukakis called on President Reagan to
endorse a House-passed bill that would increase day care funding.
   ``This is the kind of thing we need,'' Dukakis said of the
in-school day care program. ``We need it as a matter of national
policy.''
   After singing a song with the children and reading them a story,
Dukakis walked across the street and visited a Greek restaurant. He
urged supporters to ignore polls showing him well ahead of Jackson
in Ohio, but he appeared relaxed and confident, taking time at the
Cincinnati airport to toss a football with aides.
   Dukakis headed from Cincinnati to Columbus, where he spoke to a
lunchtime crowd of several thousand people at an outdoor rally, and
was to stop in Cleveland and Parma before heading back to Boston.
   He said he was not criticizing Jackson.
   ``I'm just saying that I think the American people are looking
for somebody who not only has a very strong commitment to schools
and economic opportunity and decent housing and health care, but
also someone who has done these things,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis said the appearance at the predominantly black Hughes
High School was not designed to lure voters away from Jackson. But
campaign aides said the stop was part of an effort to broaden
Dukakis' support among blacks heading into the general election.
   Greeting Dukakis at school was Loretta Carter of Cincinnati, who
worked for one of Dukakis' gubernatorial campaigns when she was
living in Boston in the 1970s.
   Ms. Carter, who is black, predicted Dukakis would win
overwhelming support among blacks if he promised Jackson a key
campaign or administration post.
   ``I think he has to have an important role,'' Ms. Carter said of
Jackson. ``But I don't think as vice president. I think if he was
on the ticket we would lose.''
   Dukakis stuck to what has been the thrust of his campaign in
recent weeks, carefully avoiding sharp criticism of Jackson while
denouncing the Reagan administration.
   He said the federal trade and budget deficits had put the
nation's economy at risk.
   ``If you're serious about good jobs, about economic development,
then you've got to balance your books,'' Dukakis said.
   He continued to denounce Reagan's plans to veto the trade bill
passed by Congress and also renewed his criticism of Attorney
General Edwin Meese III.
</TEXT>
