<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Afghan,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Islamabad Complains That Afghanistan Violates Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan summoned the Afghan charge
d'affaires Monday to protest cross-border air raids and shelling
last week that officials said killed 13 people and wounded 17.
   The government news agency APP said three Afghan fighter planes
bombed the Kurram area of northwest Pakistan last Tuesday, killing
four Afghan refugees and wounding three.
   It said Afghan artillery shelled the Khyber region farther north
two days later, killing eight refugees and a Pakistani child. It
said 11 Afghans and three Pakistanis were wounded.
   At least 3 million Afghan refugees live in border cities and
camps that serve as bases and supply points for Moslem rebels
fighting Afghanistan's Communist government and the 115,000 Soviet
soldiers aiding it.
   Under an agreement signed April 14 in Geneva, the Red Army is to
begin withdrawing May 15 and be out in nine months. Guerrillas
began fighting after a Communist coup in April 1978 and say they
will continue the war.
   Official Kabul radio reported Monday night from Afghanistan that
guerrillas attacked a textile factory in the western city of Herat
``recently.'' It also reported ``a number of rockets'' seized in
the Bagrami section of Kabul.
   It gave neither dates nor details but referred to a ``satanic
plot of extremist opposition elements,'' a standard way of
describing the insurgents.
</TEXT>
