<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Angola     05-02 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Angola,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha Downplays Talks On Angolan War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha repeated
the South African position Monday that Cuban troops must withdraw
from Angola before there can be peace in southern Africa.
   His comments in Parliament dampened prospects for a diplomatic
breakthrough on the Angolan civil war at a meeting set for Tuesday
and Wednesday in Britain. It involves Angola, Cuba, the United
States and South Africa.
   Cuba has more than 40,000 troops in Angola supporting the
Marxist government. South Africa and the United States back the
pro-Western rebels of UNITA, the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola.
   ``I want to warn against being too over-optimistic because there
are ... major mischief makers all over the world who want to
destroy every positive effort to bring about better conditions in
southern Africa,'' Botha said. ``The moment the Cubans leave that
part of southern Africa and it is safe, then South Africa's forces
will leave too.''
   Angola claims South Africa has 9,000 soldiers with heavy
artillery in southern Angola. South Africa acknowledges having
forces there but says the number has not exceeded 3,000 at any time
in the past year.
   South Africa is fighting a bush war in South-West Africa, which
it controls against the wishes of the United Nations, with the
South-West Africa People's Organization. The guerrilla group, known
as SWAPO, operates from bases in southern Angola.
   When the London talks begin, it will be the first time
delegations from the United States, South Africa, Cuba and Angola
have met at the same table to discuss plans for peace in the
region. The future of South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, is
expected to be included in the negotiations.
   The United States and South Africa want a timetable for
withdrawal of Cuban troops. Angola and the Soviet Union, its other
main ally, insist that South Africa withdraw from Namibia as
demanded in a 1966 U.N. resolution so the territory can become
independent.
   Previous efforts at a settlement have stalled, in part because
of U.S. support for South Africa's demand that Cuban troops leave
Angola before the South Africans leave Namibia.
   Botha said Monday that South Africa would like to see Namibia
``progress toward independence, but we cannot afford to allow
foreign troops in the region dictate how'' it is achieved.
 
</TEXT>
