<HEAD>BBC Says Three Legionnaires' Cases Confirmed, 13 More Suspected</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to clarify total number of BBC cases;
picks up 3rd graf pvs: No further...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three cases of Legionnaires' disease have been
confirmed among people who worked in or near British Broadcasting
Corp. buildings, and 13 more cases are suspected, the BBC said
Monday.
   Two of the confirmed cases involve a BBC doorman and a BBC
workman. A total of nine BBC employees have the disease or are
suspected of having it.
   No information was available about the other victims.
   Health officials checked and disinfected air conditioning
systems in the main Broadcasting House in central London. They also
were checking a BBC building on nearby Duchess Street and any other
possible sources of infection.
   Legionnaires' disease produces symptoms similar to pneumonia and
is often caused by bacteria from water-cooled air conditioning
units.
   The disease takes its name from the July 1976 outbreak at the
Pennsylvania American Legion convention in Philadelphia, where 221
people contracted it and 34 died.
   American doctors say Legionnaires' disease has proved fatal in
about 15 percent of cases.
   The disease has killed almost 200 people in Britain since 1979,
Independent Television News reported.
