<HEAD>Army Moves In To Quell Ethnic Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities clamped an indefinite
curfew on western Karachi Monday after the army moved in to quell
three days of ethnic violence that left at least five people dead
and 50 injured, police said.
   Local newspapers put the death toll at seven.
   Fighting between Mohajirs and rival Pathans began late Friday
after a traffic accident.
   Mohajirs are Moslems who emigrated from India after its
partition in 1947. The Pathans, who trace their roots to northern
Pakistan, consider themselves natives although they now live in
Pakistan's southernmost city.
   Police restored calm on Saturday but violence broke out again on
Sunday as residents celebrated May Day.
   Troops moved in to help police, and the district was reported
calm Monday.
   The violence centered in Orangi Township, where Mohajirs are
surrounded by Pathan neighborhoods.
   Battles between the two groups in 1986 killed hundreds of people.
