<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Prison     05-02 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Prison,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates Give Up Hostage and Control of Cell Block</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERTH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inmates freed a guard they held for 17
hours and gave up control of the largest cell block Monday, ending
the eighth serious disturbance at Perth prison in less than two
years.
   The government's Scottish Office said guard Tom Mortimer, 25,
appeared to be well. He was held in C hall, the largest cellblock,
where about 100 inmates barricaded themselves inside.
   Soon after his release, a fire engine went into the prison to
put out a small fire, the office said. It announced two hours after
Mortimer's release that the 100 inmates had surrendered a few at a
time.
   ``There has been some damage to C hall, how much remains to be
quantified,'' said a spokesman, who in keeping with British
practice was not identified by name.
   How many of the 100 inmates were directly involved in the
hostage-taking was not known, the spokesman said.
   During the siege, convicts had waved a guard's cap from a window
and set fire to pieces of what looked like a guard's clothing.
   Mortimer was seized Sunday. Soon afterward banners were hung
from a window protesting about the legal system. Guards said
prisoners also wanted an investigation of conditions, a better
chance at parole and segregation of young prisoners and those
awaiting trial.
   Perth prison now holds 449 men, 11 over capacity, but the
population has gone as high as 600 in recent months.
   Protests at Perth since August 1986 include the burning of an
entire cellblock; holding of a rooftop by three inmates for 41
hours, ended by an assault squad of six guards; a hunger strike,
and destruction of cell furniture.
   Other protests at Scottish prisons have occurred in Edinburgh,
Peterhead and Glasgow.
   Most British prisons were built in Victorian times and are
notoriously overcrowded and unsanitary.
   About 51,000 people are imprisoned in Britain, almost 20 percent
above capacity and the highest proportion of population in the
12-nation European Economic Community. About 19,000 prisoners are
held two and three to cells designed for one.
</TEXT>
