<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Laos-MIA     05-02 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Laos-MIA,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Team Heading To Laos For MIA Search</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. military team is to fly to Laos
on Tuesday to search for the remains of missing Americans at the
site where an aircraft was shot down more than 22 years ago,
officials said.
   It is the third Laos-U.S. excavation of an American warplane
crash site.
   Ross Petzing, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok, said
Monday that 15 military specialists are to fly from Bangkok to
Savannakhet city in the southern panhandle area of Laos. The crash
site is 95 miles east of Savannkhet.
   Excavation is expected to take about a week, he said.
   The experts are from the U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution Center
and the Army Central Identification Laboratory, both Honolulu-based
agencies entrusted with resolving the fates of Americans missing in
action from the Vietnam War.
   They will be working with officials of Laos' Defense and Foreign
ministries, Petzing said.
   A total of 555 Americans are missing in Laos. The remains of 19
missing Americans were recovered during joint excavations in that
communist country in 1985 and 1986, said Maj. Tim Pfister, a
spokesman for the U.S. Pacific Command.
   The U.S. team is looking for the remains of two American airmen
whose OV-1A Mohawk aircraft was downed by heavy ground fire while
on a reconnaissance mission on March 15, 1966, Pfister said.
   Pfister said another U.S. aircraft on the mission reported that
one of the crewmen of the stricken Mohawk parachuted out before the
plane crashed.
   U.S. military experts said they saw no trace of remains during a
preliminary inspection of the wreckage last week. The aircraft
manufacturer confirmed the wreckage was an OV-1A Mohawk, Petzing
said.
   A number of U.S. planes were shot down in eastern Laos while on
missions aimed at blocking the Ho Chi Minh Trail, which the North
Vietnamese communists used to infiltrate men and supplies into
U.S.-backed South Vietnam.
   Laos agreed in August last year to accelerate progress on the
MIA issue while the United States pledged to respond to its calls
for humanitarian assistance.
</TEXT>
