<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 2009EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RapeSurvey 1stLd-Writethru a0706 05-02 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rape Survey, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0706,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Students Find Rape Acceptable In Some Instances</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf ``65 percent'' to CORRECT to 47 sted 57
percent</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly one-quarter of the boys and
one-sixth of the girls responding to a survey on rape said it was
acceptable for a man to force a woman to have sex with him if he
has spent money on her.
   The survey was taken by 1,700 sixth- to ninth-graders who
attended the Rhode Island Rape Crisis Center's assault awareness
program at schools across the state.
   ``I didn't believe it,'' Jacqueline Jackson Kikuchi, the center
staff member who conducted the poll, said of the results. She
presented the findings Friday at the National Symposium on Child
Victimization in Anaheim, Calif.
   Kukuchi said she was most surprised by the students' answers on
whether it would be acceptable for a man to rape a woman if he had
dated her for a long time or spent money on her.
   ``Basically, the kids were very much into blaming the victim of
the sexual assault,'' she said.
   Among the findings:
   _ 50 percent of the students said a woman who walks alone at
night and dresses seductively is asking to be raped.
   _ 51 percent of the boys and 41 percent of the girls said a man
has the right to force a woman to kiss him if he has spent ``a lot
of money'' on her. The quantity of money was defined by
12-year-olds as $10 to $15.
   _ Among students in grades 7 through nine, 24 percent of the
boys and 16 percent of the girls said it was acceptable for a man
to force a woman to have sex with him if he has spent money on her.
   _ 65 percent of the boys and 47 percent of the girls in seventh
through ninth grades said it is acceptable for a man to force a
woman to have sex if they have been dating for more than six months.
   _ 87 percent of the boys and 79 percent of the girls said rape
is OK if a couple were married.
   ``So many of our kids have attitudes that sexual abuse is OK,''
Kikuchi said.
   The types of attitudes evidenced in the survey probably lead to
date rape and other forms of sexual assault, she said.
   Twenty percent of the girls and 6 percent of the boys taking the
survey said they had been sexually abused.
   Thirty-one percent of the boys and 32 percent of the girls said
it would not be improper for a man to rape a woman who has had
previous sexual experiences.
   Kikuchi conducted the survey from February to December 1987,
when she gave workshops to students at public and private schools
as coordinator of the center's assault awareness program.
   The workshops have been successful in changing some attitudes,
Kikuchi said. After the seminars, she said, less than 25 percent of
the participants think rape or forced kissing is appropriate in any
situation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-02 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Brings Snow to Colorado, Wyoming; High Winds over Plains,
Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful storm covered parts of Colorado and Wyoming Monday
with up to a foot of snow and sent strong winds gusting through
much of the Rockies and Great Plains.
   The storm, centered over southwestern Kansas, brought rain to
much of the Plains region, with thunderstorms hitting central and
western Kansas and central Nebraska.
   Six to 12 inches fell in the Palmer Lake area north of Colorado
Springs, Colo., and up to 11 inches was reported at Jelm, Wyo.
Denver reported 2 inches of snow.
   Parts of the Black Hills on the western edge of South Dakota
also received up to 8 inches of snow.
   A snow advisory was in effect for southeast Wyoming, with up to
three inches expected, and a warning for high winds and blowing
snow was in effect for southeast Colorado.
   Winds gusted to 83 mph at La Junta, Colo. and to 64 mph at
Colorado Springs. A tornado touched down in extreme southeastern
Colorado but did no damage.
   High winds prevailed from Texas to the Dakotas. Amarillo and
Lubbock, Texas, both reported wind gusts of around 45 mph. A high
wind advisory was issued for mountain passes in western Texas and
southern New Mexico.
   Winds gusted to 49 mph at Williston, N.D. and at Rapid City, S.D.
   Rain fell throughout the Great Plains, with about three-quarters
of an inch recorded in Broken Bow and North Platte in central
Nebraska in the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT.
   Rain also fell in western Washington and Oregon, with snow in
mountain regions. A snow advisory was in effect for the Cascades in
Oregon, with 4 to 8 inches of new snow expected.
   Patchy, light rain hit the North Atlantic coast, with some heavy
showers and hail in eastern New York State.
   Sunshine prevailed over a wide region stretching from the Gulf
Coast to the Great Lakes. Temperatures rose to the 70s over the
Great Lakes and the Ohio and Tennessee valleys, and into the
mid-80s in Gulf Coast states.
   Boise, Idaho, had a record low for the date of 23 degrees and
Winnemucca, Nev., tied a record with 19. The nation's low was 10
degrees at Yellowstone and Jackson, Wyo.
   Freeze warnings were issued for the central and northwest
valleys of New Mexico, and for southeast Arizona above 4,000 feet.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 29 degrees at
Yellowstone, Wyo. to 85 degrees at Sarasota, Fla.; Meridian Naval
Air Station, Miss.; and Laredo, Texas.
   On Tuesday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast to extend
from Arkansas across the central Plains to portions of North Dakota
and western Minnesota. Rain and snow showers were forecast to
linger over the northern and central Rockies and the extreme
western parts of Nebraska and South Dakota. Showers were predicted
from western Idaho to the northern Pacific Coast.
   Highs in the 40s and 50s were forecast for western portions of
the northern and central Plains, the northern and central Rockies,
the northern Plateau and the Pacific Northwest. Highs were
predicted to be in the 50s in New York State and New England, 80s
from Florida and the Gulf Coast to most of Texas and the Southwest
deserts. The rest of the nation was forecast to have highs in the
60s and 70s.
</TEXT>
