<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 3rdLd-Writethru a0766 05-02 0922</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0766,0953</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Joins Strike at Lenin Shipyard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-21 UPDATE with steel workers heartened by Gdansk
strike, yard operations at minimum, Nowa Huta strikers may talk
with management. Picks up 22nd graf pvs, Poland's latest ...</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa proclaimed a strike Monday at
the huge Lenin shipyard in Gdansk, where Solidarity was born in
1980, in a major escalation of the weeklong labor turmoil in
communist Poland.
   It was the fourth strike in Poland in a week, the worst wave of
labor unrest since the government's December 1981 military
crackdown on Solidarity.
   The news heartened steelworkers in southern Poland, who no
longer were the country's only workers still on strike.
   ``We feel better now,'' said Jan Ciesielski, a member of the
steel strike committee.
   Authorities were reported mounting a nationwide roundup of
regional leaders of Solidarity.
   A Solidarity communique signed by Walesa and issued late Monday
said, ``A strike wave is covering the country. They are not just
local conflicts. They are across Poland because the cause is the
economic crisis and the lack of convincing reform policies that
would offer prospects for the future.''
   Workers want pay raises of 50-60 percent to balance prices,
which have risen 42 percent this year because of reductions in
subsidies by the Communist government.
   Walesa, winner of the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, still works as an
electrician at the Baltic coast Lenin yard employing 12,000
workers. He did not launch the strike but addressed strikers later
and announced his support, according to various activists.
   Walesa led the 1980 work stoppage at Gdansk which shook the
communist government to its roots and gave rise to Solidarity, the
first independent trade union federation in the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity was suppressed and outlawed under martial law.
   Monday evening, Solidarity's chaplain, the Rev. Henryk
Jankowski, presided in the shipyard at a prayer service attended by
Walesa, a newly formed strike committee and hundreds of workers.
   About 3,000 workers were occupying the yard late Monday, enough
to shut down operations, said Solidarity adviser Jacek Kuron. The
shipyard has a payroll of 12,000 workers.
   The government press office in Warsaw at first confirmed the
strike. But on Monday evening government spokesman Jerzy Urban
called The Associated Press and said there was only a rally by
several hundred people at the shipyard.
   ``It would be rather difficult for me to say the entire shipyard
is working in that atmosphere but, generally speaking, the shipyard
is working,'' he said. Kuron said police arrested nine regional
representatives on the 13-member Solidarity National Executive
Commission. Two commission members, including Walesa, were free and
whereabouts of two more were a mystery, he said.
   Union activists said the Gdansk strike began with a march around
the shipyard by dozens of workers after a breakfast break. The
march grew to 200 people and ended at the main gate.
   There, while shifts were changing at 2 p.m., the Solidarity
activists encouraged workers to strike, union supporters said.
   ``The strike action ... undoubtedly is in response to Lech
Walesa's call (on Sunday) for protest actions in support of the
striking Nowa Huta steelworkers,'' said Joanna Wojciechowicz, a
Solidarity activist in Gdansk.
   The workers formed a strike committee led by Alojzy Szablewski,
said a spokesman at St. Brygida's Church, a Solidarity stronghold
near the shipyard.
   Management agreed to talk to the strike committee Tuesday, Kuron
said.
   Walesa, chairman of the outlawed but still active labor
federation, said through spokesmen he stayed off the strike
committee to coordinate Solidarity activities nationwide.
   The strike by thousands of steelworkers at the Lenin steel works
in Nowa Huta outside Krakow entered its eighth day Tuesday.
   Poland's latest labor trouble began April 25 with a wildcat
action by transit workers in Bydgoszcz. It was settled the same day
with pay raises of at least 50 percent.
   Thousands of workers at the Stalowa Wola heavy machinery plant
in southeast Poland struck on Friday and ended the action Saturday
after promises of higher pay.
   About half the 3,500 workers at the Dolmel electronics plant in
Wroclaw, southwestern Poland, stopped work from about 10 a.m.
Monday to the end of the shift at 2 p.m., government and opposition
spokesmen reported. Jozef Pinior, a Solidarity leader, said it
ended when management promised a raise.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman urged
the Polish government to negotiate with workers and declared, ``The
use of force ... cannot contribute to national reconciliation.''
   Police surrounded the Gdansk shipyard and checked the papers of
people approaching the gates, a witness said.
   Banners declaring ``Sit-In Strike'' and ``Gdansk Shipyard on
Strike'' were draped on the main gate.
   Police detained Bogdan Lis, a Gdansk Solidarity leader, in
nearby Sopot, said Jankowski, the Solidarity chaplain.
   According to Andrzej Gwiazda, a Solidarity leader, the shipyard
strikers demand minimum pay of 60,000 zlotys a month ($150),
reinstatement of fired union activists, amnesty for strikers and
recognition of a local Solidarity chapter.
   Average monthly pay now is about 45,000 zlotys ($112).
   In August 1980, employees of one department of the Lenin
shipyard stopped work to protest the dismissal of Anna
Walentynowicz, a crane operator and activist in the free-union
movement.
   Walesa, a little-known union organizer who also had been
dismissed, vaulted the shipyard fence and took charge of the strike.
   In two dramatic weeks, the workers won guarantees for the first
independent union in the Soviet bloc and broad social political
concessions.
   Solidarity claimed 10 million members at its height.
</TEXT>
