<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RFK 1stLd-Writethru a0762 05-02 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-RFK, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0762,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Says His Brother Would Have Backed McNamara for President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new 3rd graf to add detail on McNamara; picks up 3rd
graf pvs, Speaking of...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President John F. Kennedy would have supported
his defense secretary, Robert McNamara, to succeed him in order to
keep Lyndon Johnson out of the White House, Robert Kennedy told
interviewers.
   The disclosure is contained in ``Robert Kennedy: In His Own
Words,'' a book based on heretofore unpublished interviews Kennedy
gave between 1964 and 1967. Excerpts appear in the current Newsweek
magazine. The book is scheduled for release in June, marking the
20th anniversary of Robert Kennedy's assassination.
   In the excerpts, Robert Kennedy is quoted as saying that his
brother ``thought of trying to move in the direction that would get
the nomination for McNamara.'' He said the president thought the
country ``should be placed in the best possible hands. And we
thought that McNamara was that individual.''
   Speaking of Johnson, Robert Kennedy said: ``In every
conversation I have with him he lies. ... He lies even when he
doesn't have to.''
   Kennedy, who remained as attorney general a short while after
his brother was assassinated in 1963, described Johnson as ``mean,
bitter, vicious _ an animal in many ways.''
   ``I think his reaction on a lot of things is correct, but I
think he's got this other side of him in his relationship with
human beings which makes it very difficult, unless you want to kiss
his behind all the time. That's what Bob McNamara suggested to me a
couple of weeks ago, if I wanted to get along. No, I can't do
that.''
   Kennedy also said Johnson remarked to Pierre Salinger, then the
presidential press secretary, that the slaying of the president
``was retribution for his participation in the assassinations'' of
the one-time leaders of the Dominican Republic and South Vietnam.
Elsewhere in the interviews, Kennedy asserts that his brother
opposed those assassinations.
   After quitting the Cabinet, Kennedy won election to the Senate
from New York and in 1968 was pursuing the presidential nomination
after Johnson decided not to seek re-election.
   Salinger told Newsweek that Sen. Eugene McCarthy tried to come
to Robert Kennedy's bedside just after he was fatally shot, but
Salinger headed him off. He said McCarthy, around whom dump-Johnson
sentiment had first coalesced, told him: ``What we should do now is
create a coalition and go back to Lyndon Johnson, tell him to run _
and we'll all support him.''
   The interviews were given as part of an oral history program for
the John F. Kennedy Library.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 2116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     05-02 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvador's Legislature Paralyzed By Vote Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing party's
presidential candidate on Monday appealed to the rightist
opposition to help resolve a crisis that has split the legislature.
   ``There is either going to be consensus or permanent impasse for
three years. And the country cannot withstand impasse,'' Adolfo Rey
Prendes, nominated at the Christian Democrats' convention on
Friday, told a news conference.
   The crisis stems from a dispute over which party controls one
seat in the 60-seat National Assembly, the unicameral legislature
that was elected March 20.
   The right-wing Republican National Alliance, or Arena, claims it
won 31 seats during the election and that the Christian Democrats,
who had previously held a majority, stole a seat through electoral
fraud. The Christian Democrats deny the charge.
   Arena has appealed the final vote count for the disputed seat to
the Supreme Court, but it was uncertain when the court would rule.
The rightists maintain that, for the moment, the Assembly has 59
members.
   The legislature was to have been inaugurated Sunday for a
three-year term. The 30 Arena deputies showed up and declared
congress in session.
   But the 30 other deputies _ 23 for the Christian Democrats and
seven for the National Conciliation Party _ gathered in another
room and held their own session.
   The Christian Democrats claimed the legislature no longer exists
because the constitution says that ``half plus one'' of the
Assembly's 60 members must be on hand for it to be installed or to
act.
   ``As of today, there is no national legislature,'' Rey Prendes
said.
   But Alfredo Cristiani, president of Arena, said only a majority
of the elected deputies is needed to install the congress. He said
his party has that majority in a 59-member Assembly.
   Rey Prendes said he believes the politicians can work things out.
   ``This kind of confrontation serves no one's purposes except
those of the guerrillas, who sit calmly in the mountains watching
us destroy each other,'' he said.
   Leftist rebels have been fighting the U.S.-supported government
since 1980.
   Arena exhibited its growing power with the upset in the
legislative elections. The Christian Democrats had 33 seats in the
previous National Assembly.
   Leftist guerrillas ordered vehicles to stay off El Salvador's
roads for an indefinite period beginning Tuesday. The transport
ban, the third called this year, was announced Monday on the
rebels' clandestine Radio Venceremos.
   Previous transport bans were enforced by rebels who burned the
vehicles of violators.
   The rebels said the measure was in response to an increase in
repression by the armed forces and police.
</TEXT>
