<DOCNO> AP880502-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 2118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nigeria     05-02 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nigeria,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikes End Following Negotiations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-week national strike over gasoline
price increases ended Monday after negotiations between government
and unions, the Labor Ministry said. The strikes had paralyzed
medical and banking services.
   After talks with eight union leaders, the government agreed to
labor's main demand that four detained union leaders be freed,
Labor Minister Aboubacar Umar said in a statement. He made no
mention of a second union demand that there be no further gasoline
price increases.
   There was no immediate comment from union leaders, nor were the
names of those being released immediately made available.
   Umar acknowledged that the rising cost of living in Nigeria,
Africa's most populous nation with an estimated 100 million people,
was a sensitive issue among workers.
   Student protests began in the north-central city of Jos on April
11, the day after the government increased gasoline prices by 3
percent. Demonstrations turned violent April 13 when thousands of
university students and Jos residents clashed with police, with six
people killed.
   The unrest quickly spread to other campuses around Nigeria and
labor unions joined the protest in defiance of government threats.
   The government raised the price of gasoline and diesel fuel in
what was expected to be the first of a series of increases. The
action followed World Bank and International Monetary Fund
recommendations to make gasoline prices higher to help reduce
Nigeria's $1.5 billion budget deficit.
   Many Nigerians have considered low gasoline prices as their
right since the boom days for oil-exporter Nigeria in the
mid-1970s. Even with the increases gas sells for about 40 cents a
gallon.
   The News Agency of Nigeria has reported the government was
holding many union officials, including the chairman of the Joint
Committee for Industrial Unions and the assistant secretary of the
National Association of Nurses and Midwives.
   Last week the news agency reported the president and
secretary-general of the National Railwaymen's Union were arrested,
though rail workers did not join the strike.
   The news agency said 11 union leaders in Kano were released on
bail Friday. A judge said they could get three years in prison if
convicted of taking part in walkouts. The government dismissed
thousands of civil servants in the strikes called April 19
involving banks, government and medical services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
