<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WorldBank-Panama     05-02 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bank-Panama,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Bank Lowers Status of Its Loans to Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama has paid nothing to the World Bank for
six months on the $502 million owed to it, the bank announced
Monday.
   As a consequence, the bank's loans to Panama have been placed in
a ``non-accrual status,'' which means the bank will no longer
include on its own statements the interest and other charges due
from Panama until money is actually received.
   The bank, owned by 151 countries, is the biggest single source
of aid money for the Third World. The United States is the largest
shareholder.
   ``Placing loans in a non-accrual status is an accounting action
which does not reduce in any way the country's obligation to the
bank or the bank's ability to assist the country in formulating
policies to help redress its economic difficulties,'' the
announcement said.
   Last Nov. 30, the bank stopped disbursing loans to Panama, as it
does to any borrowing country whenever payments on earlier loans
are more than 75 days overdue.
   Panama's financial situation has been deteriorating for almost a
year because of the political crisis there, and it's been
aggravated by U.S. actions taken to try to oust strongman Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, who was indicted earlier this year in
Florida on drug-trafficking charges.
   The situation became critical Feb. 26, the day Noriega
engineered the ouster of President Eric Arturo Delvalle for issuing
an order firing the general.
   Panama has 118 banks, and has been a major Latin American
financial center, but the banks have been closed to the public by
government order since March 4 because of cash shortages following
months-long runs on accounts and a U.S. freeze on Panamanian
assets. Some Panamanian and foreign banks reopened April 18 but
only to accept deposits.
</TEXT>
