<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama     05-02 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leaders Meet to Discuss Reported Noriega Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition party leaders met Monday
to study reports that strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega made a
deal with the U.S. government to resign.
   It was the first known meeting between the party leaders in the
nearly yearlong crisis.
   ``We met to discuss jointly the grave situation of our country
and what we may do together to find a democratic solution for our
country,'' Ricardo Arias Calderon of the Christian Democrat Party
told The Associated Press. The meeting was at his home.
   Other sources at the session said representatives of six
political parties met for more than two hours.
   One source, speaking with the condition he not be identified,
said the leaders discussed ``everything that has to do with the
serious crisis,'' including the reported arrangement between
Washington and Noriega, commander of the 15,000-member Defense
Forces.
   He did not elaborate on the talks.
   U.S. officials in Washington said Friday that Noriega had agreed
to step down as the military chief but refused to leave Panama, as
the United States and the Panamanian opposition had wanted.
   U.S. Treasury Secretary James A. Baker said Sunday that talks
with Noriega continued during the weekend and that ``progress is
being made.''
   Noriega on Saturday denied he had made any commitments to U.S.
envoys.
   Opposition leaders were alarmed at the report that Noriega might
be allowed to remain in the country even if he did resign. They
said such a change in the U.S. stand would be a ``serious mistake
that would not solve Panama's problems or bring democratization to
the country.''
   The Christian Democrats called the meeting and representatives
were sent by the Authentic Panamanian Party, the Republican Party
of ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle, the Liberal Republican
Nationalist Movement and factions of the Liberal and Labor parties.
The Authentic Panamanian Party is the largest opposition party
followed by the Christian Democrats.
   Delvalle was removed by the Noriega-controlled legislature on
Feb. 26, the day after he tried to fire the general.
   Noriega was indicted by a federal grand jury in Florida last
February on drug-trafficking charges, which he denies.
   Sources in the opposition said earlier that their leaders were
afraid the United States was bypassing them and ignoring promises
to them.
   They said if Noriega quits but remains in Panama he would
continue to wield power through the Defense Forces.
   ``He would continue to be a focus of controversy,'' Arias
Calderon said.
   The opposition also insists that chief executive Manuel Solis
Palma, named to replace Delvalle, not be allowed to remain in
office until the May 1989 elections.
   Demonstrations demanding Noriega's ouster began last summer
after Noriega's former second-in-command publicly accused the
general of involvement in political assassinations, electoral fraud
and corruption.
   The United States imposed economic sanctions on Panama after
Noriega was indicted on drug charges.
</TEXT>
