<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Venezuela-Campaign     05-02 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venezuela-Campaign,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parties Open Campaign for Presidential Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAROLD OLMOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campaigning for the December
presidential election began Monday with 72 parties entering the
race but only two considered to have a good chance of winning.
   They are the governing Social Democrats and the Social
Christians.
   The third-ranked Movement Towards Socialism and smaller parties
will seek to assure their survival by picking up congressional
seats.
   In the last presidential election in 1983, the two main parties
received 90 percent of the vote.
   Former President Carlos Andres Perez, 67, is the Social
Democrats candidate. He served as chief executive from 1974-79. The
constitution bars a president from seeking re-election to a second
consecutive term.
   The Social Christian candidate is 47-year-old Eduardo Fernandez,
an energetic campaigner known as The Tiger.
   In his opening rally in Caracas he called on the voters to ``say
no to the past.''
   Perez, vice-president of the Socialist International, began his
campaign with rallies in three cities _ Valencia, Cabimas and
Ciudad Guayana.
   During his previous administration the government nationalized
the vital oil industry and began to strengthen and expand the iron,
aluminum and hydroelectric industries in the Guayana region.
   But it also was under Perez that the country contracted a big
portion of its $33 billion debt.
   President Jaime Lusinchi has struggled through much of his
five-year term with severe economic problems caused mainly by
falling oil prices.
   Government officials say unemployment is running at 10 percent,
double the rate of a decade ago. Last year inflation was a record
40.3 percent.
   Venezuela has had elected governments since the fall of dictator
Gen. Marcos Perez Jimenez in January 1958.
</TEXT>
