<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Poland,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass Reports May Day Demonstrations in Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tass reported Monday that opposition forces in
Poland boycotted the official May Day celebrations and said
anti-government demonstrators were ``particularly aggressive'' in
Warsaw and Gdansk.
   The official Soviet news agency did not mention the Polish labor
strife, referring only to ``the current situation in Poland.''
   The brief article said official celebrations of May Day had been
targeted by anti-government groups. It quoted Polish government
spokesman Jerzy Urban as saying: ``The calls for boycotts by the
opposition forces have been disregarded.''
   Tass made no mention of clashes between police and opposition
groups, but said 12,000 people took part nationwide in
anti-government demonstrations.
   Opposition spokesman in Warsaw claimed at least 30,000 people
joined in the demonstrations.
   The Soviet news media has been silent about the strikes, the
most serious labor problem for Poland's communist authorities since
the independent Solidarity union was chartered in the fall of 1980.
   Solidarity, the only free union federation in the Soviet bloc,
was suspended in December 1981 and subsequently outlawed by
Parliament.
   The Solidarity underground supports the current strikes and also
backed the boycott of government May Day observances.
   Although the Soviet media has not mentioned the labor unrest,
many Soviets have heard about it through foreign radio broadcasts.
   Tass quoted Urban as accusing Western broadcasters of ``total
falsification'' of events in Poland.
</TEXT>
