<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Reporter     05-02 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Reporter,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Reporter Jailed In Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter for a West German
newspaper was sentenced to 12 days in jail for failing to report
his stay in the country to police, a Swiss diplomat said Monday.
   Roland Hofwiller, a Swiss citizen who reports for West Berlin's
independent Tageszeitung, was arrested April 28 and convicted by a
court in Zagreb, the capital of Croatia.
   Hofwiller, a roving East European correspondent, was making a
private visit to Yugoslavia when he was arrested, said Monika
Stinner, charge d'affaires of the Swiss Consulate.
   ``He came to Zagreb and stayed with a girlfriend in her
apartment. They have a child he acknowledged as his own,'' she said.
   Foreigners are expected to report their stay to the Yugoslav
police within a day unless they stay at state-run hotels.
   Nikola Barovic, a Belgrade lawyer who said Hofwiller appointed
him as his counsel, told the AP the rule has been seldom
implemented, ``only when somebody's ears need to be punched.''
   Hofwiller's articles about ethnic problems in Yugoslavia were
reprinted in two Yugoslav youth weeklies, Mladost of Ljubljana and
Studentski List of Zagreb.
   Both newspapers have come under frequent official attacks for
publishing non-conformist views.
