<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 2219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Saints     05-02 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Saints,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Completes Last Step For July 3 Canonization Of US Nun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II completed the formalities
Monday for the naming of seven new saints, including Rose
Philippine Duschesne, a French-born American nun.
   John Paul asked the College of Cardinals at a consistory Monday
to approve the decrees and it did so. The step is the last before
canonization.
   Hundreds of people from France and the United States are
expected to attend the July 3 canonization of Mother Duschesne, the
founder of the U.S. branch of the Society of The Sacred Heart.
   Mother Duchesne was born Aug. 29, 1769, in Grenoble, France. For
10 years during the French revolution, she devoted herself to
charity, often sheltering priests persecuted by the revolutionary
government.
   She emigrated in 1818 to the United States, where she founded
the Sacred Heart teaching order and a mission school for Potawatomi
Indian girls in Sugar Creek, Kan. Pope Pius XII beatified her in
1940.
   Also on July 3, John Paul will canonize Simone de Roxas, a
Spanish priest who founded the secular Congregation of Ave Maria.
   In a ceremony May 16, the pope will make saints of three Jesuit
priests who dedicated their lives to evangelizing Indians and were
martyred in South America in 1628. They are Roque Gonzales, born in
what is now Asuncion, Paraguay; Alfonso Rodriquez of Zamora, Spain,
and Juan del Castillo of Belmonte, Spain.
   On Oct. 3, the pope will canonize Maddalena Marchesa di Canossa
of Verona, Italy, founder of the Sons and Daughters of Charity, and
on Dec. 11, Maria Rosa Molas y Vallve, a Spanish nun who founded
the Sisters of Consolation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 2225EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WHO     05-02 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WHO,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS and Anti-Smoking Programs Among Top Items at WHO conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 assembly of the World Health Organization
opened Monday and high on the agenda were programs to check the
spread of AIDS and an anti-smoking campaign.
   About 1,200 delegates from WHO's 166 member countries will elect
a successor to Dr. Halfdan Mahler of Denmark as director general of
the U.N. agency.
   Dr. Hiroshi Nakajima, 59, a Japanese specialist in
pyschopharmacology, was designated for the post last January by the
31-member Executive Board. Confirmation by the assembly, scheduled
for Wednesday, is a virtual certainty.
   Mahler, head of the agency since 1973, did not seek a fourth
five-year term.
   Delegates at the two-week assembly will consider a proposed
zero-growth, two-year budget of $639.9 million. Not included in the
budget is funding for WHO's Special Program on AIDS, which
officials have said would require $66 million this year.
   The number of AIDS cases was officially reported last week as
exceeding 88,000, but the actual number is known to be much higher.
   WHO officials have urged further implemtation of the agency's
campaign against smoking as ``the major avoidable cause of
ill-health.''
   AIDS, acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a fatal disease in
which a virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers.
   It can be transmitted through sexual contact; transfusions of
tainted blood or blood products, or sharing contaminated hypodermic
needles or syringes. AIDS can also be passed from mother to child
at or before birth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
