<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh-Rebels     05-02 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Rebels,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill 13</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buddhist rebels attacked Moslem
settlements in southeastern Bangladesh and killed 13 people,
military officials said Monday.
   The slayings raised to 36 the number of deaths blamed on the
insurgents in the past week, officials said.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said two
villages in the Chittagong Hill Tracts area were raided Sunday
night, apparently by the same band of armed rebels. The victims
included six women and four children, they said.
   At least nine people were injured in the attacks.
   Members of the Buddhist Chakma tribes, descendants of the
Mongols, have been seeking an independent homeland since 1974. They
say their tribal culture is being overwhelmed by the influx of
Moslem settlers from other parts of Bangladesh.
   An estimated 4,000 people have died in rebel attacks and
Bangladesh army actions against the insurgents. An estimated 50,000
tribal members have fled to India to escape the violence.
   Military officials said rebels on Sunday attacked Karmangipuri
village, 2 miles from the Indian border, and killed three women and
two children. The rebels fled after soldiers from a nearby camp
opened fire, they said. There was no word of injuries to the
insurgents.
   In the second attack, the rebels stormed Malangipara village,
about 10 miles from the frontier. Eight people, including three
women and two children, were killed, the officials said.
</TEXT>
