<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AIDSRobber     05-02 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Robber,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Robber Slain After Threatening Hostages With AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police sharpshooter killed a
gunman holding six people inside a bank on Monday after the man
threatened to inject his hostages with blood he said contained the
AIDS virus, police said.
   Police said they got the man drunk so they could get the
hostages out safely.
   The man seized six bank workers during an attempt to rob the
branch of Banorte Bank in Massoro, about 1,875 miles northeast of
Rio. Police surrounded the bank after security guards saw a man
threatening a teller with a revolver.
   Police and a journalist negotiated for eight hours with the
robber, who said he escaped from Sao Paulo prison and was a carrier
of acquired immune deficiency syndrome, the fatal disease that
destroys the body's immune system.
   The man, who identified himself only as ``Falcone,'' was shot
after he drank several bottles of beer provided by police, said
Officer Jose Nazareno.
   ``We gave him lots of beer to get him drunk. We hoped that way
we'd be able to get the hostages out safely,'' Nazareno told The
Associated Press by telephone. ``We had no choice but to kill him.
He was threatening the hostages with a syringe full of blood and a
revolver.''
   The robber had demanded a getaway car, a second revolver and a
rifle before he would free the hostages. He also wanted to be
allowed to escape with $75,000.
</TEXT>
