<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 2338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Rankin     05-02 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Rankin,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sir Hugh Rankin, British Eccentric, Dies at 88</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir Hugh Rankin, who has died at the age of 88,
was an aristocrat turned communist and a man who claimed records in
pastimes ranging from playing golf to crawling under trees.
   His death on April 25 deprived Britain of what The Daily
Telegraph on Monday called ``an extraordinary character whose
eccentricity was remarkable even by the rarefied standards of the
baronetage.''
   Rankin's self-composed entry in Who's Who takes up four times as
much space in that 1,972-page tome as Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's.
   It is strewn with superlatives, ranging from oldest surviving
member of the 1st Royal Dragoon Guards that fought in Ireland in
1920-22 to holding ``an amateur record amongst golfers of Great
Britain in having played on 382 separate courses of UK and Eire.''
   Rankin's pursuits ran from sheep-shearing in Australia between
1928 and 1931 to riding bicycles to the top of mountains to
exploring old Roman roads.
   ``Wife and himself are only persons who have crawled under dwarf
fir forest for last { mile of most northerly known section of any
Roman road in Europe, terminating opposite end of Kirriemuir Golf
Course,'' his Who's Who entry revealed.
   Rankin was born in the Tunisian desert on Aug. 8, 1899, the son
of big-game hunter Sir Reginald Rankin.
   Christened Hubert Charles Rhys Rankin, he was educated at
upper-crust Harrow high school but ran away to work in a Belfast
shipyard, joined the dragoons and became a champion cavalry
swordsman. He received a disability discharge after he was shot by
a Irish sniper.
   At 46, he changed his name from Hubert to Hugh, one of several
such alterations he would make, including the addition of Omar
during his Moslem period. He went from Christian to Moslem to
Buddhist.
   In 1935, he became president of the British Moslem Society but
resigned weeks later after a rowdy society meeting. ``They were
very rude ... and knew nothing of law and order or methods of
procedure,'' he was quoted as saying.
   From 1944, according to Who's Who, he was ``a practicing
Non-Theistic Theravada Buddhist'' who ``performed Holy Buddhist
Pilgrimage Nov. 1944, the second Britisher to do so.''
   Rankin served as an army captain in World War II, but according
to the Telegraph regretted fighting for Britain, saying: ``If a
revolution comes _ and come it must after the next world war _ I'll
do my damnedest to see it succeeds.''
   In 1950 he was elected to Perth County Council declaring himself
``a blood-red militant communist in every possible way.''
   Fifteen years later he claimed to be the only baronet living on
social welfare. He said he would take any job ``except being a
butler. I hate snobbishness.''
   His first wife, Helen, died in 1945. He is survived by Robina,
his second wife.
   A death notice in The Times of London said Rankin died in a
hospital and was cremated in a private service. Cause of death was
not disclosed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 2330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DysonAide 1stLd-Writethru a0814 05-02 0797</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dyson Aide, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0814,0815</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maryland Democrats Rally To Congressman After Aide's Suicide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf ``Police said'' with two grafs to UPDATE with
report in Tuesday Times about details of note.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maryland Democrats Monday rallied around
U.S. Rep. Roy P. Dyson following the weekend suicide of his top
aide, and Republicans began talking about mounting a stronger
challenge for the congressman's seat.
   Dyson remained in seclusion Monday following the death of his
administrative assistant, Tom Pappas, who plunged 16 stories to his
death Sunday from the window of his Manhattan hotel room.
   The Washington Post carried a front-page story the same day
quoting former Dyson aides as saying the congressman had ceded
control of his office to Pappas, who recruited single, young men as
employees and pressured them to socialize with him.
   Before his death, Pappas, 46, talked with friends about the
article, which quoted staff members as complaining of his unusual
demands, including that one unidentified employee perform a
striptease at a staff retreat, the Post reported Monday.
   Police said Pappas left a poem on hotel stationery. An officer
who saw it said the unsigned eight-line verse spoke of the ``dark
and ugly world'' and ended with a reference to ``crashing,'' The
New York Times reported in Tuesday's editions.
   ``Goodbye'' was neatly printed on the sheet, which was lined
notebook paper rather than stationery and bore no addressee, the
Times said.
   Dyson, Pappas and Todd Skipper, another aide, were in New York
to meet with a lawyer and attend the Broadway musical ``Phantom of
the Opera,'' police there said.
   Dyson and Skipper were interviewed by police Sunday. Dyson's
office, which said it did not know the lawmaker's whereabouts,
issued a brief statement Monday from Dyson expressing sympathy to
Pappas' friends and family.
   ``Tom was my friend and political ally for almost two decades,''
Dyson said. ``All of us who had the privilege of working with him
will miss him more than we can say.''
   Democratic officials predicted Dyson, 39, would win re-election
in November, although they said his reaction to Pappas' death would
be crucial.
   ``I don't think Roy has any trouble. I think Roy is popular'' in
his 1st Congressional District, Maryland's Democratic Gov. William
Donald Schaefer said.
   John Willis, vice chairman of the state Democratic party, said
Dyson's standing with the voters ``is good enough that he'll be
able to weather this.'' But he cautioned that Dyson's ``reaction to
this is going to be the key.''
   Republican leaders said they are thinking of asking Wayne
Gilchrest, a political novice who won the party's nomination in the
March primary, to consider stepping aside so a better-known
candidate can challenge Dyson. But they said they won't try to
force out Gilchrest.
   ``The nomination was won fair and square by Wayne Gilchrest, and
I think we have to take our lead from him,'' Nelson Warfield,
executive director of the Maryland Republican Party, said.
   ``Our role is to explain to him exactly what is involved in
being a challenger.''
   The (Baltimore) Evening Sun quoted Gilchrest as saying he
expects to be asked to quit, but that he does not plan to step
aside.
   Former Rep. Robert Bauman, a Republican who lost the seat to
Dyson in 1980, said Pappas' death ``could hurt him (Dyson), it
could defeat him. But I think it depends on the further revelations
about what drove Mr. Pappas to his suicide.''
   ``I would warn the Republican party, my own party, not to make
an issue of this,'' Bauman added.
   Bauman lost the seat to Dyson in 1980 after Bauman was charged
with soliciting sex from a 16-year-old male prostitute in
Washington. The charge was later dropped although Bauman
acknowledged he was homosexual and an alcoholic.
   The New York medical examiner's office said an autopsy showed
Pappas' death was caused by multiple internal and external
injuries. Pappas fell from his 24th-floor room to an eighth-floor
ledge.
   Spokeswoman Ellen Borakove said toxicology tests performed over
the next week to 10 days would determine whether drugs or alcohol
were present in his system. An official classification of his
death, which police have called a suicide, will await the test
results, she said.
   The Post article came as the Federal Election Commission
investigated allegations Dyson's campaign disclosure reports
concealed $6,650 in payments to Pappas.
   Political consultant Michael Ford said he talked by phone with
Pappas about the Post article for 25 minutes Sunday morning. Pappas
told Ford he was worried that the article had irreparably damaged
his career and had hurt Dyson's re-election chances, the Post
reported Monday.
   ``I told him, `You've done nothing illegal, you've done nothing
immoral and therefore I think you can deal with this,''' Ford said,
adding he didn't think Pappas was particularly depressed.
</TEXT>
