<NOTE>For Release Tuesday, May 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, May 10, the 131st day of 1988. There are 235
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On May 10, 1869, a golden spike was driven at Promontory, Utah,
marking the completion of the first transcontinental railroad in
the United States.
   On this date:
   In 1774, Louis XVI ascended the throne of France.
   In 1775, Ethan Allen and his Green Mountain Boys captured the
British-held fortress at Ticonderoga, N.Y.
   In 1818, American patriot Paul Revere died in Boston.
   In 1865, Union forces captured Confederate President Jefferson
Davis in Irwinville, Ga.
   In 1908, the first Mother's Day observance took place during
church services in Grafton, W.Va., and Philadelphia.
   In 1924, J. Edgar Hoover was named FBI director.
   In 1933, the Nazis staged massive public book burnings in
Germany.
   In 1940, British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain resigned,
and Winston Churchill formed a new government.
   In 1968, preliminary Vietnam peace talks began in Paris.
   In 1977, actress Joan Crawford died in New York.
   In 1981, voters in France elected Socialist Francois Mitterrand
president over incumbent Valery Giscard d'Estaing.
   Ten years ago: Funeral services were held for former Italian
Prime Minister Aldo Moro, who was abducted and killed by the Red
Brigades. Britain's Princess Margaret and the Earl of Snowdon
announced they were getting a divorce after 18 years of marriage.
   Five years ago: A federal appeals court in Washington reinstated
the ABSCAM bribery conviction of former Florida Congressman Richard
Kelly, ruling the FBI's conduct in the case ``did not reach
intolerable levels.''
   One year ago: President Reagan visited Tuskegee University, one
of the nation's oldest black educational institutions, where he
told graduating seniors his administration ``won't be satisifed
until every American who wants a job has a job and is earning a
decent living.''
   Today's birthdays: Former Speaker of the House Carl Albert is
80. Actress Nancy Walker is 67. TV and radio personality Gary Owens
is 52. Singer Donovan is 42. Olympic medalist skiers and twins Phil
Mahre and Steve Mahre are 31.
   Thought for today: ``Men tire themselves in pursuit of rest.'' _
Laurence Sterne, English author (1713-1768).
</TEXT>
