<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wednesday, May 11</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Wednesday, May 11, the 132nd day of 1988. There are 234
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   One hundred years ago, on May 11, 1888, songwriter Irving Berlin
was born Israel Baline in Temun, Russia. During his career, Berlin
wrote some 1,500 songs, many of which have become standards:
``White Christmas,'' ``Easter Parade,'' ``God Bless America,'' and
``There's No Business Like Show Business.''
   On this date:
   In 1647, Peter Stuyvesant arrived in New Amsterdam to become
governor.
   In 1858, Minnesota became the 32nd state of the Union.
   In 1910, Glacier National Park was established in Montana.
   In 1943, during World War II, American forces landed on
Japanese-held Attu island in the Aleutians. (The territory was
retaken in three weeks.)
   In 1947, the B.F. Goodrich Co. of Arkon, Ohio, announced the
development of a tubeless tire.
   In 1949, Israel was admitted to the United Nations as its 59th
member.
   In 1949, Siam changed its named to Thailand.
   In 1973, charges against Daniel Ellsberg for his role in the
``Pentagon Papers'' case were dismissed by a judge who cited
government misconduct.
   In 1981, reggae artist Bob Marley died at age 36 in a Miami
hospital.
   In 1982, advice columnist Abigail Van Buren admitted reusing
letters without informing her readers, after a similar admission by
her twin sister, advice columnist Ann Landers.
   In 1984, eight teen-agers were killed when fire broke out inside
the Haunted Castle at the Six Flags Great Adventure Park in Jackson
Township, N.J.
   In 1985, 56 people died when a flash fire swept a jam-packed
soccer stadium in Bradford, England.
   Ten years ago: Israelis celebrated the 30th anniversary of their
country's independence with a military parade and picnics.
   Five years ago: Secretary of State George P. Shultz returned to
Washington after a tour of the Middle East, expressing confidence
Syria would withdraw its troops from Lebanon along with Israeli
forces, despite early Syrian opposition to the proposal.
   One year ago: Former National Security Adviser Robert C.
McFarlane began testifying at the Iran-Contra hearings. The trial
of former Gestapo official Klaus Barbie began in Lyons, France. And
in a medical first, doctors in Baltimore transplanted the heart and
lungs of an auto accident victim to a patient who gave up his own
heart to a second recipient.
   Today's birthdays: Composer-lyricist Irving Berlin is 100.
Modern dancer pioneer Martha Graham is 94. Surrealist artist
Salvador Dali is 84. Actor-comedian Foster Brooks is 76. Actor
Denver Pyle is 68. Comedian Mort Sahl is 61.
   Thought for Today: ``Life is 10 percent what you make it, and 90
percent how you take it.'' _ Irving Berlin.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
