<DOCNO> AP880502-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:D'OylyCarte Adv06   05-02 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: D'Oyly Carte, Adv 06,0628</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, May 6 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Gilbert and Sullivan's Original Company Lives Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The D'Oyly Carte Opera Company has been revived
and is once again ready for the road with the rollicking songs of
Gilbert and Sullivan that made it famous a century ago.
   The company went out singing on Feb. 27, 1982, with a
performance of ``H.M.S. Pinafore'' at London's Adelphi Theater.
   Dame Bridget D'Oyly Carte, the founder's granddaughter, was in
that audience. She died in 1985 and her will left the bulk of her
$7.8 million estate to trustees who had run the company until its
demise.
   The new company in the northeast town of Sunderland opened a
10-day run of ``Iolanthe'' and ``The Yeomen of the Guard'' on April
28.
   The Gilbert and Sullivan operas, an art form as distinctly
English as bowler hats and tea and crumpets, remain hugely popular
throughout the world. Productions of such hits as ``The Mikado,''
``The Pirates of Penzance'' and ``H.M.S. Pinafore'' regularly
appear on stages from elementary schools to Broadway.
   ``We are riding the crest of a wave,'' said Richard Condon, the
company's general manager. ``If you look around the West End (of
London), audiences are going for entertaining musicals and we are
going for a lively style.''
   A three-month tour through seven other cities in England and
Scotland follows the Sunderland premiere, and the company also
hopes to book a run in London.
   ``We are already talking about taking the company to the United
States, Canada and Australia,'' Condon said. ``Inquiries began
coming in from agents as soon as we announced on March 1 that we
were back.''
   The D'Oyly Carte Company thrived for 107 years on the works of
librettist Sir William Schwenck Gilbert and composer Sir Arthur
Sullivan, who collaborated on 14 operettas over 25 years.
   The style was burlesque, poking satirical fun at politics, the
law and society with outrageous puns and far-fetched rhymes.
   Some Gilbertian phrases entered everyday speech, such as
``things are seldom what they seem,'' ``the upper crust,'' ``a
policeman's lot is not a happy one,'' ``language that would make
your hair curl'' and ``blow your own trumpet.''
   Richard D'Oyly Carte founded the company in 1875 to stage the
operettas and built the Savoy Hotel and the neighboring Savoy
Theater from the proceeds.
   Royalties flowed in from thousands more productions abroad, but
there was widespread pirating.
   In 1879 alone more than 150 unauthorized productions of ``H.M.S.
Pinafore'' played in 60 cities in the United States, according to
Brian Jones who edits The W.S. Gilbert Journal for Gilbert and
Sullivan fans worldwide.
   D'Oyly Carte hit back by staging his own ``H.M.S. Pinafore'' in
New York in 1879, and in 1880 he had five companies touring the
United States.
   Condon said the new 103-member company plans two operas a year
and has new costumes, new sets, a chorus of 32 and an orchestra of
33.
   Bramwell Tovey, the company's music director and formerly music
director of the Royal Ballet, has re-examined the surviving
operetta scores and revived long-forgotten notations and directions.
   ``For years, the old company clung to one directional format and
maybe that led to its running out of steam,'' said Condon. ``Also,
as copyright on each work expired after 100 years, the fall in
royalties coincided with rocketing costs.''
   The original company lost $446,500 in 1981 and had to cancel a
U.S. tour. The government-funded Arts Council refused an appeal for
help, pronouncing the D'Oyly Carte style ``wooden and tired.''
   Condon said $945,000 was budgeted for the new ``Iolanthe'' and
``Yeomen.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Ecuador-Populist Adv06   05-02 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador-Populist, Adv 06,0890</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, May 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fiery Populist Given Chance to Win Ecuador's Presidency</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Sunday in 2nd graf is May 8</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUAYAQUIL, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abdala Bucaram, a fiery populist
leader from this rough-and-tumble port, is given a chance of
winning Ecuador's presidency even though the Roman Catholic Church,
newspapers and others object to his raucous style and language.
   The prospect that Bucaram, leader of the populist Roldosista
Party, could win the presidential runoff election Sunday has
stirred rumors of a military coup and sent tremors through
Ecuador's financial circles.
   The military sent him fleeing into exile once before.
   His foes accuse him of appealing to class hatred in his
speeches. But Bucaram's response is that he is a champion of the
poor.
   Campaigning recently in Guayaquil's steamy heat with his shirt
tail hanging out, he called himself a ``good-hearted slob'' and
admits he may be a bit ``crazy.''
   But his opponent in the election, Rodrigo Borja, is taking
Bucaram's challenge seriously.
   Political analysts say Bucaram has a good chance of defeating
Borja, a Social Democrat and leader of the Democratic Left party,
in the runoff.
   In the first round Jan. 31, the 36-year-old Bucaram won second
place in a field of 10 candidates with 15.3 percent of the vote to
20.3 percent for the 52-year-old Borja, 52.
   The winner Sunday will replace Leon Febres Cordero, a staunchly
conservative, pro-U.S. political leader whose four-year term ends
in August.
   This nation of 10 million people, wedged between Colombia and
Peru, has suffered in recent years from severe economic problems
and political instability sparked in great part by bitter disputes
between Febres Cordero and left-leaning parties that control
Congress.
   Borja, who narrowly lost to Febres Cordero in a runoff in 1984,
has pledged to reverse the current government's free-market
economic policies and seek close ties with the Non-Aligned
Movement, also known as the Third World.
   Borja's party is Ecuador's largest, but his chances are
weakened, many analysts say, because he is viewed as a lackluster
speaker without strong leadership ability.
   Bucaram, who wears a Hitler-style mustache and says he is an
admirer of the Nazi leader's ``organizational genius,'' charged at
one point in the campaign that ``an international Jewish
conspiracy'' was against him.
   Catholic Church leaders and newspapers have assailed Bucaram for
his use of gutter-language in attacks on Borja. Bucaram has called
Borja a drunkard and drug addict in television interviews. He also
has used unprintable street language to question his foe's virility.
   ``Borja lacks strength, spirit,'' Bucaram said. ``He's a
lukewarm man. Abdala is different,'' he said of himself. ``He
awakens passions. There is no middle ground with him.''
   The attacks have prompted Borja, a calm, urbane lawyer, to
respond in kind, calling Bucaram an ``irresponsible clown'' and a
``fascist ignoramus.''
   ``I have been accused of everything in my political career from
narcotics trafficker to thief,'' Bucaram said in a midnight
interview outside his small third-floor walkup apartment on a
garbage-littered downtown street.
   Bucaram has pledged to ``punish the oligarchy'' and crack down
on wealthy tax evaders who, he charges, cheat the government of up
to $500 million a year.
   ``A vote for me is the same as scratching a Mercedes Benz with a
bottle cap,'' he told a cheering slum crowd, alluding to such an
act as defiance of the rich.
   He has promised a ``shoe bank'' to provide free shoes for all
poor children and has pledged to nearly double the monthly minimum
wage to $60.
   His foes call him a demagogue for making such promises but
acknowledge privately that Bucaram is following in Ecuador's
tradition of populist leaders.
   The late Jose Maria Velasco Ibarra won the presidency five
times, in good measure because of his inflammatory populist
rhetoric. He also was ousted four times in military coups.
   Bucaram was mayor of this city of 1.5 million people when he
fled into exile in late 1985 to escape prison on a charge of
slandering the armed forces, a criminal offense in Ecuador. He had
said all the military was good for was wasting money on parades.
   In Panama he was arrested on a charge of possessing five pounds
of cocaine. He claimed it was a frame-up arranged by Febres
Cordero, a political enemy.
   Ecuador's Congress granted him amnesty on the military offense
and pressured Panama into dropping the cocaine charge.
   He returned in August 1987 to a hero's welcome from his
followers in Guayaquil's shantytowns.
   Bucaram is heir to a political dynasty of Lebanese immigrants
who settled in Guayaquil, Ecuador's biggest city and its commercial
hub. His sister, Elsa, was elected mayor of Guayaquil in the
general elections this past January.
   Even political foes say Bucaram was successful in administering
Guayaquil, a tough port city that has proved unmanageable for many
mayors.
   He won over hundreds of thousands of slum dwellers by paving
streets, piping in drinking water and providing other essential
services.
   He cracked down on street crime and kept the city clean by
jailing anyone who let garbage pile up in front of his property.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday AMs, May 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-China-Pollution Adv09   05-02 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Pollution, Adv 09,0771</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday AMs, May 9, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>China's Industrial Boom Threatens Rural Environment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Along with a new prosperity, China's industrial
boom of the past decade has filled rural skies with smog, poisoned
wells and blackened streams.
   The mushroom-like growth of small rural factories that burn coal
and lack money or know-how to clean up their wastes has made
environmental pollution a nationwide problem.
   The Communist Party leadership, which long claimed that only
profit-driven capitalist industries polluted the environment, has
begun to construct an environmental protection system. The first
environmental protection law was passed in 1979. Several others
setting standards for air and water purity have been approved since
then.
   A National Environmental Protection Agency was created in 1984,
replacing a lower-level committee on the environment.
   But the chemists, technicians and enforcers in the new system
are stretched thinly across the vast rural interior.
   The estimated 20,000 workers, most without college degrees and
with a minimum of special training, have the power, on paper at
least, to shut down factories, impose heavy fines, move industries
from harmful locations and deny permission for construction of new
ones.
   In reality, however, they often must compromise when strict
enforcement of standards could mean shutting down a town's main
taxpayer, or when the money to build treatment facilities is
lacking.
   The National Environmental Protection Agency in Beijing, with
100 staffers, mainly analyzes pollution data, leaving local
agencies to do the enforcing.
   ``We want to maintain the beauty of mountains and rivers,'' said
Tang Shidi, head of the environmental office in Panzhihua, a small
steel town surrounded by thickly forested mountains in central
China's Sichuan province.
   ``But on the other hand we have to support economic
development.'' He told a visitor to his office that he makes
recommendations to local authorities when a new factory or office
is built, but acknowledged they were not always followed.
   ``We have a principle to give active support (to development) .
.. and distribute industry rationally,'' said Liu Yuncheng, a
deputy department chief at the National Environmental Protection
Agency.
   But he acknowledged, ``Factories that provide most of the
finances for localities and cause serious pollution problems are
difficult to deal with.''
   Encouraging rural industry has been a key element of the
government's post-1978 development drive. Small local factories,
now numbering 15 million, have raised rural incomes and absorbed
the surplus rural labor force.
   These factories now account for more than a quarter of China's
industrial output, which has more than tripled in the past decade
to $372 billion.
   Liu said 40 percent of rural factories have pollution problems,
including 10 percent with ``serious'' problems. Most could be
resolved fairly easily if funds were available, he said.
   Government funds, however, fall far short of the need and are
unlikely to increase at a time when farmers, teachers and the army
all are clamoring for more money from a Treasury already in the red.
   According to the national agency, the state and industry spent
$1.35 billion last year to fight pollution. Officials estimated it
would take three times that just to clean up Shanghai, a major city.
   Most of the money was spent in cities, which are among the most
smog-ridden in the world.
   The official statistics on pollutants are daunting. Only one
fourth of the 36 billion tons of waste water discharged from
factories each year is treated. Few factory smokestacks have
scrubbers to keep pollutants from rising into the air.
   Tang said that until a few years ago the Golden Sands River that
supplies Panzhihua's drinking water ran black because a coking
plant dumped water laden with coal dust into the river. Now, he
said, the waste water is filtered, but the river still is
threatened by discharges from a paper mill.
   The official media have reported other examples.
   In April, two villagers in rural Shaanxi province in north China
drowned in industrial waste when the dam burst in a reservoir
holding toxic chemicals from a mineral processing facility. Wells
in the arid region were poisoned, destroying the local residents'
water supply for perhaps years to come.
   Ninety percent of a 14,825-acre pine forest in Sichuan was
destroyed by acid rain from nearby sulfur processing plants.
   Rural pollution also spills over from cities. The Environmental
Protection Agency said more than 200,000 acres of farmland are
buried under 7.5 billion tons of industrial waste from city plants.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, May 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1404EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--BuyingbyMail Adv15-3Takes   05-02 1100</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Buying by Mail, Adv 15-3 Takes,1121</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos, 1 cartoon. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Take a phone book, some census data, ZIP codes
and auto registration lists. Add a computer, credit cards and
800-prefix phone numbers and you have the main ingredients for an
enterprise that's one of the wonders of the Western world _
direct-mail marketing as refined, with amazing ingenuity, in the
United States. Here's an intriguing report on how the numbers
magicians do it.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SID MOODY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In the late 1940s, construction of an underpass in Washington,
D.C. effectively sealed off Spencer Howell's novelty shop from the
outside _ and buying _ world.
   To keep on eating, he broke the blockade by placing an ad in
House & Garden offering tubes of whiskey-flavored toothpaste. He
sold 100,000 before the year was out. A bottle opener in the shape
of dentures sold even better.
   Spencer Howell had rediscovered a sales tool as ancient as the
Babylonians: direct mail. Instead of waiting for the customers to
come to you, go to them.
   Some 6,000 to 10,000 catalog retailers _ the figure varies _ do
just that, 11.8 billion catalogs a year, according to trade groups.
They range from titans such as L.L. Bean in Maine to Lands' End in
Wisconsin to Sears, Roebuck and Co. anywhere to Larry Selman in
Santa Cruz, Calif. who sells glass paperweights from a $15 catalog
including a toadstool-shaped antique you can have for $27,000.
   The average American home gets 50 catalogs a year. A burdened
letter carrier delivered 324 catalogs to this writer between last
Labor Day and Thanksgiving.
   Last year 88 million Americans _ 51.2 percent of the adult
population _ bought something by phone or mail. Direct mail has had
a 15 percent annual growth (30 percent for upscale catalogs) since
1970, compared to 5-10 percent for store sales. This is 8.3 percent
of the nation's general merchandise sales. Direct mail is a
high-tech, almost scientific, business which undoubtedly has the
brains to overcome April's 30 percent third class postal hike by
becoming even more so.
   Little of this would have been possible without the computer,
the credit card and the 800-prefix telephone number. And above all,
the mailing list. The mailing list stems from four of the more
mundane items on this part of the planet: the phone book, census
reports, ZIP codes and your car registration.
   Mailing list compilers can get more info from these bare numbers
and names than a Biblical exegete could from the Dead Sea Scrolls.
Donnelley Marketing, one of the big compilers, says it has more
doctors of philosophy interpreting the data than the neighboring
Stamford, Conn. hospital has doctors of medicine.
   Babylonian catalogs came on cuneiformed clay tablets. After
Gutenberg invented movable type, Aldus Manutius of Venice had a
catalog of books he published of Greek and Latin authors. Ben
Franklin _ who else? _ put out a catalog of 600 books in 1744.
American colonials bought everything from lace cuffs to musket
balls by mail from the Mother Country.
   But Montgomery Ward is the direct father of today's direct mail.
His 1872 catalog promised farmers savings of up to 40 percent by
eliminating the middleman for items ranging from harnesses to
parasols. The first compiler was not far behind.
   He probably was Lester Martin, clerk of Story County, Iowa, who
discerned that the registrees of Henry Ford's new tin lizzies were
not only farmers but the wealthier of the breed. Such names might
mean money. Martin got rights to the names and opened the M and F
Mailing Co. with his brother-in-law. Reuben H. Donnelley, another
visionary, bought them out in 1917.
   This vision comes true daily at Donnelley's computer operation
in Lincoln, Neb. There the names and addresses from the nation's
2,700 telephone books are ``laboriously converted to computer
language,'' says Dick Vincent, Donnelley's director of marketing
services. An average directory takes six weeks to computerize.
   But what's in a name?
   Not a whole lot until those computers start comparing notes with
other computers. Census data, for instance, tell how many people
live at a phone address. It gives particulars on value of home,
income.
   The name begins to take on some flesh.
   Compare those results with motor vehicle registrations, compiled
by the R.L. Polk Co. of Taylor, Mich. Two cars at the same address?
Maybe mom works. An RV? Somebody goes camping. Station wagon? Kids.
Sports car? A carefree young in heart if not in fact, a spender.
   Add some input from ZIP. Admittedly these can be misleading,
says Larry Heely, a mailing list executive at Direct Media in Port
Chester, N.Y. The same ZIP code in Chicago contains the wealthy
living in high-rises along the lakefront and the decidedly
unwealthy only a few blocks inland.
   ``ZIPs are not homogeneous,'' says Bill Weisshahar at
Donnelley's computer facility in Nevada, Iowa. So some firms like
Claritas in Chicago dissect who lives where within a ZIP and
divides the United States into 250,000 neighborhoods.
   ``When I got out of college, I moved into an apartment with
orange-crate furniture and tacked posters on the wall for decor,''
says Dave Chambers of Claritas. ``I've moved up and away, but the
new tenant probably still has orange crates and tacked posters.
Birds of a feather flock together.'' All the easier, then, to
identify the flock.
   This computerized database from national sources _ about half
the states will sell vehicle registration lists _ is then
inspected, rejected and detected as closely as a 280-pound woman
discus thrower from behind the Iron Curtain.
   Almost everybody buys mailing lists from everybody else to try
to find out who John and Jane Doe are behind the door at 000 Main
Street, Centerville and just what it is they want to buy. Do they
subscribe to The New Yorker? Upscale. Money magazine? Strong
evidence of loose change. National Geographic? Travelers, armchair
or actual. Field & Stream? And live in rural Colorado? And own a
camper? John and Jane are going to hear from Eddie Bauer and Orvis.
If they buy a sleeping bag and a fly rod, L.L. Bean and Norm
Thompson won't be far behind.
   Word in direct mail, through list renting, moves fast.
   ``It's mind-boggling how many sources of data there are,''
Chambers says. Credit card applications. Mortgage loans. Alumni
directories. Charitable donations. Building permits. Voting lists.
Computers cross-reference all this to draw a profile.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1405EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--BuyingbyMail Adv15-1stAdd   05-02 1115</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Buying by Mail, Adv 15-1st Add,1132</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: a profile.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Many hospitals sell lists of new mothers. That's grist for the
baby catalogs. And, in time, grist for kitchen appliances, toys,
back-to-school wear, home computers, brides and eventually _
particularly if the addressee has had the same phone for 30 years _
empty nest catalogs.
   To keep all this straight, lists are continually subjected to
merge-purge, eliminating duplications, merging the newly born and
purging the newly departed, since even direct mail cannot reach
beyond the grave.
   Omaha Steaks International, say, will take a hint from this
list, one from another and make a very educated guess as to who's
entertaining a lot, having first, of course, cross-checked with the
vegetarian list. Maybe it will be a Jaguar owner in an upscale ZIP
code with a bouncing new mortgage on a showplace address who
subscribes to Gourmet and Gentleman's Quarterly and recently bought
a crystal table set from Bloomingdale's by mail.
   ``When a customer makes his first purchase, we generally don't
make money,'' says Omaha president Fred Simon. ``But if we give him
good service and a good product, he becomes a member of our family.
It's a process of time.''
   ``You test, test, test,'' says Dick Vincent. ``If you use a tool
list for golfers, you'll lose your shirt. You use a lot of little
sample mailings. You don't go for broke on one mailing or you will.
   ``The thing about direct mail is that it is measurable. You
spend X dollars for a mailing, and you get Y back. In face-to-face
retailing you can make a lot of mistakes before they catch up to
you.''
   To help avoid database generalities, Donnelley periodically
sends out questionnaires to the public with free coupons to entice
a return. More food for the computer.
   Success in direct mail is not assured. Reasons for failure are
emphatic. ``If you rent 20 lists and 19 bomb, you know you sent
your catalog at the wrong time, or it was lousy,'' Heely says. It
won't be because you rented duds. For reasons related to the Golden
Rule, list renters don't trade off lemons. A list of heavy buyers
means higher fees to the renters.
   The more people buy, the more their habits, desires and depth of
pocket becomes known and targeted by more catalogs. To the
ever-growing number of two-earner families, this means broader
chances for convenience shopping. No traffic jams on the way to the
mall or parking hassles once there. No tugs-of-war at bargain
counters. No sassy or dumb clerks.
   Instead, the catalog house has a friendly, knowledgeable voice
at the end of an 800 number to answer any problem and assure the
customer he or she isn't buying a blind pig in a blind poke. ``It's
a lot less expensive to keep the customer happy than to try to find
a new one,'' says Lisa Caugherty of the Direct Marketing
Association in New York, a trade group.
   This is no more than Ben Franklin guaranteed when he assured his
customers, ``who live remote, by sending their orders and money to
the said B. Franklin, may depend on the same justice as if
present.''
   A catalog buy is an act of faith based on a picture of something
seen but never touched. Buyer satisfaction is deferred. ``If you
don't receive the goods promptly, the perceived need for it goes
away, and the emotional reward goes away, too,'' says Jo-Von
Tucker, a New York catalog consultant. So one of the first
commandments of direct mail is thou shalt fill orders promptly if
not sooner.
   Years ago, entry into direct mail was almost as easy as licking
a stamp. Lillian Vernon Katz, a 24-year-old housewife, scraped up
$2,000 in the early 1920s, placed $495 worth of ads for matching
purses and belts and offered to monogram them free. Lillian Vernon
did $115 million in sales last year.
   Richard Thalheimer started up his Sharper Image catalog by
writing clever copy and offering oddball items such as a suit of
15th century armor for $2,450. Gary Comer, a former ad copywriter,
started Lands' End as a yacht supplier, then tacked downwind to
become one of the biggest clothing mailers.
   Omaha Steaks was a local food supplier until 1952 when Fred
Simon's father heeded friends' requests to mail meats to their
friends. The stampede was on.
   Mom and Pop still might, just conceivably, start a catalog today
over the kitchen table. ``But they better have $500,000 up front
and be able to sweat it out for two years,'' says Larry Heely.
   ``It's a very crowded mail box,'' says Jo-Von Tucker. She helped
J.R. Carroll, an Irish tobacco company, spend over $5 million with
the help of marketing psychologists and all the sci-fi of Madison
Avenue to prepare their recent debut into direct mail with an
up-up-scale catalog full of enticing photos of wares to equip your
own Buckingham Palace by.
   ``The day of the dinosaur catalogs like Montgomery Ward's
(recently abandoned) are over,'' she says. ``Catalogs today are
aimed at lifestyles.''
   ``Mass marketing is dead,'' pronounced Vincent. ``Now it's
databased. Magazines have a lot of wasted circulation. TV is too
broad.''
   This is both an opportunity and a challenge for the mailing
list. Fred Simon of Omaha Steaks aims at a broad market of buyers
of high quality (average catalog purchases are somewhere between
$35 and $50). A paperweight catalog has a far narrower focus.
   Claritas helps by breaking down ZIP codes into categories. It
tells you where to find such socio-economic groupies they identify
as: Money and Brains, Furs and Station Wagons, Pools and Patios,
Young Influentials, Towns and Gowns (academics in non-metropolitan
areas), God's Country (well-educated frontier types), Coalburg and
Corntown (``Terre Haute and Lima, Ohio surrounded by rich farmland
and peopled by solid, blue-collar citizens raising sturdy Tom
Sawyerish children in decent front porch houses''). They'll also
tell you, for a price, where to find Shotguns and Pickups, Norma
Rae-villes and Tobacco Roads.
   At the brush of a computer button Heely brings up data on
Woodworkers Supply of New Mexico: 62,833 catalog purchases in the
last six months, 173,930 for 1987. An average list, rented for one
time use with the owner's veto over content, goes for around $80
per thousand names. Throw in another $10 if you want a breakdown as
to gender a ``recency'' of purchase. Of that the broker, who
mediates between landlord and rentee, gets about 20 percent, the
manager who has been handling the list, gets 10, the renter pays
maybe $3.50 to run off his list. The rest is gravy in his pocket.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--BuyingbyMail Adv15-2ndAdd   05-02 1036</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Buying by Mail, Adv 15-2nd Add,1049</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: his pocket.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Lists and listers pinpoint like a B-1 bombsight. They can tell
you that there is a correlation between someone with a propensity
for elective surgery and the amount of cash and spare time the
cutee has. Computer modeling, applying a myriad of demographic and
lifestyle overlays on the primary database, are producing what Ms.
Tucker calls ``a young science.''
   It has to be to marry the tastes of an endlessly varied buyer
and an endlessly fanciful seller. Where but in America could
American Express otherwise sell 6,000 busts of King Tut? How else
could you find buyers mailing and phoning for every kind of fitness
machine, stereo woofer, subliminal Weight Control tapes, two-ounce
bottles of quail scent to train Bowser to the hunt, a 24-room
purple martin house with guard rails for baby birds ($289),
videotaped tours of Highland games in Scotland or Civil War
battlefields, $29.95 music box dolls that play ``Thank Heaven for
Little Girls,'' a real steam launch for $61,500, 42-inch-high
stuffed leather rhinosceri ($495 plus $12.95 shipping), fur coats,
mutual funds?
   Who are these customers who hold 600 million credit cards and
once flooded L.L. Bean with 100,000 phone calls in a day? And what
are the catalogs that impel them to lick stamps and dial phones?
   ``It is the merchandiser's dream to identify the core group of
20 percent who buy 60 percent of the nation's goods,'' says
Vincent. The 20 percent is not always whom you might expect.
Catalog buyers are not sit-by-the-fire-thumbing-a-catalog couch
potatoes. More likely they are working couples with limited time to
shop. They are yuppies, but also over-50s, who have some
discretionary income now the kids have gone. The upscale could well
be semi-rurals who are 1,500 miles from Nieman Marcus. L.L. Bean's
primary constituency is suburban. Rural folk can buy lumber jackets
and gas lanterns down at the general store. The market is,
potentially, anyone who can dial a phone.
   In 1967, 653 businesses had 800 numbers and handled 7 million
phone calls. Today there are 535,000 toll-free numbers, 6.3 billion
calls to them and even an 800 number for information on 800 numbers.
   Today's catalog is only a distant relative to yesteryear's Sears
version that was a backhouse fixture. Banana Republic's is a safari
through suburban bush clothing together with a written one from
some exotic trek. Patagonia has rock climbers and sky divers
scrambling over the pages of its sportswear, implying that here is
the garb of real he-persons. Garrett Wade's handsome tool catalog
elevates photos of hammers, saws and wooden planes almost to fine
art.
   ``Catalogs are first and foremost a photographer's medium,''
says Jo-Von Tucker. ``But it has to be more than a pretty picture.
It has to have a tone and personality, not just ticky-tacky boxes.''
   ``The creative part gets more attention, but it's only 20
percent of success,'' says Chambers. ``The rule of thumb is that 40
percent is the right product and 40 percent is the targeting.''
   Bean's no-nonsense pictures, town-meeting typeface and laconic
cracker-barrel prose combine to say ``granite solid value.'' Some
tool wholesalers, on the other hand, intentionally print on poor
paper with indifferent illustrations so the home hobbyist thinks he
is getting bargains straight from the close-out sale.
   The fact that there are 51 million videocassette recorders in
the U.S. is not lost on the catalog industry. Country Curtains will
provide a cassette so you can see right on your own TV set what
their products will do for your windows. Selling by VCR is an idea
whose time has only just begun.
   Computerized shopping by TV has long been said to be right
around a corner that never seems to arrive. J.C. Penney, however,
has just launched an electronic catalog in the Chicago suburbs
which enables the viewer to scan, linger over and buy illustrated
items from some 50 suppliers, including a supermarket. All you have
to do is turn on the cable catalog channel and manipulate it with a
Touch Tone phone. The system will even play selections from records
you might want to buy.
   For the retailer who wants to know what is selling, which is the
name of the game in the game of names, Penney's system, called
Telaction, ``can tell if people looked at the blue shoes as well as
the black they bought or how long someone looked at a dress even if
she didn't buy it,'' says Mary Dale Walters of Telaction.
   The cost of finding a customer via catalog is rising with the
cost of technology, the cost of paper, the cost of mailing.
   DMA, whose more than 2,000 members have just been hit with the
postal hike, is looking into alternative delivery systems. The
industry is not happy with a joint survey by DMA and Doubleday, the
publisher, that the U.S. Postal Service failed to deliver four to
14.1 per cent of third class mail in 1983 and did no better when
resurveyed last year. The Post Office says it will tighten up
procedures. One man's junk mail is another's expensive mailing list.
   Another problem for direct mail is the matter of privacy. The
industry takes considerable pains to stay on the right side of a
sometimes fine line. If you don't want any catalogs, you can ask
DMA to get you off the lists. More people, however, tell DMA they
would like to get more catalogs than want none. A Consumer Reports
survey found almost nine people in 10 were ``mostly or completely''
satisfied with their shopping by mail or phone.
   And Spencer Howell? After 45 million catalogs offering
everything from ``Go Away'' doormats to records of three minutes of
silence, he has retired to the golf course where he may reminisce
about the year his Game Room offered a Christmas card bearing
greetings from The First Family. Inside were a fig-leafed Adam and
Eve posed in their Garden.
   ``It seemed a cute idea,'' he says, as have catalogers since the
days of the Babylonians. ``But it didn't sell worth a damn,'' which
undoubtedly some Babylonian also said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
