<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Southern Europe, Adv 15-1st Add,0986</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>ROME: both countries.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``We lost the industrial revolution, but we're going to win the
post-industrial revolution,'' says Spanish banker Jane Sola.
   What triggered Spain's development was the smooth transition
from General Francisco Franco's 40-year dictatorship to the
pro-business socialist government of Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez.
   In neighboring Portugal, the European Community's poorest
member, another political switch has spurred economic growth. Prime
Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva has brought stability in the wake of
16 years of revolving-door governments.
   Many wealthy Portuguese, who left the country after a 1974
leftist revolution that toppled a 42-year dictatorship, have
returned to dance in fashionable Lisbon nightspots and to present
their daughters at lavish debutante balls.
   Cavaco Silva, a 48-year-old former economics professor, is
pushing ahead with privatization of dozens of large state-owned
companies, including tobacco, banking, media and insurance
interests.
   ``The degree of confidence in Portugal is very, very high,'' the
premier says.
   The first state-controlled company to be put on the block as
part of Cavaco Silva's privatization program is EPSI, Portugal's
largest producer of polyethylene and polypropylene. The Italian
Enichem company is at the top of the list of prospective buyers.
   Cheap labor, which compares favorably with costs in Asia, has
attracted foreign manufacturers and brought unemployment down to
6.6 percent, the lowest in the EEC after Luxembourg.
   A $2-an-hour minimum wage brings in high-tech industries like
Texas Instruments, which recently launched a $43 million expansion
of an electronics plant at Oporto that employs 1,000 people.
   Tourism is also booming, with around 10 million foreigners
vacationing in Portugal every year to make the industry a
$1-billion-a-year business.
   At the other end of the Mediterranean, tourism is still Greece's
biggest foreign exchange earner. A record 8 million tourists spent
$3.2 billion last year.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou's Socialist government, in a reversal
of former policy, now wants to broaden the country's economic base
and attract foreign capital into Greek firms through freer
financial markets.
   Reforms of the banking system are laying the groundwork for a
money market that will allow American brokerage houses to buy seats
on the booming Athens stock market.
   Western European investors, taking advantage of new measures
permitting their profits to be repatriated, last year poured more
than $52 million into the Athens exchange last year.
   ``Greece is changing at last,'' says John Costopoulos, president
of Creditbank, Greece's biggest private bank.
   Greeks can now apply for home mortgages and bank interest rates
are high enough to attract private depositors.
   ``Overall modernization of the economy is the basic condition
for our survival and growth,'' says National Economy Minister
Panayotis Roumeliotis, who coordinates economic policy.
   Papandreou and Turkish Premier Turgut Ozal have reached a
``no-war'' agreement and set up a hot line telephone between their
capitals to defuse tensions between the two NATO members.
   Bankers and businessmen are firmly behind the current
Greek-Turkish rapprochement.
   Turkey, which in the 17th century camped 300,000 men before the
gates of Vienna, firing cannons into the city in order to enter
Europe, applied to join the Common Market in April 1987. Greece
says it won't automatically block the application.
   Turkey, the only Islamic nation among the five southern European
countries, is making a bid to replace war-torn Lebanon as a banking
center for the Middle East.
   At the same time, its new seaside resorts are luring Western
tourists for bargain vacations. More than 3 million foreigners
spent $2 billion in Turkey last year, a 60 percent earnings
increase over 1986.
   Ozal, a former World Bank official, says that his export drive
and free-market policies _ including the privatization of state
monopolies _ brought growth of 7 percent last year that will enable
Turkey's economy ``to skip a century.''
   Luxuries like whiskey, instant coffee and French champagne are
now snapped up in Turkey, where the per capita income is half that
of Portugal.
   Massive investment in energy, transport and communications have
transformed many towns into huge construction sites. Turkey is now
planning a third bridge over the Bosporus waterway, reflecting the
country's determination to link itself with Western Europe.
   The EEC absorbs more than 40 percent of all Turkish exports, and
West Germany is home to 1.4 million Turkish workers and their
families.
   But with a 67 percent inflation rate, a currency crunch and a
huge foreign debt, Turkey still has a long way to go to reach the
prosperity of the EEC countries.
   For the other southern European countries, the worldwide October
stock market crash also highlighted persistent problems.
   _Italy is facing wildcat strikes in transport and industry, a 12
percent unemployment rate and a runaway national debt. And the
south of the country, still plagued by crime syndicates like the
Mafia, lags economically far behind the north.
   _In Greece, stagnant exports, Europe's lowest productivity and a
huge public sector deficit keep growth rates low.
   _In Spain, the Socialists are troubled by Europe's highest
unemployment _ 21 percent in 1987 _ and union protesters filled the
streets of Madrid when the government suggested that state and
private employers not grant wage hikes of more than 5 percent.
   _In Portugal, the per capita income of $2,500 is only half that
of Spain and Premier Cavaco Silva concedes that people still go
hungry.
   And if the pace of development can't be speeded up in southern
Europe, the economic spurt that is ending Mediterranean poverty may
run out of steam in the competitive post-1992 market.
   ``Unless there's cohesion among the 12 EEC nations, development
in the southern regions will be like quicksand,'' says La Pergola,
the Italian minister. ``Cohesion must start at the bottom, the
south, through new forms of financial engineering.''
</TEXT>
