<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Southern Europe-Leaders, Adv 15,0618</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Southern Europe</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ROME (AP) _ Here are brief biographies of the leaders of five
key nations in southern Europe.
   
   ITALY _ Christian Democratic Premier Giovanni Goria, 44, who
resigned March 11, has been asked by President Francesco Cossiga to
remain as caretaker premier until a new leader is chosen.
   Party leader Ciriaco De Mita is currently trying to put together
another five-party coalition.
   Goria, a former accountant from the northern city of Asti, was a
surprise choice for premier when he took office on Aug. 1, 1987 at
the head of the shaky coaltaly's 47th postwar
government. Goria was Italy's youngest premier ever.
   Goria previously served as treasury minister and was credited in
that post with loosening the country's restrictive foreign exchition that
was Iange
controls and with helping to bring double-digit inflation to its
present level of about 5 percent.
   He is married and has two children.
   
   SPAIN _ Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez, a 46-year-old Seville
labor lawyer, took office in December 1982 following a landslide
victory of his Socialist Party. He had no previous government
experience but was head of the parliamentary opposition after Spain
returned to democracy in 1977.
   Gonzalez is married to sch
   
   ROME (AP) _ World War II left the nations of southern Europe
bombed-out and poor, devastated by six years of combat while a few
neutral countries led by dictators watched from the sidelines.
   Italy was brought to its knees by the Nazi occupation and the
Allied invasion, while right-wing dictators kept a tight grip on
Spain and Portugal. Greece was plunged into civil war between
Communists and nationalists. Moslem Turkey was reeling from abrupt
change wrought by wartime contact with the West.
   Italy struggled back on track after 21 years of rule by Fascist
dictator Benito Mussolini with elections in 1946. Funds from the
U.S. Marshall Plan laid the groundwork for industrialization.
   The Christian Democrats, in power through much of the postwar
period, presided over dramatic economic expansion by the 1960s that
was termed an ``economic miracle.'' But in the 1970s, political
instability and worker unrest brought economic crisis and fueled
terrorism led by the leftist Red Brigades.
   In Spain, the pro-German fascist regime of General Francisco
Franco won the bitter civil war of 1936-1939, but watched World War
II from neutral sidelines. In the '60s and '70s, Franco backed the
Roman Catholic Church, traditional landowners and industrialists
but suppressed free-market business initiatives.
   After Franco's death in 1975, the country quickly blossomed into
an ebullient democracy under a constitutional monarch, King Juan
Carlos.
   Portugal also watched from the sidelines under the dictatorship
of Antonio de Oliveira Salazar which lasted 42 years until 1974.
The country veered left after a 1974 revolution, but stabilized in
the 1980s under business-minded, centrist governments.
   Greece recovered economically from the devastating 1946-49 civil
war thanks to Marshall Plan funds. Political instability in the
1960s after years of right-wing government triggered the 1967
colonels' dictatorship, which collapsed after the 1974 invasion of
Cyprus. A referendum that year abolished the monarchy and made
Greece a presidential republic. The socialist government of the
1980s has moved gradually toward centrist, pro-business policies.
   Turkey remained a neutral dictatorship for much of World War II,
then declared war on Germany and Japan in 1945. The economically
backward country became a firm ally of the United States as
American aid helped cut down state capitalism in favor of free
enterprise and Westernization in the 1950s.
   A short-lived military takeover in 1960 ushered in a period of
political and economic problems that led to street violence in the
1970s by Marxist revolutionaries, right-wing ``Gray Wolves'' and
separatist Kurds. The military took over again in 1980, but a
pro-Western democracy was restored in parliamentary elections held
in 1983.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
