<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--GrandPiano Adv15-2Takes   05-02 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Grand Piano, Adv 15-2 Takes,0722</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 2 35mm slides.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ In June, the 500,000th Steinway piano, designed
by artist Wendell Castle, will be unveiled at a Carnegie Hall
concert. Yamaha, Steinway's main competitor, reaches the 500,000
mark every 2{ years on its assembly line in Japan. But at
Steinway's plant in New York, most things are still done the
old-fashioned way. That's what makes a Steinway a Steinway.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a box-shaped, soundproof room, Raymond Parada
stands before a piano keyboard pulled from its shining 9-foot body.
Parada plinks at the keys, listening carefully, making adjustments
instinctively.
   No music pours from the instrument. Parada is not a pianist.
Instead, he ``turns music boxes into Steinways,'' spending 24 hours
with the inner workings of each piano, creating concert grands for
artists from Vladimir Horowitz to Billy Taylor.
   ``The piano must allow an artist to develop his talents. It is
not like an automobile, where it works the same for everybody _ you
turn the wheel right, the automobile goes right,'' explains Parada,
who does things the old-fashioned way at Steinway & Sons.
   In fact, everything's done much the same way it's been done
since John Engelhard Steinway arrived from Germany in 1853 and
switched from cabinetmaking to keyboards. The Steinway piano is
still hand-strung, fussed and fawned over, individually numbered,
tuned and retuned by highly skilled specialists like Parada.
   It still takes one full year to create the Steinway concert
grand, ``the piano by which all others are judged,'' the product of
more than 100 patented piano-making techniques.
   It remains the choice of the great pianists _ Claudio Arrau, Van
Cliburn, Vladimir Horowitz _ as it was the choice of Ignace
Paderewski and Franz Liszt a century ago.
   ``It's the only piano for me,'' says Peter Nero. ``I was 13 when
I started in competition at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, 14 when
I started at Juilliard, and it's been Steinway all the way.''
   In June, the 500,000th Steinway, designed by artist Wendell
Castle, will be unveiled at a Carnegie Hall concert. Yamaha, its
top competitor, reaches the 500,000 mark every 2{ years on its
assembly line in Japan.
   The Steinway doesn't come cheap either: The price list runs from
$7,500 to $40,000 for the 9-foot concert grand. Yamaha's least
expensive piano costs about $2,700, while its concert grand prices
are about the same as Steinway.
   How has Steinway survived 135 years, outlasting an assortment of
competitors while keeping its reputation for quality?
   ``A Steinway is a Steinway only because we don't cut any
corners,'' says John Steinway, 70, one of the last two family
members still in the piano-making business. ``We make quality,
nothing but the top quality we can make.
   ``My great-grandfather started that when he started the firm 135
years ago. I often say we're probably thickheaded and stubborn. We
stick to our principles. But it works.''
   ``The Steinway manufacturing process relies on tradition,''
offers William Garlick, an antique piano aficionado now employed as
Steinway's national field service manager. ``That tradition has
carried on, although we don't ignore technology.''
   Instead, an exacting process which combines the innovative and
the antiquated is used to create 3,400 Steinway pianos each year at
the company's 11-acre Queens factory.
   In one part of the plant, a worker hand-trims pieces of veneer
for the piano's outer surface with a 120-year-old machine. Later in
the process, a newly developed machine perfectly shapes its
soundboard to fit the piano body.
   ``Even that is not a production-line concept,'' says Bruce
Stevens, president of the firm since Steinway Musical Properties,
Inc., bought it three years ago. ``It's letting technology do
something even better than we could do it before. One man still
handles that job alone.''
   There are many answers as to what makes a Steinway a Steinway:
the input of the artists, the commitment to quality, the genius of
19th-century piano meister C.F. Theodore Steinway. But those
responses may miss the forest for the trees, which provide the
Steinway wood.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--GrandPiano Adv15-1stAdd   05-02 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Grand Piano, Adv 15-1st Add,0649</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: Steinway wood.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``One of the things done right here is we use only good wood,''
says Garlick. ``We have people constantly looking throughout the
world for good wood.''
   The wood _ imported mahogany, northeast rock maple, yellow
poplar _ is improved through aging. Air-dried outdoors for up to 18
months, the wood is then kiln-dried to remove the moisture and run
through the mill for shaving and rough shaping.
   Each piano's outer rim is bent in a process which appears more
likely to splinter wood than shape it. For the grand piano, it
involves seven men, 19 panels of wood 22 feet long, plenty of
pushing, and a winch. Amazingly, the wood doesn't break but bends
into the shape of a concert grand.
   The process is repeated 150 times a year on the machine
developed in 1880 by C.F. Theodore Steinway, the family's
acknowledged piano genius. The pieces of wood in the rim are
individually coated with old-fashioned animal glue.
   ``It sets up very fast, very strong, and it's acoustically
sound,'' Garlick explains.
   A soundboard is cut to the specifications of each rim. It's
slightly curved and ribs are attached by hand _ two more Steinway
innovations.
   But perhaps the most important function, a simple task which
determines each succeeding step, occurs in the Steinway foundry.
Metal plates shipped in from Springfield, Ohio, are punched with
two holes taken from the original drawings of Henry Engelhard
Steinway.
   Known as the reference holes, these quarter-inch puncture marks
serve no purpose other than to guide creation of the piano from
that point forward. The soundboard, the stringing, the placement of
the keyboard _ everything revolves around the two marks.
   ``It's been the same two holes since Day One,'' Garlick says.
   In the aptly named body-stretching stage, an employee climbs
inside the piano rim and pushes out with his hands and feet before
the plate and soundboard are fitted. The piano ``action'' _ its
hammers, felt and other interior parts _ are painstakingly pieced
together and subjected to repeated quality checks.
   By the time the piano is assembled, wired and shipped to Raymond
Parada's department, it has gone through 25 to 30 checkpoints. The
workers responsible for bigger jobs like soundboard placement,
piano stringing and tone adjustment often sign their work.
   ``It's an aspiration of everybody to be immortal, and so, like
an artist signs his painting, I sign the piano,'' explains Parada,
his voice growing soft. ``I put into the piano the best of myself.''
   His attitude is pervasive throughout the plant. Three
piano-stringers working side by side in the factory use three
different methods to perform their task, each convinced his way is
the right way.
   ``We don't mind that. We encourage the little rivalries between
them, because the product comes out good,'' says John Steinway, who
began his career running wood from the yard to the factory.
   The unique process at the plant means each piano will sound a
bit different. The company allows any perspective buyer, be it
Peter Nero or Peter Zero, to play several pianos and pick the one
which sounds best to them.
   The future of Steinway holds an immediate challenge: a frontal
assault by Yamaha on their once near-exclusive concert grand market.
   There are some defectors. Billy Joel played a Yamaha grand on
his recent album ``The Bridge'' and Bruce Hornsby, winner of the
1987 best new artist Grammy, doesn't use a Steinway.
   While Yamaha made its first concert grands in 1902, they only
recently began concentrating on the grand piano market.
   ``I think Yamaha's doing a very good job these days, but it's
still not a Steinway,'' says Nero, who owns four.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
