<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Tips for Buyers, Adv 15-2 Takes,0700</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Some people go through life with a sure touch
for the practicalities of everyday life. Others flounder. For them,
former TV reporter Betsy Ashton has written a guide designed to
keep them out of the many traps that open up in a consumer society.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KAY BARTLETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Who among us was raised with an innate knowledge
of which telephone company gives us the best deal? Who, in fact,
ever dreamed that picking a telephone company would be a way of
life in 1988?
   And if you ``wouldn't buy a used car from that man,'' whom would
you buy one from? And how do you negotiate with him when you're not
even really sure what rack and pinion means?
   What about the jungle of financial jargon that everyone else
seems to understand _ like CD's, IRA's, deferred annuity bonds,
Keoghs, municipals, etc.?
   It was simpler when people just went to the bank that gave the
best toaster. If you already had a toaster, the next toughest
choice was whether you wanted the Revere Ware pots or a non-brand
that had pretty yellow flowers on it.
   These are things that almost everyone, at some point in life _
just starting out, after a divorce, recently widowed _ must learn
to deal with without getting stung in the process.
   ``You aren't born with this knowledge. Kids of people who own
businessess or are in the financial world might know some of it,
but most of us don't,'' says Betsy Ashton, a former national
consumer affairs correspondent for television, and author of
``Betsy Ashton's Guide to Living on Your Own,'' due in bookstores
early this summer.
   ``This book is not for people who see an ad on television and
send $5 away and expect to get a diamond ring in return. They
deserve what they get. This book is for reasonably intelligent
people who must face these kinds of things for the first time and
aren't aware of the pitfalls.
   ``This book is not about the things your mother never told you,
it's about the things your father never told you,'' says Ms.
Ashton. Like taxes, audits, how much insurance you need, which
health club to join, how to pick a telephone company and how to
deal with the media if you've gotten yourself into a mess that
would incidentally make a good story.
   A lot of the advice comes from Ashton's nearly 17 years in radio
and television, first teaching art on cable TV, then covering the
courts in Washington, D.C., and later as the consumer affairs
expert there and ultimately for CBS.
   She often got tips from viewers who had been ripped off by one
scheme or another. As a local reporter, she named names and
products.
   ``That's the job of the local reporter, but I don't do that in
the book,'' she says. ``This is more of a household encyclopedia
that would be applicable anywhere.'' She explains, for instance,
some of the oldest tricks in the books, such as the bait and switch
ruse, and how not to go for the bait.
   It's a practical book. The section on health clubs, for
instance, warns against paying the annual membership fee to clubs
that haven't opened yet. Some have gone under before they got
going. Others, she warns, may be on shaky financial ground, so
check them out before handing over your check for a year's
membership.
   Also figure out what you really need. Are you paying for fancy
exercise machines that you're not likely to use. Or a swimming
pool, when what you really want is the racquet ball court? She
advises going to YMCA's or schools to see if you might get the
facilities you want much cheaper. Or, go to a club that has only
the facilities you actually intend using. It will probably be
cheaper.
</TEXT>
