<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Tips for Buyers, Adv 15-1st Add,0616</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: be cheaper.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   She confesses to being a victim herself, joining health clubs to
drop that extra 20 pounds that always crept back on. She finally
calculated that her demanding schedule, working long days, made it
impractical; her visits turned out to cost her $40 a session.
   Her book tells you what questions to ask up front and urges the
timid to push for answers to key questions, especially, ``What is
this going to cost me?''
   ``Healthy skepticism is important,'' she says. ``A financial
planner or an accountant should be able to explain things to you
without talking down to you and telling you to `just trust me.'
   ``Ask him or her about fees, about how much of his income is
derived from commissions, ask for references, look for possible
conflicts of interest.''
   She tells how to find out what the car dealer paid for the car
he is selling you, the toll-free 800 number to call to find out
whether the model of used car you're considering has ever been
recalled, how to spot cosmetic cover-ups on a used car.
   Ashton, 43, and recently remarried, says her book draws on files
she had kept as a television consumer expert.
   ``I spent a lot of time on the telephone updating things, and
re-interviewing people, but basically it was years and years of
reporting that went into the book,'' she says.
   If you're going to try the media, she tells you how. First, do
all the work yourself. The local reporter or columnist doesn't have
time to unearth every single aspect of your case. They get
hundreds, maybe thousands of letters from irate consumers seeking
to enlist the newspaper in their cases.
   You, the abused, must document your claim, agree to be
interviewed, and, if you live in a multimedia town, don't ship out
carbons to every reporter in town. Pick the one you like best,
offer an exclusive story, and hope for the best.
   It helps if the story is interesting and has broad appeal.
   Ashton had an unusual career trail.
   She was accepted by the Peace Corps, but fell in love and
married instead. A talented artist, whose apartment is decorated
with Ashton originals, she worked for an advertising agency, taught
art in high school, and decided that if Julia Child could teach
French cooking on television, she could teach art on there. So she
did.
   She did radio interviews around the feminist movement, covered
the courts for a Washington TV station, and worked as an artist at
the same time.
   ``You learn that lawyers are very repetitive,'' she says. ``The
first time they said something, I took notes, the second time I
started sketching the jurors and the third time I added the color.''
   She turned down the job as consumer affairs reporter the first
time it was offered.
   ``I thought it was going to be all fluff,'' she says. ``I
thought it was the equivalent of being the weather girl.
   ``The second time it was offered, it was explained that it would
be more of a Ralph Nader sort of thing. We were going after
companies and individuals that were ripping off the public. That I
liked.''
   Ashton grew up in the suburbs of Trenton, N.J. with pretty much
of a belief in the goodness of her fellow human beings.
   ``I really didn't know there were these kind of people, people
who simply preyed on others as a way of life,'' she says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
