<DOCNO> AP880502-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1509EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--LionelHampton Adv15-1stAdd   05-02 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Lionel Hampton, Adv 15-1st Add,0702</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: for me.'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I had been in the Chicago Defender Newsboys Band in Chicago.
They had a xylophone; it's got the same keyboard. I played drums in
the marching band and timpani and xylophone in the concert band. We
had a good bandmaster, Maj. Endicott Smith, who had graduated in
music from the University of Heidelberg. He taught me German
harmony. Anybody interested, he would teach them.''
   Hampton had studied Armstrong's records, so on that October day
in 1930 he romped through Armstrong's trumpet solo in ``Big Butter
and Egg Man'' on the vibraphone. ``It knocked Louis out,'' Hampton
says.
   They recorded eight songs that day. On the first one, Eubie
Blake's ``Memories of You,'' Hampton played vibes while Armstrong
sang and the drums while Armstrong played his trumpet.
   The Les Hite Band backed Armstrong for nine months at the Cotton
Club. Hampton became known.
   When the engagement ended, Hampton assembled his first band.
They traveled, in four cars and a trailer for his drums and vibes,
from San Diego to Vancouver, B.C.
   ``I always played good dance music and played jazz for a show. I
built up a following,'' Hampton says. ``I play a lot of dances now.
They always ask me to make return engagements. Young people dance,
too. I'm just back from a teen-age affair in Washington. There were
5,000 kids there. We were supposed to quit at 10:30. At 12:30 they
were yelling for more and stomping on the floor.''
   In the early 1930s, Hampton traded touring for a job in the
Paradise Nightclub across the street from the Los Angeles train
station. They'd leave the doors open, Hampton says, and sailors
arriving to paint the town would come in. Beer was 25 cents a
pitcher and there was sawdust on the floor.
   ``I had a good band there,'' Hampton says. ``Benny Goodman was
at the Palomar Ballroom. John Hammond was with him. Naturally John
would ask where he could hear some good jazz. He heard us and he
brought Benny down. Lo and behold, I'm on the bandstand playing and
I hear a guy playing clarinet beside me. I could tell it was
Benny's famous clarinet. It was Aug. 19, 1936. I'll never forget.
We played like that about two hours straight. People were calling
people and they were coming from all over town. That place was
packed and jammed. We was blowing.
   ``Benny asked me to come the next morning to a recording date. I
went and we did `Moonglow' and `Dinah.' Those records got so
popular, Benny kept calling me to come to New York. We thought he
was kidding.
   ``The Paradise took the sawdust off the floor and put
tablecloths on the tables. It was $1.25 to come in. After that jam
session, you couldn't get in, even with the price of admission. We
got super-famous overnight, because Benny had come and christened
us.''
   On Nov. 11, 1936, Hampton joined the Benny Goodman Quartet at
the Pennsylvania Hotel in New York City.
   ``Everything was segregated then, black and white,'' he says.
``That night the barrier broke. You've got to give Benny credit.''
   Hampton says that black pianist Teddy Wilson had played
intermission music for Goodman Band concerts and played with
Goodman and drummer Gene Krupa as the Benny Goodman Trio on
records, but never live until that Nov. 11 when the trio became a
quartet.
   ``I had four gorgeous years with Benny,'' Hampton says. ``Then
Benny had back trouble and his doctor told him to rest awhile. He
got me a contract at RCA and I started making all-star records.
They're re-issuing them.''
   In between gigs, Hampton supervises his philanthropies, the
Lionel Hampton Ear Research Foundation and the Lionel Hampton
Endowment Fund, which gives college scholarships. The Lionel
Hampton Community Development Corporation added money to government
money to build the low-income Gladys Hampton Houses, named for his
late wife, and Lionel Hampton Houses in Harlem and middle-income
Hampton Hills in Newark.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
