<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv15   05-02 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 15,0883</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On her 17th birthday last fall, Linzi Hateley
got a plum of a present, the title role in ``Carrie,'' the new
Broadway musical about a girl with telekinetic powers.
   At the time, Miss Hateley was a student at the Italia Conti
Academy, a drama school in London. Her acting credentials were
meager: a British touring company of ``Annie'' and a small part on
a television series.
   But the next day she was the Cinderella story in the London
tabloids. ``Unknown lands lead in major show co-produced by the
prestigious Royal Shakespeare Company.''
   ``It didn't sink in at all until I settled down and started
rehearsing,'' Miss Hateley says now. It has been a turbulent and
fast-paced few months.
   ``Carrie'' is based on the Stephen King novel that most people
remember as a movie with Sissy Spacek playing the troubled
teen-ager. In the film, Carrie is taunted and tormented by other
high school students and her mother before she gets revenge on prom
night.
   ``I was told right from the beginning not to try and base myself
on Sissy Spacek,'' Miss Hateley recalls. ``The musical tries to
follow the book rather than the film because the show really is
more of a tragedy than a horror story.''
   ``Carrie'' is a unique collaboration of American and British
theater people. With the blessing of actors' unions in both
countries, the show has a joint Anglo-American cast.
   The director is Terry Hands, artistic head of the Royal
Shakespeare Company. The music and lyrics were written by Michael
Gore and Dean Pitchford, the men who wrote ``Fame.'' Debbie Allen,
Broadway's recent ``Sweet Charity,'' did the choreography.
   The show was to co-star Barbara Cook as Carrie's bizarre and
vindictive mother, but Miss Cook, dissatisfied with her role, left
after the show's engagement in Stratford, England, the home base of
the Royal Shakespeare Company.
   ``Barbara was so nice,'' Miss Hateley says. ``She's so motherly
and was always lovely to me. I think she didn't want to be nasty,
which is what the part requires.''
   Betty Buckley, who played the gym teacher in the movie version
of ``Carrie,'' has now taken over the role of the mother.
   ``She came in and said, `Let's get into this,''' Miss Hateley
says. ``The score hasn't really changed a lot since then, just the
way that it is being done has. It's becoming a little weirder now.
Before it was very melodic. Now it's stranger.''
   Miss Hateley is from a small town near Birmingham in central
England. Her father is a toolmaker and her mother a secretary.
Neither had any theatrical aspirations. Their daughter, the second
of two children, did.
   ``When I was very young, I had a lot of energy,'' Miss Hateley
says.``I was always a real pain until I started dancing and got rid
of some of that energy.''
   She was sent to the local dancing school and got jobs in
community productions. At the age of 14, she was accepted by the
Italia Conti in London, and her parents took out loans to pay the
expensive tuition.
   ``I'm paying them back now out of my salary,'' Miss Hateley
says. ``They did so much for me.''
   While at the school, she auditioned for ``Carrie,'' singing ``On
My Own'' from ``Les Miserables.'' After a second audition, she got
the job.
   Her parents came to see the musical in Stratford and were
surprised at her performance.
   ``They knew that I sang well and obviously they were very
confident in me or they wouldn't have let me go to the theater
school in the first place,'' Miss Hateley says. ``But more than
anything, they were shocked with the acting I was doing. They had
never really seen me act.''
   The young actress worked closely with Hands, best known on
Broadway as the man who staged the RSC productions of ``Much Ado
About Nothing'' and ``Cyrano de Bergerac,'' with Derek Jacobi and
Sinead Cusack.
   It wasn't until the show moved to New York and started to
rehearse again that Miss Hateley began to understand her character.
   ``I've just suddenly come to realize that the whole thing about
Carrie is that she really is quite an intelligent person,'' Miss
Hateley says. ``She doesn't have to be ugly and she doesn't have to
be awkward. She can be quite beautiful in her own way. She's just
different.''
   When Miss Hateley first started doing the role, she wondered how
she could keep up the intense pace required by it. Now she is
getting used to it.
   ``I take everything as it comes and even if the show isn't a
success, it's still a great achievement for me and a great
experience,'' Miss Hateley says. ``I listen to everybody's advice.
I'm not saying that I always take it but if I listen to it all,
then I can make my own decisions. I'm learning so much and so
quickly. I have to.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
