<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Brazil-Blacks Adv08-2Takes   05-02 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Brazil-Blacks, Adv 08-2 Takes,0744</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Slaves Freed 100 Years Ago but Racial Strain Remain in Brazil</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note May 13th anniversary.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY LISA GENASCI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALVADOR, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On May 13, 1888, Princess Isabel of
Brazil signed the Golden Law and 780,000 slaves went free, three
centuries after blacks first came in bondage from Africa.
   A hundred years later the Brazilian government is commemorating
the event with tributes to what it calls ``racial democracy.''
   Blacks, however, maintain that widespread prejudice and
inequality leave them little to celebrate.
   President Jose Sarney has designated May 13 a national holiday.
The government, the media and the Roman Catholic Church have begun
nationwide campaigns aimed at portraying Brazil's multi-racial
society as integrated.
   But while millions of Brazilian blacks and whites live and work
side by side in apparent harmony, many here contend that ``racial
democracy'' is a myth.
   ``Abolition of slavery here was merely a legal act. It has meant
little in reality,'' said Arnaldo Beltrami, spokesman for the
Brazilian Bishops council, which in the world's largest Catholic
nation is given great importance.
   The Golden Law, already approved by the national legislature,
was signed by Princess Isabel while her father, Emperor Dom Pedro
II, was out of the country. The 780,000 slaves joined millions of
other blacks already released from bondage and they were left to
fend for themselves without education, training or jobs.
   It happened 25 years and 134 days after Abraham Lincoln's
Emancipation Proclamation in the United States.
   As the slavery issue helped set off the Civil War in the United
States, abolition in Brazil, without compensation to slave owners,
was a factor in the ouster of Dom Pedro's monarchy and the
establishment of Brazil as an republic.
   Today, blacks and mulattoes make up about 80 million of Brazil's
143 million people. They are prominent in sports and entertainment
_ among them the soccer great Pele, singer-composer Milton
Nascimento and actor-vaudevillean Grande Othello.
   But political leaders, army generals, corporate executives,
diplomats and bishops are almost exclusively the descendants of
white Portuguese colonizers or other white European immigrants.
   The 559-seat national Congress has just seven black members.
   Help-wanted ads still specify that applicants should have a
``good appearance,'' meaning they should be white.
   Blacks are unwelcome in many restaurants, bars and upper-class
apartment buildings, where doormen sometimes force them to use the
service entrance.
   ``Blacks here are found in hillside shantytowns, working as
maids or as manual laborers, in prisons and in juvenile delinquency
centers,'' said Benedita da Silva, Brazil's first black
congresswoman and a former maid.
   To the casual observer, Brazil is an astonishing blend of racial
types.
   Centuries of racial mixing, starting with the Portuguese, native
Indians and then African slaves, have produced a range of skin hues
and hair types that the country's Portuguese language defines in
120 different ways.
   Much of Brazilian culture also comes from black Africa,
including samba music, many typical national dishes such as
``feijoada'' black bean stew, cachaca sugar cane liquor, and
popular voodoo-type spirit religions.
   President Sarney, in announcing the May 13 holiday, spoke of a
mixed-race people ``living and growing in harmony.'' He held up
Brazil as a model for nations like South Africa.
   TV GLobo, the country's largest private television network, for
several months has been broadcasting a public service announcement
with well-known black performers and athletes wishing viewers
``Axe'' (pronounced ah-SHEH), an African word meaning ``good luck''
and ``power.''
   Another TV message sponsored by the Roman Catholic Archdiocese
of Rio de Janeiro shows a black hand and a white hand slowly
clasping while a voice says, ``Many races, one people.''
   The government-controlled Bank of Brazil is paying for a similar
media campaign.
   But racial prejudice still runs deep.
   Paulo de Jesus, 18, lives with his father and four brothers and
sisters in a crumbling Portuguese colonial-era house in Salvador, a
city of 1.8 million, about 1,120 miles northeast of Rio de Janeiro.
Salvador was Brazil's capital in the 17th century and as the
principal slave port became a center of black culture.
   Paulo de Jesus said he does not feel discriminated against, but
he added that he often is stopped, searched and asked for
identification by police officers. Twice he has been arrested on
``suspicion,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
