<DOCNO> AP880502-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Brazil-Blacks Adv08-1stAdd   05-02 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Brazil-Blacks, Adv 08-1st Add,0701</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>SALVADOR, Brazil: he said.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In a recent independent survey, 309 Brazilian youngsters 7 to 18
years old were asked to look at photographs of a white and a black
person and to link certain characteristics to each. The survey
indicated that 82.9 percent of the children considered the black
man ``stupid,'' 85.7 percent found him ``ugly'' and 84.2 percent
saw him as ``a thief.'' In comparison, the percentages,
respectively, for the white were 17.1, 14.3 and 15.8.
   In Rio de Janeiro, a black businesswoman married to a white
Swiss citizen told the newspaper Jornal do Brasil that when she
tried to pay for dinner by check at a fashionable nightclub, the
management refused to accept it, apparently in the belief the
checkbook was stolen.
   ``They insulted me and threw me out,'' Elisabeth da Silva
Zobrist told the paper. ``I called the police and ended up with the
manager at the precinct station. They accepted my check only after
the police chief called up my house and confirmed I was who I said
I was.''
   Blacks also lag behind whites in education and income.
   A government census showed blacks on average complete just 2.1
years of schooling, compared to 4.8 years for whites. And blacks
earn 47 percent less than whites doing the same work, according to
a 1985 labor union study.
   ``Blacks have never been integrated into Brazilian society as
full citizens,'' said the black composer and singer Gilberto Gil,
who also is the Bahia state secretary of culture.
   ``We need to think about what Princess Isabel's signature on a
piece of paper actually meant for us, if anything,'' Gil added in
an interview in his office in Salvador, Bahia's capital.
   Starting in the 1500s, Brazil brought in an estimated 3.6
million West Africans to work on sugar, cotton and coffee
plantations and to mine gold and diamonds.
   The abolitionist movement grew after 1850, when the government
outlawed slave trading. In 1871 the Free Womb Law declared that
children born of slave mothers would be considered free.
   When Brazil finally abolished slavery, it was the last country
in the Western Hemisphere to do so, and under sharp international
censure.
   ``The emancipation actually took the wind out of a growing
abolitionist movement. Maybe our lives would be different if the
law had not been signed just then,'' said the black historian and
activist Joao Jorge Rodrigues. He suggested Brazil could have taken
more time to prepare blacks for citizenship.
   But the documentary history of slavery in Brazil was virtually
erased in 1891 when Finance Minister Ruy Barbosa had the records of
slave trade burned on grounds that the country should look ahead
and forget its ``African'' past.
   Possibly because of that, black consciousness today is dim and
black pride almost non-existent. Few black rights groups or
activists exist. Many mixed-race Brazilians seek to appear whiter
and climb the social ladder.
   ``There is no such thing as `black' here,'' said Januario
Garcia, head of the Institute for Research on Black Culture in Rio
de Janeiro. ``People use any word but black to define themselves.
They want to be as white as possible.''
   Still, in this centennial year, awareness of discrimination is
growing.
   At Rio de Janeiro's famous pre-Lenten Carnival parades this past
February, many of the poor, mostly black groups competing for
prizes with floats and samba music chose racism as their themes,
rather than the usual folklore motifs.
   The champion group, Vila Isabel, offered a tribute to Zumbi,
leader of a 17th century slave revolt and a hideaway for runaway
slaves. The runnerup was the Mangueira school, which sang of blacks
``free from the master's whip, but trapped in the slums.''
   Many black groups said they don't intend to celebrate the May 13
holiday but planned festivities for Nov. 20.
   That is the anniversary of the death of Zumbi, killed in 1695 by
Portuguese troops who defended slave owners.
   ``We need to celebrate black strength, not a gift from white
men,'' Garcia said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
