<DOCNO> AP880502-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1400EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-India-Wars-Sikhs Adv08   05-02 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-India-Wars-Sikhs, Adv 08,0782</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Killing Goes on in Sikh War for Independent Homeland</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Companion stories are BC-India-Wars-Gurkhas, b0603, and
BC-India-Wars-Buddhists, b0605.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The killing goes on as it has for six
years and the prospects for peace talks have grown slimmer in the
war waged by Sikh militants for an autonomous homeland in the
Indian state of Punjab.
   In an apparent move to open peace talks, Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi freed a radical Sikh priest from jail, but then he said he
would talk only within the framework of the Indian Constitution.
   The militants responded that they will not negotiate until the
government accepts their demand for the independent Sikh nation of
Khalistan, a concept that is very much outside the Consititution.
   ``We will continue tofight in the same manner until we get
Khalistan,'' said Jagir Singh, spokesman for the Panthic Committee,
an underground umbrella grouping of militant Sikh groups.
   ``It is not a demand,'' he said in an interview. ``It is our
right.''
   Sikhs make up 2 percent of India's 800 million people but are a
majority in Punjab. Sikh militants claim they are being subjugated
by Hindus, who form 80 percent of the population.
   The Sikh agitation has claimed at least 735 lives this year and
the violence has worsened recently.
   More than 350 people have been killed in the six weeks since
Gandhi freed the radical Sikh priest Jasbir Singh Rode from jail.
   The killings blamed on Sikh militias have raised fears that the
government would turn a harsher face toward Punjab. At the same
time the priest was freed, Gandhi pushed through Parliament a bill
that would allow the government to clamp emergency rule on Punjab,
severely limiting individual rights.
   Jagir Singh was asked in the interview if he expected a
government move to drive out the radicals who have taken refuge in
the Golden Temple, the Sikh holy place in Amitsar.
   ``We are ready for an attack,'' he said.
   He characterized the militants' attitude with a Punjabi proverb:
``A brick will be replied to with a stone.''
   Indian officials seek to play down the possibility of a raid on
the temple. An army raid in 1984 left more than 1,200 people dead,
most of them Sikhs, and the desecration of the shrine angered the
entire Sikh community. Five months later, Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi, Rajiv Gandhi's mother, was assassinated by Sikh bodyguards
in an act of revenge.
   Police officers in Amritsar see little hope that conciliatory
moves by the government would end the violence.
   ``These people kill nearly 10 people every day,'' said Izhar
Alam, Amritsar district police superintendent. ``We must take
strong action.''
   He added this should include sending security forces into the
Golden Temple, where about 100 armed militants are believed to have
taken shelter.
   Alam also said police alone could not raid the temple complex.
   ``Other forces will have to be included,'' he said. ``The
militants have AK-47 automatic rifles and carbines. All we (the
police) have is .303 rifles and pistols.''
   The biggest impediment to any plan to raid the militants'
sanctuary is a threat held out by Rode, the freed priest.
   ``If the government enters the temple, they will be laying the
foundation for Khalistan,'' Rode said.
   He spoke at a meeting April 13 of about 40,000 Sikhs in south
Punjab. It was his first major appearance since his release and
there were reports he would encourage moderation among the
militants and that a peaceful approach would come from the meeting.
   But most speakers urged more agitation. While Rode did not
directly support moves for Khalistan, he called for continuing a
movement to ``free Sikhs from the bonds of slavery.''
   ``His demands are the same as ours,'' Jagir Singh said a day
later.
   Rode, named to the most influential Sikh religious post shortly
after his release, denies entering into any deals with authorities.
He says the only way for a solution is for the government to talk
directly to the Sikh militants.
   Even moderate Sikhs believe the government should make the first
move for peace, such as freeing hundreds of Sikh youths jailed as
suspected militants.
   Devinder Singh, a farmer at the mass meeting of Sikhs, said the
government first has to prove it wants a settlement.
   ``People in Punjab distrust the government,'' he said. ``We have
been let down too many times. Let them offer something first.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-India-Wars-Buddhists Adv08   05-02 0940</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-India-Wars-Buddhists, Adv 08,0973</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Little-Known Buddhist Bush War Still Rages inside Bangladesh</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Companion stories are BC-India-Wars-Gurkhas, b0603, and
India-Wars-Sikhs, b0604.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELONIA HILLS, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Makeshift Buddhist pagodas dot the
jungle across the border from here in Bangladesh. But the rumble of
military vehicles and, sometimes, bursts of gunfire shatter the
tranquil setting, reminders that a little-known bush war that began
11 years ago still rages.
   The hymns of monks are silenced as terror flashes through the
refugee camps filled with Chakma tribespeople on this side of the
border.
   The Chakmas, descendants of the warlike Mongols who once surged
across Asia, are fighting the Bangladesh government to hold onto
their land, their Buddhist religion and their age-old customs
against an influx of Moslem settlers.
   Chakma guerrilla leaders say at least 4,000 people have died in
the cycle of killings and bloody reprisals since the Chakmas took
up arms in May 1977 and killed 40 Bangladesh policemen in their
first ambush.
   The battle is vicious, unequal, unremitting and rarely reported.
   Bangladesh seldom allows foreign reporters to visit the Chakmas'
ancestral homeland in the Chittagong Hill Tracts.
   India does not permit foreign journalists to travel to its
border states housing the refugees, but Indian reporters can make
the trip with police permission.
   The Chittagong Hill Tracts, which roll over 5,138 square miles
in southern Bangladesh, border Burma and the northeastern Indian
states of Tripura and Mizoram.
   Belonia Hills is the region in India's Tripura state that faces
the Chittagong Hill Tracts.
   In camouflage uniforms of war, Bangladeshi soldiers move from
village to village in the deep woods and jungles of the hill
tracts, often firing at random to frighten away the Chakmas,
sometimes to kill them, said Bakul Chakma, a refugee at the
Takumbari camp 10 miles from the border.
   The battle, often fought at midnight on jungle paths traveled by
elephants and reptiles, pits 20,000 Bangladeshi soldiers and 40,000
paramilitary troops and policemen against 4,000 guerrillas.
   In the past two years, more than 50,000 tribespeople have fled
to India's Tripura state to avoid the fighting.
   ``We tried enough persuasion. When nothing worked, we took up
arms,'' said Priti Kumar Chakma, a leader of the tribespeople's
``Shanti Bahini,'' or Army for Peace.
   ``What option do we have other than killing those who want to
finish us?'' the 41-year-old guerrilla said in an interview
arranged on condition the location not be disclosed.
   In 1987 Amnesty International, the London-based human rights
organization, said it had received ``increasing reports of
arbitrary arrests, torture and extrajudicial executions'' of
tribespeople in the Chittagong Hill Tracts by Bangladeshi troops.
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad's government in Bangladesh has
denied the allegations. It says it wants to develop the area and
has pledged the local currency equivalent of $90 million to help
tribesmen come down from the hills and join mainstream society.
   Islam is the official religion of Bangladesh, and about 80
percent of its 105 million people are Moslems. The remainder are
Hindus, Buddhists and Christians.
   Ershad's government in Dhaka, about 200 miles northwest of the
hill tracts, says it is absurd for the Chakmas to demand 11 percent
of the land in Bangladesh when they make up less than 0.5 percent
percent of the population.
   Bangladesh is one of the world's most densely populated nations.
   Most of the 600,000 tribespeople in the Chittagong Hill Tracts
are Chakmas. The others are Mogs and Tripuraies.
   So far about 300,000 Moslems have settled in the area and
thousands of Chakmas have been evicted from their homes in the deep
woods and moved to what the Dhaka government calls ``ideal
villages.''
   ``The so-called ideal villages are nothing but concentration
camps,'' charged Bimal Larma, a Chakma guerrilla.
   In addition to land, the Chakmas are demanding autonomy, but
this has been rejected by the government.
   The tribespeople, who speak a mixture of Tibetan-Burmese
dialects, fear they will become a minority in the hills where they
have lived for centuries.
   Their political wing, the United People's Party, charges that
some tribespeople have been forcibly converted to Islam and that
Moslem settlers are encouraged to marry Buddhist girls.
   ``We have no similarities at all with the Moslems,'' said
refugee Ranjit Narayan. ``We love pork; they despise it. We worship
Buddha; they follow Islam. Unless forced, we do not kill, but they
kill us at the slightest provocation.'' Narayan, 54, fled to India
in 1986 with his wife, four sons and a daughter.
   ``I have seen my neighboring villages being burned, women raped
and men killed. I told my wife, `We can't stay here anymore. Let us
go.' '' he said.
   They walked four days to reach Takumbari, the largest of seven
refugee camps in Tripura. The camps, which house 50,586 refugees,
have no electricity. The houses are made of bamboo and roofed with
dry leaves.
   Since Takumbari was set up two years ago, it's population has
swollen to 15,510. In that time, 546 people have died of disease
and 549 children have been born.
   The Indian government gives each adult and teen-ager a daily
ration of 14 ounces of rice and about two ounces each a day of
lentils and dry fish, plus 20 paise (about one U.S. cent). Children
under 12 get half-rations.
   Bangladesh has accused India of aiding the Chakma rebels.
   ``This is absurd. We have enough problems of our own,'' Tripura
Interior Minister Samir Ranjan Burman said. ``We are helping the
Chakmas on purely humanitarian grounds.
   ``We cannot push them back, it would mean certain death for
them.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
