<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   05-02 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0529</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Zelly and Me''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Once upon a time in Hollywood the ``woman's picture'' held sway.
American women flocked to matinees and sobbed and sympathized with
the plight of such stars as Joan Crawford, Bette Davis, Norma
Shearer and Greta Garbo.
   No more. Movie matinees are largely populated by small fry and
weary shoppers in malls.
   ``Zelly and Me'' arrives a few decades late. It is patently a
woman's picture: the writer-director, co-producer and leading
performers are women.
   However, despite the best performance yet by Isabella
Rossellini, the film cannot escape a pervading preciousness, and
its chances of finding a wide audience of both sexes seem slender
indeed.
   The Zelly of the title is Mademoiselle (Rossellini), the
European nanny whose life is devoted to her young charge, the
orphaned Phoebe (Alexandra Jones). They live in a mansion presided
over by Phoebe's autocratic grandmother, Coco (Glynis Johns).
   Zelly and Phoebe occupy a fantasy world of stuffed animals, all
with special names and identities, and they share a devotion to the
legend of Joan of Arc (filmgoers will recall that Miss Rossellini's
mother, Ingrid Bergman, portrayed Joan of Arc on the screen).
   For reasons that aren't quite clear, Coco punishes the child for
faultless infractions. The punishments become more severe, even
sadistic. Phoebe, whose parents were killed in a fiery plane crash,
burns herself in retaliation.
   The nanny helplessly watches Phoebe's torment, finding solace
only in day-off meetings with the neighbor in another mansion
(David Lynch). When Zelly is fired by the enraged grandmother, the
pair dream up a scheme to spirit away Phoebe. The conclusion brings
happiness to no one.
   ``Zelly and Me'' is the first feature film by Tina Rathborne,
and it appears at least partly autobiographical. Her attention to
the details of girlhood becomes almost unbearably cloying, and only
in the latter portions does the film gain any momentum.
   Within the confines of a largely ineffectual role, Rossellini
performs with an inner radiance hauntingly like her mother's.
Johns, absent too long from the screen, is effective in a seemingly
unrewarding role. Alexandra Jones is a gifted young actress, fully
capable of occupying the screen by herself.
   David Lynch, director of ``Blue Velvet,'' makes his acting debut
as the neighbor who is not what he seems. He seems stiff in the
role, needful of the direction of, say, David Lynch.
   The Columbia Pictures release was produced by Sue Jett and Tony
Mark. The rating is PG; small children might be frightened by the
girl's punishment. Running time: 87 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
