<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   That wonderful magic from the Disney animation
wand will be in video stores on May 31 in time for summer rentals
and sales.
   Walt Disney Home Video is also offering a limited edition Mickey
Mouse videocassette to help celebrate Mickey's 60th birthday. The
original feature includes snippets from some of the mouse's
greatest hits, including the Socerer's Apprentice segment from
``Fantasia.''
   Other Disney features for summer fun include ``Mickey and the
Beanstalk,'' ``Donald in Mathmagic Land'' and ``The Reluctant
Dragon.''
   And hold on to your feathers, duck fans: Disney also plans to
release three volumes of the hit TV ``Ducktales'' series, featuring
the adventures and misadventures of Duckburg's leading citizen,
Scrooge McDuck, and his nephews Huey, Dewey and Louie.
   The series has received raves from critics. TV Guide said the
animated comedy-adventure show ``features the superior production
values and animation kids of all ages have come to expect from
Disney.''
   Also in May HBO is releasing ``Weeds'' and ``House of Games,''
and Orion Home Video has scheduled Danny DeVito's zany sendup of
matricide, ``Throw Mama From the Train.''
   Videos reviewed this week:
   
   ``Weeds'' (HBO Video, VHS@Beta, $89.99, Rated R
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   NEW YORK _ At the start of ``Weeds,'' Lee Umstetter, doing a
life sentence for armed robbery, attempts suicide twice _ once by
leaping from his cell block at San Quentin, and once by a crude
attempt at hanging himself.
   ``Depressed, are you?'' asks his cell mate.
   ``Well, I needed a little vacation,'' replies the droll Lee,
played by Nick Nolte.
   That's about as deep as the explanations get in ``Weeds,'' a
flat, humorless film based on a play by a real-life ex-con who,
like Umstetter, was confined to the California state penitentiary.
   In the film, Umstetter decides to channel his rage and
frustration into creativity. With only a 6th grade education, he
reads Dostoevski, Tolstoy, Nietszche and Genet.
   Borrowing a bit too liberally from his readings, he writes a
play about prison life called ``Weeds.'' It's produced in San
Quentin and, unaccountably, there happens to be a rich, beautiful
critic in the audience named Lillian Binghamton. Equally
unaccountably, eyes meet and, presto, it's amore.
   Lillian, played by Rita Taggart, writes a rave review and
campaigns successfully to free her new-found love from prison.
   It turns out, though, she isn't much of a critic since she
failed to perceive that the play is largely plagiarized.
   Later in the movie, she catches Umstetter in bed with a younger
woman. There's a touch of chagrin from this person who has freed
her lover from a life in prison. But in a moment or so, it's
forgotten.
   Lillian, in short, is incredibly dimwitted.
   The movie winds on episodically, with Umstetter forming a
traveling acting troupe made up of his old jail buddies. They take
it on the road, finally making it to New York where the New York
Times drama critic takes the wind temporarily out of their sails.
   But by this time the play is not the counterfeit it started out
to be. It's so real, in fact, that they produce it in a prison and
cause a riot.
   Presto! Instant headlines and fame, and the bright lights of
Broadway.
   Sure. Right.
   ``Weeds'' is rated ``R'' for strong prison language and some
nudity.
   _ By Lee Mitgang, AP Education Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``House of Games'' (HBO Video, VHS@Beta, $89.99, Rated R)
   
   ``House of Games'' is set in the seedy underworld of con
artists, and the movie is _ deliberately _ something of a con
itself.
   Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright David Mamet, who wrote and
directed this 1980's film noir, repeatedly confounds the viewer by
staging increasingly elaborate confidence games. It's often
difficult to be sure who's conning whom, and that's what makes the
movie such creepy fun.
   Lindsay Crouse plays Dr. Margaret Ford, a psychiatrist who has
just made a lot of money writing a book but who is clearly unhappy,
maybe even clinically depressed. On an impulse, she decides to help
a patient who is a compulsive gambler and visits the House of Games
where she encounters Mike, the ringleader of the con artists,
played by Joe Mantegna.
   She is strongly attracted to Mike and also to the excitement of
his dangerous profession. In a series of plot twists she moves from
victim to accomplice to aggressor, drawn ever deeper into a web of
deceit that seems certain eventually to destroy her.
   Crouse, who is married to Mamet, is fascinating in a role
tailor-made for her, while Mantegna has just the right oily charm
for his part.
   All in all, ``House of Games'' is an original, diverting film
and well worth a look for those who missed it in theaters last year.
   _ By Mike Silverman, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
