<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 2129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   05-02 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0773</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Hairspray'' (MCA) _ various artists.
   ``Dirty Dancing'' (RCA) _ various artists.
   ``More Dirty Dancing'' (RCA) _ various artists.
   
   ``Do You Love Me?'' by the Contours is one of peaks of rock 'n'
roll, matching depth of anxiety to banality of lyric in the finest
tradition of the Clearasil generation. ``You broke my heart, 'cause
I couldn't dance ...'' Ah, what a world of pain recalled.
   Then there's that trick fade, before the Contours come booming
back _ ``Work! Work!'' _ in an ecstatic finale.
   Great as it is, ``Do You Love Me?'' doesn't rescue the ``Dirty
Dancing'' soundtrack albums from the contempt of all prudent
consumers. RCA has spread this collection on two compact discs,
giving as little as 35 minutes of retread listening in a format
that would hold twice as much. So they're charging $25 or more for
what is essentially a $2 record in the oldies bin.
   The real sin, though, is the mixture of old and new. Oldies, as
John Waters says, are ``the only known remedy to today's Hit Parade
of Hell.''
   The soundtrack collection from Waters' first mainstream film,
``Hairspray,'' is the better buy. The title track, despite its
satirical intent, is absolutely faithful to the old sound.
   But again, the exasperated consumer wonders, why no instructions
for dancing the Madison along with ``The Madison Time'' by The Ray
Bryant Combo?
   Through such indifference, the old tribal wisdom is in danger of
being lost.
   _ By Robert Barr, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Naked'' (Sire) _ Talking Heads
   
   Too often on ``Naked,'' it's impossible even to guess what the
Talking Heads are talking about. David Byrne's oblique lyrics are
frustrating because there are snatches of wonderful imagery that
leave the listener begging for more details.
   Byrne's eccentricity probably isn't the only reason it's hard to
find a plot in ``Naked.'' The Talking Heads recorded the basic
tracks before Byrne began to work on the tune or words, reducing
his flexibility as a composer.
   But while the record's melodies and lyrics are less than fluid,
rhythmically ``Naked'' is a marvel _ so lively it would make even
Tipper Gore want to dance.
   The Talking Heads brought in studio musicians to create a denser
sound than on their last two records. As a result, instruments dart
in and out of the arrangements, almost always serving to enhance
the syncopation. The band and its co-producer, Steve Lillywhite,
achieved a full but remarkably clean sound.
   Most momentous is the satirical ``(Nothing But) Flowers,'' in
which Byrne provides a fresh perspective on urban sprawl by
describing with mock horror a place where ``highways and cars were
sacrificed for agriculture.''
   ``Mr. Jones'' and ``Totally Nude'' are also made for the dance
floor, while the best of the slower songs is the darkly melodic
``Bill,'' about a fat man, a little girl and a gun. What happens?
We don't know. The song, like too much of ``Naked,'' is clothed in
ambiguity.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Tracy Chapman'' (Elektra@Asylum) _ Tracy Chapman
   
   One of Boston's best kept secrets was a young
poet-songwriter-folksinger named Tracy Chapman. Not any more.
   With the release of her self-titled debut LP the world has a new
musical gift. Her rich contralto with its melancholic underpinnings
sweep us back to the early 1970s _ to Joan Armatrading, Carol King
and Joni Mitchell. Her lyrics, with a deadbolt look at poverty,
racism and inequality take us back even further _ to Bob Dylan,
Odetta, Pete Seeger.
   The LP opens with ``Talkin' Bout a Revolution,'' a song that
tells of ``standing in the welfare lines, crying at the doorsteps
of those armies of salvation, wasting time in the unemployment
lines, sitting around waiting for a promotion.''
   The a cappella ``Behind the Wall,'' talks of a domestic fight:
``Last night I heard the screaming, then a silence that chilled my
soul.''
   As an undergraduate at Tufts University in Medford, Mass.,
Chapman performed in coffee houses and clubs. She was something of
a mesmerizing hit for locals who flocked to hear her.
   Her debut LP, with its range from folk to pop ballad to reggae,
is likely to enchant even more.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
   

</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
