<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-02 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0544</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy reversed a three-month slowdown in
April as production and new orders picked up sharply, according to
a survey of purchasing managers.
   The National Association of Purchasing Managers said Sunday its
index of economic activity rose to 54.9 percent last month from
53.3 percent in March.
   The index had declined the first three months of the year,
indicating a slowing in economic growth. A reading above 50 percent
generally indicates economic expansion, while a reading below that
benchmark indicates the economy is declining, the group says.
   __
   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The government's economic indicators are
pointing to continued growth.
   The Commerce Department said Friday its Index of Leading
Indicators rose 0.8 percent in March after a revised 1.3 percent
gain in February.
   In another report, the government said sales of new homes rose 4
percent in March, the second consecutive monthly advance.
   Earlier in the week, the government said the overall economy
expanded at a 2.3 percent annual rate in the first three months of
the year.
   Allen Sinai, chief economist of the Boston Co., called the
string of upbeat reports ``terrific news on the future state of the
economy.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Back-to-back increases in new home sales have
pushed such sales to the highest levels since August, the
government says.
   The 4 percent rise in new homes sales in March followed a 14.1
percent jump the previous month, the departments of Housing and
Urban Development, and Commerce said Friday.
   But some analysts are worried that rising mortgage rates could
limit growth in the second half of the year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average prices that farmers got for raw
products held steady in April for the second month in a row but
were 4 percent above a year ago, the government says.
   ``Prices were higher for soybeans, cattle, hay and oranges, and
lower for lettuce, eggs, milk and strawberries,'' the federal
Agricultural Statistics Board said Friday.
   Consumer food prices are expected to rise 2 percent to 4 percent
this year, compared with a 4.1 percent average increase in 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC oil ministers have suspended for a
month their efforts to agree on a proposed token cut in oil
production.
   Ministers of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
said early today they would reconvene June 8 to discuss the
proposed reductions.
   Several ministers expressed disappointment at the breakdown of
the four-day-old negotiations, which they viewed as a chance to
shore up oil prices and open a new avenue to cooperation with
non-OPEC producers who had proposed the production cuts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CORNING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corning Glass Works, the nation's leading
maker of cookware, has signed a definitive agreement to purchase
Revere Ware Inc., the second-largest manufacturer of range-top
cookware.
   Corning said Friday the acquisition would be made in cash, but
spokesman Eugene Saunders would not comment on a report that the
price was $120 million.
   Revere Ware, a Clinton, Ill.-based maker of stainless steel and
copper cookware, is a subsidiary of the privately held Revere
Copper and Brass Inc.
</TEXT>
