<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co. says it has extended
by two weeks its $1.74 billion tender offer for Lucky Stores Inc.
and may sweeten the bid.
   In a statement issued Friday in New York, American Stores said
the extension of the offer was being made in light of Lucky's
decision to merge with a New York investment firm in a $2.2 billion
leveraged buyout.
   The tender offer is now scheduled to expire May 13.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines has reached a tentative
four-year contract agreement covering its 10,000 mechanics and
ground service employees.
   The company also said Friday its has signed a contract with the
union representing 6,700 flight attendants.
   Meanwhile, the parent of Northwest Airlines, NWA Inc., reported
its first-quarter loss widened to $43.5 million from a loss of $35
million in the first three months of 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission
has filed a brief in federal court challenging Delaware's new
takeover law, arguing that the measure is unconstitutional.
   The SEC's brief is considered significant because it could play
a role in the fate of the law in Delaware, where many U.S.
corporations are incorporated. State officials said Friday they had
not decided whether or how to respond to the brief, which was filed
a day earlier in U.S. District Court.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department has proposed making
employers put warning tags or locks on machinery as it is being
cleaned or serviced.
   The proposal announced Friday comes nine years after unions
requested the regulation and more than 1,000 deaths later as a
result of its absence.
   The proposed regulations, which the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration estimates will save 122 lives and prevent
60,000 injuries annually, had languished at the White House for
nearly a year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission says it will try
to block Schering-Plough Corp.'s acquisition of the contact lens
assets of Cooper Cos.
   The agency directed its staff Friday to seek a court order
blocking the $150 million takeover, charging that the move would
significantly reduce competition in the manufacture and sale of
soft contact lenses.
   Schering-Plough, based in Madison, N.J., produces lenses through
its Wesley-Jessen Inc. subsidiary in Chicago. Cooper, with
headquarters in Palo Alto, Calif., makes and sells lenses through
its Menlo Park subsidiary, CooperVision.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished mixed Friday in a slow session that
saw the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials drop 8.95 to 2,032.33.
   The dollar finished higher against most major currencies.
   Bond prices finished slightly lower.
   Soybean futures prices soared to new contract highs, other grain
futures and livestock and meat prices were mixed and energy futures
were mostly lower.
</TEXT>
