<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoTalks     05-02 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Talks,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Expects Chrysler Progress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bargainers for Chrysler Corp. and
the United Auto Workers continued negotiations centering on
displaced Wisconsin employees in hopes of clearing the way for a
national contract settlement.
   The final push on the national pact won't begin until local
agreements are reached covering 6,500 employees in Kenosha, Wis.,
and Milwaukee.
   Local talks continued Sunday, and UAW Vice President Marc Stepp,
head of the union's Chrysler department, said negotiations would
continue into the night.
   UAW President Owen Bieber was to join national contract talks
today at Chrysler headquarters.
   Stepp said Sunday he expected Wisconsin workers to be covered by
the same basic language contained in the overall Chrysler
agreement. But any enhanced job security provisions in the
agreement wouldn't be implemented until the Kenosha assembly plant
is closed, he said.
   Talks on the national contract, which expires Sept. 14 and
covers 66,000 active workers in 15 states, began April 18, four
months early.
   Last week, Chrysler said it would wait until the end of the year
to close the 5,500-worker former American Motors Corp. plant in
Kenosha and to transfer K-car assembly work from Detroit to Mexico.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
