<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ADM-Millers     05-02 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ADM-Millers,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Millers at Archer Daniels Midland Reject Contract Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the grain millers union at
Archer Daniels Midland Co. have voted by a 3-1 margin to reject the
agricultural company's three-year contract proposal.
   But the American Federation of Grain Millers Local 103 also
agreed to work under the old contract terms while negotiations
continue, an official said. The old contract expires today.
   According to Local 103 President Charlie Hood, members needed
about four hours to examine the numerous differences between the
current pact and the proposal.
   Hood categorized the 44-page document as containing ``excessive
concessionary demands.''
   After turning down the proposal, the local agreed to have a
federal mediator set the next meeting between management and the
union. The move was also acceptable to ADM's negotiator, Hood said.
   Hood refused to comment on pay, insurance or other ``financial
issues.'' Key issues, he said, concerned ``creating a joint
management-labor safety program, trying to eliminate rotating
shifts, extending time off for work-related injuries and basic
civil rights in the plant.''
   He declined to elaborate on the civil rights issue.
   ``The company has made it clear that the reason for these
concessionary demands is for increased corporate profit,'' Hood
said. ``It is difficult for the membership to understand in the
face of past and projected profits that the company needs these
additional concessions.''
</TEXT>
