<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Corn showed the greatest strength, opening slightly higher on
improving export prospects. Several countries, including South
Korea, Taiwan and India, were expected to bid this week for
shipments of U.S. corn, analysts said.
   ``This is one of the better lineups we've seen for export
business in the last three (to) four weeks,'' said Dale Gustafson,
an analyst in Chicago with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Wheat opened fractionally higher; soybeans were slightly lower
following last week's dramatic gains. But losses in the soybean
market were limited by ongoing concern about dry weather
conditions, Gustafson said.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to } cent higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.05\ a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to 1 cent higher with May at $2.03\ a bushel; oats were {
cent to 1{ cents lower with May at $1.58} a bushel; soybeans were }
cent to 1{ cents lower with May at $6.88} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .18 cent to .40 cent higher with June at 71.30
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .18 cent lower to .18 cent higher
with May at 78.85 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .60 cent
higher with June at 49.32 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.47 cent to .80 cent higher with May at 52.15 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly higher on Friday while most pork
futures retreated.
</TEXT>
