<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Boeing     05-02 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Boeing,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Orders Airlines To Check Boeing 737s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transport Ministry said Monday it recommended
to Japanese airlines that they ground and conduct maintenance
checks on Boeing 737 jets of the model that lost part of its
fuselage over Hawaii.
   An official of the ministry's engineering deparment said there
are 21 Boeing 737s in Japan being operated by All Nippon Airways,
Air Nippon and Nansei Koku airline.
   ``We are not ordering the airlines to do so, but we are
suggesting they do it for safety,'' said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   He noted the Boeing company's service bulletin had recommended
checks on 737s that have over 30,000 landings, and that there are
nine such 737s being flown in Japan.
   The suggestion came after the U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration ordered Hawaii's Aloha Airlines to check old 737
jetliners that have been flown 55,000 times or more.
   The upper fuselage of an Aloha Airlines 737 with 89 passengers
and five crew members aboard peeled off on an inter-island flight
last Thursday. One person was killed and 61 others were injured.
</TEXT>
