<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Scotus-FishingRights     05-02 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Fishing Rights,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Award Attorneys' Fees to Tribes in Fishing Rights
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to award
nearly $3 million in attorneys' fees to Indian tribes who won a
lengthy court battle against Washington state officials over
fishing rights.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that struck
down the award on grounds a federal law reimbursing lawyers who
represent the winning side in civil rights cases does not apply to
the Indians' lawsuit.
   Twenty-one tribes sought to recapture legal fees awarded by a
federal judge who then was overruled by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals. The Indians were supported by 33 other tribes who said
their ability to vindicate treaty rights could be undermined if
they are unable to recover legal fees won in court.
   The case acted on today stems from a 1970 lawsuit in which
Indians asserted fishing rights in Washington state waters based on
a treaty signed in 1885.
   Indians relinquished land under the treaty in return for
guarantees of fishing rights. The treaty said the Indians have the
``right of taking fish at usual and accustomed grounds and stations
... in common with all citizens of the territory.''
   Federal courts ultimately ruled the treaty entitled the tribes
to approximately half the harvestable fish in state waters that
passed through recognized tribal fishing areas. The Supreme Court
upheld those rights in 1979.
   Years of litigation over legal fees followed, leading in 1985 to
a federal judge's award of $2.95 million to the tribes to be paid
by Washington state.
   But the 9th Circuit court threw out the award last year.
   The appeals court said the fishing rights case was not covered
by a 1976 federal law reimbursing the prevailing side's legal
expenses in civil rights lawsuits.
   The appeals court said, in effect, that Washington state
officials did not violate deliberately the Indians' rights by
limiting their fishing harvest. The case was a dispute over the
intepretation of the treaty, the appeals court said.
   ``It is not disputed that the Indians had rights under the
treaty,'' the appeals court said. ``Just exactly what those rights
were was unknown until the Supreme Court decision (in 1979.) If the
state of Washington violates these now known and well-delineated
rights, there would be an actual conflict between state and federal
law which might give rise'' to a federal civil rights lawsuit.
   The appeals court added: ``That, however, has not yet happened
and is not the situation here.'' Therefore, there is no basis for
the award of legal fees, it said.
   Indians said the ruling could be devastating to their efforts at
enforcing treaty rights.
   ``Cases to vindicate treaty rights affecting important resources
of an area may take years to complete because of the extreme
sensitivity of the issues,''said a group of 33 tribes who supported
the appeal by the Washigton tribes. ``Such cases are especially
draining on normally scarce tribal resources.''
   The case is Makah Tribe vs. State of Washington, 87-1390.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
