<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1501EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-US     05-02 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-US,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Demands Wider Opening Of South Korea's Domestic Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. trade delegation demanded
Monday that South Korea open its domestic markets to U.S. goods and
end restrictive trade practices to help ease the American trade
deficit.
   Peter Allgier, assistant U.S. trade representative, made the
demand at the start of a three-day trade meeting with South Korean
officials which opened in Seoul on Monday.
   South Korean officials said Allgier, chief of the 19-member U.S.
delegation, asked South Korea to slash its growing trade surplus
with the United States by cutting tariffs and dismantling various
import and sales restrictions.
   Hwang Doo-young, head of the 19-member South Korean delegation,
explained Seoul's efforts to solve the problem and presented a
detailed schedule to open its market, the officials said.
   The officials declined to disclose details, however.
   The Seoul meeting, the officials said, will devote its first day
session to discussions on South Korea's high import tariffs and
future plans to open its market for such U.S. services and goods as
advertising, beer and wine.
   The two sides will spend the second day discussing Washington's
demand for retroactive protection of the U.S. intellectual property
rights, the officials said.
   The third will go for talks on eashing South Korea's alleged
restrictions on the sale of U.S. cigarettes, insurance and
agricultural products, they said.
   The Seoul meeting came after a series of bilateral talks on
solving the issues had failed. The United is threatening to
retaliate unless South Korea cuts its trade surplus with the United
States, which reached $9.5 billion last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1540EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BuildingContracts     05-02 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Building Contracts,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Building Contracts Down 3 Percent in March</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Construction Spending, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracts for new construction dropped 3 percent
in March, weakened by a sharp decline in commercial and industrial
building, according to a survey released Monday.
   The survey, conducted by the F.W. Dodge Division of McGraw-Hill
Information Systems Co., showed that the value of new construction
contracts on a seasonally adjusted, annualized basis fell to $242.4
billion in March from $249.7 billion in February.
   ``With the usual winter volatility out of the way, March
contracting data showed that 1988 construction activity is
beginning to settle into a credible pattern as housing firmed and
commercial building weakened,'' said George A. Christie, F.W. Dodge
vice president and chief economist.
   ``We can look for some temporary improvement of housing starts
in the months ahead as buyers become aware that mortgage rates
won't be going any lower for a while.''
   On the other hand, Christie said, commercial building faces the
prospect of an extended decline as the surplus of office space is
gradually absorbed.
   Contracting in March for commercial and industrial projects
dropped 19 percent from a month earlier, although institutional
building rose 14 percent, the survey showed.
   The value of newly started residential buildings declined 2
percent. Starts of single-family homes reached their highest rate
so far this year, but declines in apartment and hotel-motel
projects more than offset the modest improvement in single-family
building, F.W. Dodge said.
   Contracts for nonbuilding construction _ mainly public works and
utilities _ edged up 1 percent in March. Highway construction
rebounded after several sluggish months, but March contracts for
waste water treatment plants declined, leaving the total value of
public works contracts virtually unchanged from February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
