<DOCNO> AP880502-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1507EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OPECStandoff Bjt   05-02 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC Standoff, Bjt,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi Stance Illustrates Depth of Rift With Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-OPEC, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia's scuttling of an OPEC plan
for token cuts in oil production may signal a stiffened Saudi
resolve to hold down world oil prices and punish archenemy Iran.
   The Saudis appear increasingly intent on frustrating Iran's
efforts to galvanize a consensus for oil production cuts that could
send prices higher this summer.
   The result may be more in-fighting for the fractious
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and perhaps an even
deeper political paralysis.
   Prices fell sharply Monday after OPEC decided to suspend talks
on a proposed 2 percent cutback in oil production until June.
   Most industry observers had expected the Saudis to go along with
the cutback, since it was so small as to have virtually no effect
on OPEC evenues. An eight-country majority supported the cuts,
which were to be taken in conjunction with cutbacks by a group of
six independent oil-producing nations.
   The fact that Saudi Oil Minister Hisham Nazer stood fast against
the cuts appeared to mean the cartel's most influential member is
unwilling to accept any OPEC action that could lay the foundation
for an Iranian-led price increase.
   Last December the Saudis successfully defeated an Iranian
proposal to raise OPEC's official price by $2.70 a barrel, to
$20.70.
   Iran relies heavily on oil export revenues to finance its
7{-year-old war against Iraq. Saudi Arabia has helped bankroll the
Iraqi war effort.
   Paul Mlotok, who monitored the OPEC meeting for the New York
investment firm Salomon Brothers Inc., said he expected oil prices
to slump this week and then hold steady until OPEC's June meeting.
   Iran and other OPEC members had hoped that by cutting back a
little on production now, when world oil demand is relatively weak,
prices would rebound and then jump even higher this summer during
the traditional peak season for fuel consumption.
   By preventing an accord at the Vienna meeting, the Saudis
probably ensured that any summer price increases will be small,
limiting the benefit for Iran.
   ``This was, for the Saudis, a clear political victory,'' said
Bahman Karbassioun, a Vienna-based oil consultant and former member
of the OPEC staff.
   He said he believed the Saudis never had any intention during
the Vienna meeting of striking a compromise deal.
   ``It was a very well organized and well planned'' effort by the
Saudis to deny Iran the agreement it badly wanted, he said.
   Last week, two days before the OPEC meeting started, the Saudi
government announced it was breaking diplomatic relations with
Iran. It accused Tehran of engaging in terrorism and subversion.
   Kazempour Ardebili, the deputy Iranian oil minister, said after
the Saudi announcement that it may have been intended to spoil the
atmosphere of the Vienna meeting.
   Hashemi Rafsanjani, speaker of the Iranian Majlis, or
parliament, on Sunday said the Saudi stalling on oil production
cuts amounted to ``flagrant treachery'' orchestrated by the United
States.
   Saudi Arabia and Iran have been rivals for power and influence
within OPEC from the early days of the cartel, which was formed in
1960 but did not gain a grip on pricing until the Arab oil embargo
of 1973.
   In 1986, however, the Saudis and Iranians appeared to reach a
tacit understanding to work together following a price crash that
sent oil below $10 a barrel.
   The fragile alliance began to unravel last summer after rioting
at the holy city of Mecca, in Saudi Arabia, killed 402 people, most
of them Iranian.
   As long as relations between Iran and Saudi Arabia remain poor,
OPEC is likely to encounter major problems holding oil prices
steady, let alone raising them to the official target of $18 a
barrel.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Robert Burns has covered OPEC for The Associated
Press since 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
