<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FirstRepublicBank     05-02 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-First RepublicBank,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shareholders To Vote On Smaller Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First RepublicBank Corp.'s board of directors will
lose some prominent members if shareholders approve the next step
of the ailing bank holding company's restructuring efforts.
   A reduction in the board's size from to 16 from 33 will be
recommended to shareholders during First RepublicBank's annual
meeting June 28, spokesman Joseph C. Bowles said Monday.
   Albert Casey, the new chairman of the bank holding company, had
suggested the smaller board at a meeting last week, and the board
backed that proposal, Bowles said.
   Casey became chairman April 12 after federal insurers and
regulators decided a change in management was necessary to rebuild
Texas' largest bank holding company. A reduction in the size of the
board is a continuation of that change, Bowles said.
   The 17 board members who will not be up for re-election include
First RepublicBank President Joseph R. Musolino and some of Texas'
most prominent business leaders.
   Dallas businessman H.R. ``Bum'' Bright, majority owner of the
Dallas Cowboys; longtime board member James D. Berry, Ed R. Haggar,
chairman of Dallas-based Haggar Apparel Co.; and Texas Republican
Party chairman George W. Strake Jr. also will not be on the ballot,
Bowles said.
   He said no new individuals will be placed on the ballot for
election to the board. Casey, Dallas businessman Charles Cullum and
San Antonio, Texas, businessman Sam Barshop are among the 16 board
members who will remain.
   First RepublicBank posted a first quarter loss of $1.5 billion,
forcing an emergency federal recaptilization of the company. The
loss was the second-largest ever for a U.S. bank after Citicorp's
$2.5 billion loss in the second quarter 1987.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. loaned First RepublicBank $1
billion during the quarter to boost depositors' confidence in the
institution. The FDIC's long-term plan could cost an estimated $2
billion to $4 billion.
</TEXT>
