<HEAD>Wheat Futures Fall While Other Grains Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures closed substantially lower Monday
on the Chicago Board of Trade while corn finished higher and
soybean prices closed mixed.
   Analysts tied the lower wheat prices to weekend rains and the
higher corn prices to a lack thereof.
   ``Most of the Plains did manage to get rains over the weekend
but it didn't get any further,'' said Dale Gustafson, an analyst in
Chicago with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   ``It really didn't get into the eastern edges of Kansas and
Nebraska, where there's some dryness,'' he said.
   Corn also was supported by a favorable export outlook, he said.
   Soybeans for May delivery traded as high as $6.98 a bushel
during the session but prices fell on late profit-taking, Gustafson
said.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 6\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.01 a bushel; corn was 1} cents
to 3 cents higher with May at $2.05\ a bushel; oats were 1 cent
lower to \ cent higher with May at $1.58{ a bushel; soybeans were 3
cents lower to 1{ cents higher with May at $6.90 a bushel.
