<2ND_LINE>AM-Allegis,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allegis Sells Share In Apollo Reservations System for $500 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegis Corp., the parent company of United
Airlines, said Monday it will sell a 50 percent share in its Apollo
computer reservations system for $500 million to USAir and four
European airlines.
   Under terms of the agreement, pending review by the U.S.
Department of Transportation, the Apollo system will be owned and
operated by a joint venture, known as Covia Partnership, formed by
Covia Corp. and Alitalia, British Airways, KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines, Swissair and USAir.
   Covia Corp., which is fully owned by United Airlines, will
retain a 50 percent share in the new venture and be the managing
general partner, the company said. Barry Kotar, Covia's president
and chief executive officer, will fill the same roles in the new
partnership.
   Covia Partnership, based in Rosemont, Ill., will operate
United's computer reservations system, its telecommunications
network and provide various data processing services. It will own
the Apollo software, databases and computer center in Denver.
