<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1756EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-LTV     05-02 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-LTV,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LTV's Profit Up 12.7 Percent in First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Corp. reported its profit rose 12.7 percent in
the first quarter from a year earlier, boosted by gains from the
company's reorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy
laws.
   The diversified steel and aerospace giant said Monday that its
first-quarter profit increased to $163.9 million, or $1.16 a share,
from $129.6 million, or $1 a share, in the first three months of
1987.
   The figure for the latest quarter includes a one-time special
credit of $24.8 million resulting from the sale of two iron ore
vessels.
   The rise in net income occurred despite a decline in
first-quarter sales, to $1.88 billion from $1.91 billion a year
earlier.
   ``The deferral of interest, pension and other costs while we are
operating under the protection of Chapter 11 has greatly benefited
both periods,'' said Raymond A. Hay, LTV's chairman and chief
executive officer. The company entered Chapter 11 protection from
creditors in July 1986.
   Hay noted, however, that the deferrals of costs and expenses
have resulted in claims which must be provided for in a plan of
reorganization before LTV can emerge from bankruptcy.
   In January 1987, the federal Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp.
terminated and took control of the three pension plans of
subsidiary LTV Steel Co., assuming financial responsibility for
$2.3 billion in unfunded liabilities.
   But in September, the pension agency returned trusteeship of the
plans to LTV, saying it took the step to curb abuse of the federal
pension insurance program. It cited $252 million in profits the
company reported for the first half of 1987 and LTV's establishment
of a new pension arrangement for its workers.
   LTV has said it believes the agency's attempt to return
trusteeship of the pension plans is illegal.
   Excluding the special credit for the sale of the vessels, the
company said its operating income for the quarter rose to $151
million from $139.7 million a year earlier because of higher income
from steel.
   Operating income from steel rose to $131.2 million from $101.1
million in the first quarter of 1987, while steel sales expanded to
$1.3 billion from $1.2 billion.
   Income from LTV's aircraft products division dropped to $11.3
million from $22.2 million, largely because of reduced activity
following completion of the B-1B bomber program in the fourth
quarter of 1987.
   Income from the energy products division rose to $2.6 million
from $900,000 in the first three months of 1987.
</TEXT>
