<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MagazineBuyout     05-02 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Magazine Buyout,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Management Group Says It Has Agreed To Buy Ms., Sassy Magazines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Managers of Fairfax Publications (U.S.) said
Monday they have agreed to buy Ms. and Sassy magazines from the
company's Australian parent for an undisclosed price.
   Sandra Yates, president and chief executive of the newly formed
Matilda Publications Inc., and Anne Summers, Matilda's vice
president, said they expected to close the deal on May 20.
   Yates said no changes were planned at either monthly magazine.
   John Fairfax Ltd., based in Sydney, Australia, acquired Ms.
magazine last September. Unconfirmed reports had placed the
purchase price at between $10 million and $15 million.
   Sassy, a new magazine aimed at teen-age girls, was launched in
March. Yates had previously estimated startup costs at $10 million.
   Fairfax was taken private in December, and Yates said the
company decided to sell the magazines to pay off some of its debts.
   Yates said she and Summers held an option to purchase the
magazines, and they decided to exercise it after arranging
financing from an unidentified venture capital group and the New
York office of State Bank of New South Wales.
   ``This financial deal provides us with the best opportunity for
the growth of Ms. and Sassy, while maintaining their
independence,'' she said.
   She said the ``working capital we have been able to secure is
equivalent to what Fairfax would have invested had their plans
remained intact.''
   Ms., which was founded 16 years ago by Gloria Steinem and Pat
Carbine, has recently increased its rate base to 500,000 copies a
month from 450,000.
   No circulation figures have been released for Sassy, but Yates
said the magazine has ``well and truly made its rate base of
250,000.''
   She said other parties had inquired about the magazines, but she
was unaware of any other firm bids for the two publications, which
were put up for sale in the middle of March.
</TEXT>
