<DOCNO> AP880502-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1635EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Trade Bjt   05-02 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Trade, Bjt,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Surplus Falls 7.2 Percent In Fiscal Year 1987</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surge in imports caused Japan's merchandise trade
surplus to fall 7.2 percent to $94.3 billion in the 1987 fiscal
year, the Finance Ministry announced Monday.
   The report confirmed the continuing strength of Japan's economy
in spite of the strong Japanese yen, which hurts the
competitiveness of Japanese products in domestic and overseas
markets.
   Exports grew 10.5 percent to $233.4 billion, but imports grew
even faster, rising 26.9 percent to $139.1 billion. Both figures,
measured on a balance-of-payments basis, were records.
   The report did not provide a breakdown of where Japan's imports
were coming from. But other recent figures have shown that the
biggest growth is from the newly industrialized countries of Hong
Kong, Taiwan, South Korea and Singapore.
   Growth of imports from the United States has been sluggish.
   The trade surplus of $94.28 billion in the fiscal year ended
March 31, although smaller than the 1986 surplus of $101.65
billion, was the second highest on record.
   The report demonstrated that Japan is still able to increase its
exports at a double-digit pace in spite of the drag of the strong
yen. At the same time, Japan's burgeoning consumer economy is
sucking in more imports.
   Imports have also risen because Japanese exporters are getting
more of their components from abroad.
   Finance Ministry officials noted that the composition of
Japanese imports has shifted, with a larger share now consisting of
manufactured goods rather than raw materials.
   Government programs aimed at reducing trade friction by limiting
the economy's reliance on exports and encouraging domestic demand
played a role in cutting the trade surplus.
   ``Although the higher value of the Japanese yen had an effect,
the main cause of the fall in the trade surplus is the government's
program to boost imports,'' the official said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``These statistics show that the government's effort to change
the country's industrial structure and reduce our dependence on
exports has been successful,'' another ministry official said, also
speaking anonymously.
   The country's current account surplus also plunged almost $10
billion during the fiscal year for its first decline in six years,
the ministry said.
   The current account includes capital transfers and trade in
goods and services to measure a nation's commerce. The ministry
said the current account surplus registered $84.54 billion in
fiscal 1987, down from $94.14 billion the previous year.
   Japan's merchandise trade, measured on a balance-of-payments
basis, does not include freight or insurance charges on either
imports or exports. Another commonly used trade measure, the
customs-clearance basis, includes freight and insurance charges on
imports. That boosts the value of imports and makes the trade
deficit smaller.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880502-0292 </DOCNO>
