<1ST_LINE>r f AM_Japan-Beef     05-02 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM_Japan-Beef,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Continue Without Announced Result</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Japan-Trade, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Japan continued
high-level negotiations Monday in their dispute over increasing the
sale of American beef and oranges in Japan.
   Neither side would disclose whether or how much progress was
made in the round of talks Japanese Agriculture Minister Takashi
Sato started last Wednesday with U.S. Trade Representative Clayton
Yeutter.
   The two cabinet-level officials met both Monday morning and
afternoon and tentatively scheduled another session for Tuesday,
sources said.
   U.S. officials would say only they continued to insist on
removal of Japanese import quotas the two countries agreed to in a
1984 accord that expired last month. Otherwise, the issue will be
pursued before GATT, General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs, at its
meeting Wednesday in Geneva, they said.
   Japanese officials said a major issue was ``timing'' of the
removal. They declined to confirm Tokyo news reports of various
Japanese proposals for a three- or five-year interval before full
lifting of the barriers.
   Japan is the major customer for U.S. farm products but its
domestic livestock and citrus producers have insisted on the quotas
on imports of beef, oranges and orange juices as vital to their
livelihood. U.S. exporters have argued that as a result Japanese
consumers are paying more than double the fair price for beef and
oranges.
</TEXT>
