<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OfficeVacancies     05-02 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Office Vacancies,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Office Vacancy Rises in First Quarter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release after 6:30 p.m. EDT, time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continuing uncertainty about the health of the
economy supressed demand for office space in the nation's central
business districts during the first quarter, according to a study
released Monday.
   The national real estate firm Cushman & Wakefield Inc. said
office vacancy rates jumped to 15.1 percent during the quarter from
13.8 percent in the previous quarter in the nearly 50 markets it
reviewed.
   ``The uncertainty plaguing the financial markets and the
economy's performance over the past eight months are beginning to
affect the country's major real estate markets,'' said Cushman
President and Chief Executive Officer Arthur J. Mirante II.
   Austin, Texas had the most vacant downtown space with a vacancy
rate of 34.7 percent during the first quarter, up from 33.4
percent, although other oil-dependent cities showed some
improvement from the previous quarter.
   San Jose, Calif., had the second-highest vacancy rate of 28.8
percent, followed by Memphis, 28.1 percent; Denver, 26.9 percent;
Miami, 26.8 percent; Orange County, Calif., 26.4 percent; West Palm
Beach, Fla., 25.8 percent; Houston, 25.5 percent and Dallas, 25
percent.
   Among the cities with the lowest vacancy rates, Hartford, Conn.
led the nation with a vacancy rate of 8.1 percent. Hartford was
followed by Detroit, 8.9 percent; Charlotte, N.C., 10 percent;
Boston, 10.5 percent; Seattle, 10.7 percent; Washington, 10.8
percent; Philadelphia, 10.9 percent; Jacksonville, Fla., 11
percent; Chicago, 12.1 percent and Greensboro, N.C., 12.5 percent.
   A significant decrease in new construction helped vacancies in
suburban markets ease slightly to 21.9 percent from 22.2 percent in
the previous quarter.
   Cushman & Wakefield predicted that office vacancy rates in
central business districts would peak during the current quarter if
economic conditions remain stable, and then resume a downward trend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
