<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankBid 1stLd-Writethru   05-02 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid, 1st Ld-Writethru,0775</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Bank Seeks More Irving Shares</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 9th graf to UPDATE with closing stock price.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's second-largest bank said Monday it was
seeking to acquire a majority stake in Irving Bank Corp., but
analysts said swaying shareholders away from Bank of New York Co.'s
competing hostile bid remains an uphill battle.
   Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, which had sought a 45 percent
stake in Irving, said it will seek to purchase 9.5 million Irving
shares, or about 51 percent of the New York-based bank.
   The state-run Italian bank is offering $75 a share, the same
price as under its previous plan that sought to purchase 8.5
million shares. In addition, Banca Commerciale said it would pay
intererst on the per-share purchase price from May 31 until the
deal closes.
   Banca Commerciale also said it ``continues to contemplate''
paying Irving shareholders a special $10-a-share dividend on
remaining shares if it is successful in acquiring the bank.
   Irving's board approved the amended offer and recommended
shareholders tender to it, but analysts were less enthusiastic.
   ``I don't think most investors will bother studying it,'' said
Virginia Adair, an analyst at Merrill Lynch & Co. ``I think it will
be treated as fairly insignificant.''
   Irving said the offer, which hinges on a complex restructuring,
has a blended value of between $65.20 and $72.55 a share, a slight
increase over its previous offer.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said his company would not
increase its bid, adding that ``the stock market has chosen to
ignore BCI's proposal.''
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Irving rose
12{ cents to close at $61.62{ a share; Bank of New York rose 12{
cents to close at $30.50 a share.
   Bank of New York, which holds a 5 percent stake in Irving, is
offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its stock for each of
Irving's 18.5 million shares outstanding, or about $1.08 billion.
   The bank also is waging a proxy fight by running a slate of 16
candidates for election to Irving's board at a shareholders meeting
scheduled for May 6.
   As of last Friday, about 10 million Irving shares had been
tendered under Bank of New York's buyout offer of roughly $64 a
share. Those shares, coupled with the 888,634 shares Bank of New
York already owns, give the bank a 59.2 percent stake in Irving,
the company said.
   The tender offer was extended Monday for a fourth time; it will
expire at noon EDT Friday.
   Separately, Banca Commerciale said Italy's central bank has
indicated it has no objection to Banca Commerciale's purchase of a
controlling interest in Irving. But the Bank of Italy's support did
little to quell analysts' more serious concerns over domestic
regulatory approval.
   Because the ownership structure of the Italian bank is part
industrial and part government, analysts believe approval from the
Federal Reserve could be hard to come by.
   A Banca Commerciale-Irving combination ``would violate our
domestic laws on bank holding companies,'' Adair said.
   Some observers suggested that Banca Commerciale's willingness to
pay interest on its payout to shareholders is an admission that the
deal could run into regulatory snags.
   ``The interest gives some protection about a prolonged approval
process while shareholders are waiting for the Fed to make up its
mind,'' said Stephen Berman, an analyst with County Securities USA.
   ``To some extent it's kind of a recognition of the potential
tie-up of share for a long time,'' he added.
   Bank of New York received conditional approval from the Fed and
the New York State Banking boards in March, and began its tender
offer shortly after.
   Banca Commerciale's stock purchase is part of a complex
restructuring proposed by Irving that includes several cost-cutting
measures and asset sales.
   To that end, Irving said it will sell its 39 percent equity
interest in Banca della Svizzera Italiana to the Swiss-based
financial firm Unigestion SA for $390 million in cash. Irving
estimates a pre-tax gain of $136 million, or $5 per share, from the
transaction.
   The bank also said it would sell its 50-story building at One
Wall Street. Both transactions are expected to fund the special $10
dividend payout.
   Irving Chairman Joseph Rice said in a statement that the bank's
board ``greatly appreciates the willingness of BCI to improve its
offer.'' If the deal were consumated, Banca Commerciale would have
the right to buy an additional 10 percent of Irving stock on the
open market.
</TEXT>
