<2ND_LINE>AM-Bear Stearns,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bear Stearns Names New Vice Chairman, President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bear Stearns Cos. Inc. announced Monday that its
executive committee had elected E. John Rosenwald, Jr. vice
chairman and James E. Cayne president.
   Bear Stearns, a publicly traded financial company, is the parent
of Bear, Stearns & Co. Inc., a major investment and brokerage firm.
   Both positions, which are new, will apply to both the parent
company and the brokerage subsidiary.
   Both men will continue as members of the board of directors and
executive committee of the parent and as senior managing directors
of Bear, Stearns & Co. Rosenwald and Cayne have been members of the
office of the president since October 1985 when Bear Stearns became
a public company, but that office has been eliminated.
   Rosenwald, 58, has headed the company's corporate finance
department since 1976 and is the senior investment banker in the
department. He joined Bear Stearns in 1954, first as a research
analyst and later in its international department.
   Rosenwald headed institutional sales for 20 years before moving
to corporate finance. He became a general partner of Bear Stearns
in 1962.
   Cayne, 54, is manager of the company's U.S. branch system and is
responsible for individual investor sales. He started at Bear
Stearns in 1969 as a salesman for individual investors and became a
general partner in 1973, building the retail business into a major
division.
   The chairman and chief executive officer of Bear Stearns
Companies is Alan C. Greenberg; the executive vice president and
chief operating officer is Alvin H. Einbender.
</TEXT>
