<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AutoPrices     05-02 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Prices,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Price of Most Nissans Goes Up Average of 1.5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Corp. in U.S.A. said Monday it was
raising the price on most Nissan passenger cars and trucks an
average 1.5 percent.
   The increase, which is effective immediately, averages about
$167 per vehicle, said Thomas D. Mignanelli, executive vice
president of operations for the Carson, Calif.-based U.S. sales and
distribution arm of Japan's Nissan Motor Co. Ltd.
   The company said the increase is the result of the continued
strength of the yen against the dollar.
   Prices for all four-door Sentra models, the Maxima GXE wagon,
the Pulsar SE and Pulsar SportBak SE, are unaffected by the
increase, said Bob Thomas, a spokesman for Nissan.
   Prices for other Sentra models, Maxima sedans, and models
belonging to the Stanza, Pathfinder, pickup truck, 200SX and 300ZX
lines are affected, Thomas said.
</TEXT>
