<1ST_LINE>r f AM-InsiderTradingCharge     05-02 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insider Trading Charge,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Executive Recruiter Accused of Insider Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission on
Monday accused a Massachusetts man of violating insider trading
regulations by making stock profits based on information he learned
in his job as head of a corporate recruiting firm.
   The SEC civil complaint accused Michael O. Ingoldsby of making
$14,000 in profit in trading shares of stock in Artel
Communications Corp., a fiber optics company with headquarters in
Hudson, Mass.
   The SEC charged that Ingoldsby, the head of an executive search
firm located in Wellesley, Mass., was hired by Artel in September
1986 to find a new chief executive for the company.
   Ingoldsby allegedly purchased 23,500 shares of Artel stock after
learning that Robert L. Bowman, an executive he had recruited to
head Artel, was about to accept the top post at the company.
   The SEC complaint, which was filed in federal court in Boston,
seeks an injunction barring Ingoldsby from violating
insider-trading regulations in the future and seeks fines equal to
the $14,000 he allegedly made in profit in trading Artel stock.
   Ingoldsby, the head of Michael O. Ingoldsby Associations Inc.,
did not return phone calls asking for comment on the SEC charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
