<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 2215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WPPSSSettlement     05-02 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WPPSS Settlement,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Utilities Group Settles With Bondholders In WPPSS Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-four small utilities and cities in six
Western states reached a $25.8 million settlement Monday with
bondholders who sued them following Washington Public Power Supply
System's default on bonds sold to construct two nuclear power
plants.
   Jack Lowery, lead counsel for the group, confirmed the
agreement, the latest in a series of settlements totaling about
$203 million involving defendant utilities, bond underwriters and
legal firms.
   Lowery said the 24 utilities, in Washington, Oregon, Idaho,
Montana, Wyoming and Nevada, owned a combined interest of 6.5
percent in the two terminated plants, WPPSS No. 4 on the Hanford
nuclear reservation and No. 5 at Satsop, west of Olympia.
   Lowery said most of the $25.8 million would come from insurance
coverage, although some of the utilities would have to pay out of
their own pockets.
   While maintaining they did no wrong, by settling the utilities
saved legal expenses from a case that could take years to resolve
and avoided the possibility of losing their case in a jury trial,
he said.
   The giant case stemming from the WPPSS bond default, the biggest
in municipal bond market history, is to go to trial Sept. 7 in U.S.
District Court before Judge William Browning in Tucson, Ariz.
Dozens of individual cases were combined in the federal action.
   Eighty-eight utilities agreed to build the two WPPSS plants
during the 1970s, but the plants were abandoned in 1982 after cost
overruns and an assessment that the power from the plants would not
be needed.
   The settlement Monday came on the eve of three days of hearings
in federal court in Seattle before Judge Browning in the WPPSS case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
