<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AEA-China     05-02 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AEA-China,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AEA Establishes Liaison With China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Electronics Association,
which represents the $360 billion U.S. electronics industry, has
opened a liaison office in China, the trade group announced Monday.
   The AEA made the announcement in conjunction with an opening
ceremoney in Beijing, attended by more than 100 Chinese and
American dignitaries.
   AEA officials are in Beijing for three days of meetings with
leaders of ministries, the State Council and key commissions of
China, the group said in a statement.
   ``The liaison will assist U.S. firms interested in doing
business with the PRC electronics sector by providing policy and
technical information, on-site market support and U.S. perspective
on Chinese technology and trade policies,'' said Ralph Thomson,
AEA's senior vice president for public affairs, who will supervise
the venture.
   The establishment of the AEA liaison follows two years of
discussion by leaders of both country's electronics industries.
   Santa Clara-based AEA has more than 3,500 member high-technology
companies in the United States. The group also has an office in
Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
