<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 2338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GouldRepurchase     05-02 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gould Repurchase,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gould Sells Unit To German Company; Plans 20 Percent Stock Buyback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gould Inc. said Monday it had agreed to sell its
Industrial Automation Systems Group to a West German company and
would use the proceeds in a program to repurchase up to 20 percent
of its outstanding common stock.
   The computer and electronics company, based in suburban Rolling
Meadows, said it had agreed to sell the automation systems group to
AEG AG, a Daimler-Benz Group member. Completion of the sale was
expected in the next 90 days.
   Gould said it expected the sale to raise $290 million cash,
which would be used for the stock repurchase program authorized by
the board of directors.
   Gould expects to repurchase up to 20 percent of its 45.2 million
outstanding common shares from time to time in the open market or
privately negotiated puchases, or through other means over the next
12 months as directed by market conditions.
   Gould stock closed Monday at $11.50, up 37{ cents.
   ``The plan which we are implementing today reflects the
company's longstanding desire to enhance shareholder value,'' said
James F. McDonald, Gould chairman and chief executive officer.
   Following the sale of the automation systems group, Gould will
have annual revenue exceeding $750 million and a work force of
about 8,500 people in 29 locations worldwide.
   AEG is a leading electrical and electronic engineering group
based in Frankfurt, West Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
